'''Christina María Aguilera''' ({{IPAc-en|æ|ɡ|ɪ|ˈ|l|ɛər|ə}}; {{IPA-es|aɣiˈleɾa|lang}};<ref>{{cite AV media|people=W Magazine|date=May 16, 2018|title=Christina Aguilera Breaks Down Her Most Iconic Music Video Looks|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=doXqDkzFEkQ |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/varchive/youtube/20211211/doXqDkzFEkQ| archive-date=2021-12-11 |url-status=live|time=0:01}}{{cbignore}}</ref> born December 18, 1980) is an American singer, songwriter, actress, and television personality.<!--Only the most notable occupations associated with her, other less notable occupations should be listed in the infobox. --> Known for her four-octave [[vocal range]] and ability to sustain high notes,<ref name="ClassicFM"/> she has been referred to as the "[[Honorific nicknames in popular music|Voice of a Generation]]".<ref name="VOAG">{{cite web|author=Paul Grein|date=1 December 2021|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/awards/2021-peoples-choice-awards-christina-aguilera-music-icon-award-1235004745/|title=Christina Aguilera to Get Music Icon at 2021 People's Choice Awards|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=3 January 2022}}</ref><ref name="VOAG1">{{cite web|author=Melissa Maerz|date=3 August 2020|url=https://ew.com/recap/the-voice-season-3-episode-1-premiere/|title=The Voice Season Premiere Recap: Week One of Auditions|publisher=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|access-date=3 January 2022}}</ref> Aguilera rose to stardom with her [[Christina Aguilera (album)|eponymous debut album]], for which she is credited for influencing the revival of [[teen pop]] during the late 1990s and early 2000s. Her works, which incorporate feminism, sexuality, and domestic violence, have generated both critical praise and controversy, for which she is often cited as an influence by other artists.

After appearing in television programs, Aguilera signed with [[RCA Records]] in 1998. Her debut album spawned three [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] number-one singles — "[[Genie in a Bottle]]", "[[What a Girl Wants (Christina Aguilera song)|What a Girl Wants]]" and "[[Come On Over Baby (All I Want Is You)]]" — and earned her the [[Grammy Award for Best New Artist]]. Established as a [[bubblegum pop]] artist, she released her first Spanish record, ''[[Mi Reflejo]]'' (2000), which topped the [[Billboard Top Latin Albums|''Billboard'' Top Latin Albums]] for [[Billboard Top Latin Albums#Top 20 Albums with Most Weeks at Number-One|nineteen consecutive weeks]]. Aguilera assumed artistic control of her fourth studio album ''[[Stripped (Christina Aguilera album)|Stripped]]'' (2002). In the music video for its song "[[Dirrty]]", she sparked controversy for exploring her sexuality, leading to the departure of her [[teen idol]] image. However, further singles "[[Beautiful (Christina Aguilera song)|Beautiful]]", "[[Fighter (Christina Aguilera song)|Fighter]]" and "[[Can't Hold Us Down]]" became top-ten singles in many countries, and she was named the most successful female artist of 2003.

Her fifth album, ''[[Back to Basics (Christina Aguilera album)|Back to Basics]]'' (2006), was met with favorable reviews and became the second of her career to debut atop of the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]]. Its singles "[[Ain't No Other Man]]" and "[[Hurt (Christina Aguilera song)|Hurt]]" reached the top-ten positions in most countries. In 2010, Aguilera starred in ''[[Burlesque (2010 American film)|Burlesque]]'' and contributed to [[Burlesque (soundtrack)|its soundtrack]]. In subsequent years, she featured on the successful singles "[[Feel This Moment]]", "[[Say Something (A Great Big World song)|Say Something]]", and "[[Moves Like Jagger]]". The latter reached number one on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 making Aguilera one of the few artists to reach the top spot over three decades. Outside of her music, she was named a spokesperson for the [[World Food Program]] (WFP), served as a coach on [[reality competition]] show ''[[The Voice (American TV series)|The Voice]]'' (2011–2016), and acted in the drama series ''[[Nashville (2012 TV series)|Nashville]]'' (2015). In 2019, she headlined [[Christina Aguilera: The Xperience]], her first residency show at the [[Planet Hollywood Las Vegas]].

Aguilera is considered a [[pop icon|pop culture icon]] and is generally described as a [[triple threat (entertainer)|triple threat entertainer]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Madeline Roth|date=1 September 2015|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2258171/christina-aguilera-online-singing-class/|title=11 Things Christina Aguilera Needs to Teach Us in Her New Online Singing Class|publisher=[[MTV]]|access-date=3 January 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Jake Thompson|date=5 December 2021|url=https://www.eonline.com/news/1310796/christina-aguileras-best-red-carpet-looks-ever-are-truly-iconic|title=Christina Aguilera's Best Red Carpet Looks Ever Are Truly Iconic|publisher=[[E! News]]|access-date=3 January 2022}}</ref> With estimated sales over 90 million records, she is recognized as one of the world's [[List of best-selling music artists|best-selling music artists]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tv.apple.com/gb/person/christina-aguilera/umc.cpc.45clmilwx42d87lvkahr3rnaw|title=Christina Aguilera|publisher=[[Apple TV]]|access-date=26 July 2022}}</ref> In 2009, she was classified as the twentieth most successful artist of the 2000s by ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''. Throughout her career, she has accumulated numerous [[List of awards and nominations received by Christina Aguilera|awards and accolades]], including five [[Grammy Awards]], one [[Latin Grammy Award]], two [[MTV Video Music Awards]] (VMA), one [[Billboard Music Awards|''Billboard'' Music Awards]], one [[Guinness World Record]], a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]], and was named a [[Disney Legend]]. Aguilera is regarded as one of the most influential Latin artists in the [[show business|entertainment industry]];<ref name="ProeminentLatin"/><ref name="Influyentes"/> in 2013, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' listed her among the [[Time 100|100 most influential people in the world]], and was ranked as the eighth [[The Greatest (TV series)|greatest woman in music]] by [[VH1]]. Furthermore, she has been cited as one of the greatest singers in contemporary pop music, ranked among the greatest of all time by magazines such as ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' and ''[[Consequence of Sound]]''.

==Life and career==
===1980–1998: Early life and career beginnings===
Christina María Aguilera was born in [[Staten Island]], [[New York City]] on December 18, 1980, the eldest of two daughters to musician Shelly Loraine Kearns ([[née]] Fidler) and [[United States Army]] soldier Fausto Xavier Aguilera.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wang|first1=Julia|title=Christina Aguilera Biography|url=http://www.people.com/people/christina_aguilera/biography/|website=[[People (magazine)|People]]|access-date=September 28, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140331213217/https://people.com/people/christina_aguilera/biography/|archive-date=March 31, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> Her father was born in [[Ecuador]], and her mother has German, Irish, Welsh, and Dutch ancestry.{{sfn|Dominguez|2003|p=2}}<ref name="Early life">{{cite journal|last1=Gregory|first1=Sophfronia Scott|last2=Ferguson|first2=Hayes|title=Uncorking the Genie|journal=People|date=September 27, 1999|volume=52|issue=12|pages=75–76|url=https://people.com/archive/uncorking-the-genie-vol-52-no-12/|access-date=January 21, 2022|issn=0093-7673}}</ref> The family moved frequently because of his military service, and lived in places including New Jersey, Texas, New York, and Japan.<ref name="FastTrack">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/WPcap/2000-02/13/003r-021300-idx.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180621070136/https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/WPcap/2000-02/13/003r-021300-idx.html|title=Christina Aguilera's Fast Track|last=Harrington|first=Richard|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|date=February 13, 2000|archive-date=June 21, 2018|url-status=dead|access-date=August 25, 2017}}</ref> Aguilera said he was physically and emotionally abusive.<ref name="OldSoul"/> She used music to escape her turbulent household.<ref name="WMagazine"/> Following her parents' divorce when she was six years old, Aguilera, her younger sister Rachel, and her mother moved into her grandmother's home in [[Rochester, Pennsylvania|Rochester]], a suburb in the [[Pittsburgh]] area.<ref name="Early life"/> Her mother later remarried to Jim Kearns and had a son with him named Michael.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/christina-aguilera/bio/199304/|title=Christina Aguilera Biography, Celebrity Facts and Awards |magazine=[[TV Guide]]|access-date=May 20, 2020}}</ref> After years of estrangement, Aguilera expressed interest in reconciling with her father in 2012.<ref>{{cite web |last=Chen |first=Joyce |title=Christina Aguilera wants to reconcile with estranged father, would be open to 'doing lunch' |url=https://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/gossip/christina-aguilera-reconcile-estranged-father-open-lunch-article-1.1020009 |website=New York Daily News |access-date=January 21, 2022 |date=February 10, 2012}}</ref>

As a child, she was drawn to [[soul music|soul]] and [[blues]] records her grandmother bought and would practice singing, which earned her a reputation as "the little girl with the big voice" in her neighborhood.<ref name="newsweek">{{cite web|url=http://www.newsweek.com/christina-aguilera-comes-age-112341|title=Christina Aguilera Comes of Age|last=Ali|first=Lorraine|date=July 30, 2006|work=[[Newsweek]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180120135330/http://www.newsweek.com/christina-aguilera-comes-age-112379|archive-date=January 20, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> Aguilera aspired to be a singer, and won her first talent show at age eight with a rendition of [[Whitney Houston]]'s "[[I Wanna Dance with Somebody (Who Loves Me)]]".<ref name="FastTrack"/> At age 10, she performed "[[A Sunday Kind of Love]]" on the competition show ''[[Star Search]]'', and was eliminated during the semi-final round.<ref name="WMagazine">{{cite web|url=https://www.wmagazine.com/story/christina-aguilera-cover-story|title=From the Vaults: The Fall & Rise of Christina Aguilera|last=Hirschberg|first=Lynn|magazine=[[W (magazine)|W]]|date=July 2011|access-date=January 21, 2022|archive-date=October 21, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141021034600/http://www.wmagazine.com/people/celebrities/2011/07/christina-aguilera-cover-story/|url-status=dead}}</ref> She performed the song again on [[KDKA-TV]]'s ''Wake Up with Larry Richert''.{{sfn|Kimpel|2006|p=2}} During her youth in the Pittsburgh area, Aguilera sang "[[The Star-Spangled Banner]]" before [[Pittsburgh Penguins]] hockey, [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] football, and [[Pittsburgh Pirates]] baseball games, and the [[1992 Stanley Cup Finals]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.triblive.com/news/anthem-singer-fires-up-mellon-crowd/|title=Anthem singer fires up Mellon crowd|last=Grupp|first=John|newspaper=[[Pittsburgh Tribune-Review]]|date=May 6, 2009|access-date=January 21, 2022}}</ref> She attended [[Rochester Area School District]] in Rochester and Marshall Middle School near [[Wexford, Pennsylvania|Wexford]], and briefly attended [[North Allegheny Intermediate High School]] before being homeschooled to avoid being bullied.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ca.movies.yahoo.com/person/christina-aguilera/biography.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812193158/https://ca.movies.yahoo.com/person/christina-aguilera/biography.html|archive-date=August 12, 2014|title=Christina Aguilera Biography|publisher=[[Yahoo! Movies]]|access-date=July 29, 2014}}</ref>

In 1991, Aguilera auditioned for a position on the [[Disney Channel]]'s ''[[The Mickey Mouse Club#1990s revival, The All-New Mickey Mouse Club (MMC)|The Mickey Mouse Club]]'', though did not meet its age requirements. She joined the television series two years later, which featured her performing musical numbers and [[sketch comedy]] until its cancellation in 1994.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://music.yahoo.com/read/interview/12043048|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070401032341/http://music.yahoo.com/read/interview/12043048|title=Dreaming of Genie|last=Goldstein|first=Rob|publisher=[[Yahoo! Music]]|date=May 15, 1999|archive-date=April 1, 2007}}</ref> Fellow cast members included [[Ryan Gosling]], [[Keri Russell]], [[Britney Spears]], and [[Justin Timberlake]].<ref name="AguileraBiographyPeople">{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/christina_aguilera|title=Christina Aguilera Biography|magazine=People|access-date=December 8, 2010}}</ref> After the show ended, Aguilera moved to Japan and recorded her first song, "All I Wanna Do", a duet with Japanese singer [[Keizo Nakanishi]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://content.time.com/time/arts/article/0,8599,2044752,00.html|title=Christina Aguilera: Biography|date=September 15, 2001|magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|access-date=June 25, 2019|first=Kevork|last=Djansezian}}</ref> In 1998, Aguilera returned to the US to seek a recording contract. She approached [[RCA Records]], who told her to contact [[Walt Disney Records]] instead because they were having financial difficulties.{{sfn|Dominguez|2003|p=43}} She sent her [[cover version]] of Whitney Houston's "[[Run to You (Whitney Houston song)|Run to You]]" to Disney in hopes of being selected to record the theme song "[[Reflection (Mulan song)|Reflection]]" for their animated film ''[[Mulan (1998 film)|Mulan]]'' (1998).<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,84715,00.html|title=Club Kid|last=Willman|first=Chris|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=October 11, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150103052149/http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0%2C%2C84715%2C00.html|archive-date=January 3, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Aguilera was ultimately selected to sing "Reflection"; the song was released in June 1998 and charted on the [[Hot Adult Contemporary Tracks|''Billboard'' Adult Contemporary]] chart at number 15.{{sfn|Dominguez|2003|p=44}}

===1999–2001: ''Christina Aguilera'', ''Mi Reflejo'', and ''My Kind of Christmas''===
After "Reflection", Aguilera attracted the attention of RCA's A&R [[Ron Fair]] and was signed with the label quickly afterwards.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/the-christina-aguilera-story-so-far-241369/|title=The Christina Aguilera Story (So Far)|first=Anthony|last=Bozza|magazine=Rolling Stone|date=October 28, 1999|access-date=January 21, 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Smith|first=Andy|title=One talented teen|journal=[[The Providence Journal]]|date=August 15, 1998}}</ref> RCA was pressured by the contemporary [[teen pop]] craze evoked by Aguilera's peer Britney Spears, leading to the label rushing production of the album and aligning Aguilera to be part of the teen pop trend.{{sfn|Dominguez|2003|p=45}} They released the lead single from the album, "[[Genie in a Bottle]]", a trendy [[pop music|pop]] and [[contemporary R&B|R&B]] track, in June 1999.{{sfn|Dominguez|2003|p=45}} The single rose Aguilera to stardom, peaking atop the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] and charts of 20 other countries.<ref name="GeniePeak21">{{cite magazine|title=Portrait of an Artist: Christina Aguilera|magazine=Billboard|date=January 20, 2000|volume=112|issue=5|pages=6–7}}</ref> It has sold over seven million copies as of 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chartsinfrance.net/Christina-Aguilera/news-93194.html|title=L'histoire d'un tube : 'Genie in a Bottle' de Christina Aguilera fête ses 15 ans|publisher=Charts in France|language=fr|date=August 17, 2014|access-date=January 20, 2018}}</ref> Aguilera's [[Christina Aguilera (album)|eponymous debut album]] followed in August 1999 and peaked at number one on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]].<ref name="FastTrack"/> It was certified [[RIAA certification|eight times platinum]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA),<ref name="RIAA"/> and had moved 17 million copies worldwide by 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/rockandpopfeatures/7682705/Christina-Aguileras-eye-on-the-prize.html |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220110/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/rockandpopfeatures/7682705/Christina-Aguileras-eye-on-the-prize.html |archive-date=January 10, 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live|title=Christina Aguilera's 'eye on the prize'|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|access-date=August 26, 2017|first=Craig|last=McLean|date=May 7, 2010}}{{cbignore}}</ref> The album produced three other singles: two US number-one singles "[[What a Girl Wants (Christina Aguilera song)|What a Girl Wants]]" and "[[Come On Over Baby (All I Want Is You)]]", and one US top-five single "[[I Turn to You (All-4-One song)#Christina Aguilera version|I Turn to You]]", a cover of [[All-4-One]]'s song.<ref name="AguileraBBCharts">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/299251/Christina+Aguilera/chart?f=379|title=Chart history for Christina Aguilera|magazine=Billboard|access-date=June 20, 2014}}</ref> At the [[42nd Annual Grammy Awards]] in February 2000, Aguilera won [[Grammy Award for Best New Artist|Best New Artist]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://music.yahoo.com/read/story/12051721|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080528131603/http://music.yahoo.com/read/story/12051721|title=Christina Aguilera Wins Best New Artist|last=Rosen|first=Craig|publisher=Yahoo! Music|date=February 24, 2000|archive-date=May 28, 2008}}</ref>

Aguilera's two following studio albums, ''[[Mi Reflejo]]'' and ''[[My Kind of Christmas]]'', were released in September and October 2000, respectively.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Charts and retail notas|magazine=Billboard|volume=112|issue=45|page=47|date=November 4, 2000|first=Leila|last=Cobo}}</ref> The former, a Spanish-language album consisting of re-recorded versions of tracks on Aguilera's debut album and several original songs, topped the [[Billboard Top Latin Albums|''Billboard'' Top Latin Albums]] for 19 consecutive weeks and was certified six times platinum in the [[Latin music|Latin]] field by the RIAA.<ref name="RIAA">{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&se=Christina+Aguilera|title=Gold & Platinum – Christina Aguilera|publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of America]]|access-date=January 20, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140726142412/http://www.billboard.com/charts/2001-02-03/latin-albums|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/2001-02-03/latin-albums|title=Top Latin Albums: February 3, 2001|magazine=Billboard|date=January 2, 2013|archive-date=July 26, 2014}}</ref> It won [[Latin Grammy Award for Best Female Pop Vocal Album|Best Female Pop Vocal Album]] at the [[2nd Annual Latin Grammy Awards]] in 2001.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/christina-wins-latin-grammy-20011030|title=Christina Wins Latin Grammy|last=Saraceno|first=Christina|magazine=Rolling Stone|date=October 30, 2001|access-date=December 4, 2012|archive-date=September 26, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130926070045/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/christina-wins-latin-grammy-20011030|url-status=dead}}</ref> The latter contains covers of [[Christmas music|Christmas]] popular songs and a few original [[dance-pop]] tunes,{{sfn|Dominguez|2003|p=108}} and was certified platinum by the RIAA.<ref name="RIAA"/> In support of her albums, Aguilera embarked on her first concert tour, [[Christina Aguilera in Concert]], from mid-2000 to early 2001. The tour visited North America, Europe, South America, and Japan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1424807/aguilera-to-play-prom-in-augusta-georgia/|title=Aguilera To Play Prom In Augusta, Georgia|first=David|last=Basham|publisher=MTV News|date=August 21, 2000|access-date=July 6, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010330211536/http://www.christina-a.com/christinainjapan.html|url=http://www.christina-a.com/christinainjapan.html|title=Christina Aguilera Live in Japan|publisher=Christina Aguilera website|date=February 9, 2001|archive-date=March 30, 2001}}</ref> ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' in 2000 recognized Aguilera as the Top Female Pop Act of the Year.<ref name="YIM2000"/> Despite the successes, Aguilera was displeased with the music and image her manager Steve Kurtz had aligned her to, feeling unable to control her own image.<ref name="NotAPuppet"/> In October 2000, she filed a [[fiduciary duty]] lawsuit against Kurtz for improper, undue, and inappropriate influence over her professional activities. After terminating Kurtz's services, RCA hired [[Irving Azoff]] as Aguilera's new manager.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/story?id=114375&page=1|title=Aguilera's Ex-Manager Fires Back|work=ABC News|date=October 19, 2000|access-date=December 6, 2012}}</ref>

Aguilera took her first steps in artistic control with a cover of [[Labelle]]'s "[[Lady Marmalade]]" (1974) with [[Pink (singer)|Pink]], [[Mýa]], and [[Lil' Kim]] for the ''[[Moulin Rouge! Music from Baz Luhrmann's Film|Moulin Rouge!]]'' soundtrack.<ref name="newsweek"/> RCA executives initially opposed to Aguilera recording "Lady Marmalade" because it was "too [[urban music|urban]]", but Aguilera ultimately managed to record the song of her own accord.<ref name="NotAPuppet"/> The collaboration topped the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 for five weeks based on airplay alone, becoming the first airplay-only track in history to remain on the chart's top spot for more than one week.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/lady-marmalade-mw0000424595|title=Lady Marmalade – Song Review|website=AllMusic|first=Jose|last=Promis|access-date=January 20, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|title=Hot 100 Spotlight|magazine=Billboard|date=June 2, 2001|first=Silvio|last=Pietroluongo|page=123|volume=113|issue=22}}</ref> It won [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Collaboration with Vocals|Best Pop Collaboration with Vocals]] at the [[44th Annual Grammy Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfgate.com/news/article/The-2002-Grammy-winners-2868670.php|title=The 2002 Grammy winners|work=San Francisco Chronicle|date=February 28, 2002|access-date=July 7, 2014}}</ref> In mid-2001, [[Warlock Records]] released ''[[Just Be Free]]'', a compilation of [[demo (music)|demo]] tracks Aguilera recorded in 1994 and 1995, when she was looking forward to an album release after the end of ''The Mickey Mouse Club''. Aguilera filed a suit against Warlock Records and the album's producers to stop the release.{{sfn|Dominguez|2003|page=34}} The two parties came to a confidential settlement to release the album, in which Aguilera lent out her name, likeness, and image for an unspecified amount of damages.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jam.canoe.ca/Music/Artists/A/Aguilera_Christina/2001/07/03/pf-742790.html|title=Disputed Aguilera album to be released|last=McGrath|first=Stephanie|publisher=[[Jam!]]|date=July 3, 2001|access-date=May 25, 2007}}</ref>

===2002–2003: ''Stripped''===
[[File:Stripped Tour CH - cropped.jpg|thumb|upright|190px|left|Aguilera performing on [[The Stripped Tour]] in 2003]]
While working on her fourth studio album, Aguilera leaned toward a new artistic direction that she felt had more musical and lyrical depth.<ref name="USAToday">{{cite news|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/music/news/2002-10-23-christina-aguilera_x.htm|title=Aguilera's image is 'Stripped'|last=Gardner|first=Elysa|newspaper=USA Today|date=October 24, 2002|access-date=October 19, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160301144224/http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/music/news/2002-10-23-christina-aguilera_x.htm|archive-date=March 1, 2016}}</ref> She named the album ''[[Stripped (Christina Aguilera album)|Stripped]]'' and explained that the title represented "a new beginning, a re-introduction of [herself] as a new artist in a way".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1458433/christina-stands-up-for-the-ladies-discusses-fathers-abuse/|title=Christina Stands Up For The Ladies, Discusses Father's Abuse|first=Jennifer|last=Vineyard|publisher=MTV News|date=October 30, 2002|access-date=July 7, 2014}}</ref> Aguilera served as the album's [[executive producer]] and co-wrote most of the songs.<ref>{{cite AV media notes|title=[[Stripped (Christina Aguilera album)|Stripped]]|others=Christina Aguilera|year=2002|type=CD liner notes|publisher=[[RCA Records]]}}</ref><ref name="Nowhere"/> To present her new persona, Aguilera released "[[Dirrty]]" as the lead single from the album in September 2002.<ref name="RicherSound"/> Its accompanying music video generated controversy for depicting overtly [[sexual fetishism|sexual fetishes]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Edwards|first=Tanya L|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1458275/how-dirty-is-dirrty-x-posing-the-kinks-in-x-tinas-video/|title=How Dirty Is 'Dirrty'? X-posing The Kinks In X-tina's Video|publisher=MTV News|date=October 23, 2002|access-date=January 21, 2022}}</ref> Aguilera's new image presented in the video was widely criticized by the public that it began to overshadow her music.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Tryangiel|first=Josh|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1376243-1,00.html|title=Welcome to my Bubble|magazine=Time|date=August 27, 2006|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012211218/http://time.com/time/magazine/article/0%2C9171%2C1376243-1%2C00.html|archive-date=October 12, 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Dark|first=Jane|url=http://www.villagevoice.com/2002-11-12/music/siren-wailing/|title=Siren Wailing|work=[[The Village Voice]]|date=November 11, 2002|access-date=June 18, 2007|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041209030356/http://www.villagevoice.com/issues/0246/dark.php|archive-date=December 9, 2004}}</ref><ref name="blender">{{cite web|last=Duerden|first=Nick|url=http://www.blender.com/guide/67285/good-bad-dirrty.html|title=The Good, the Bad and the Dirrty|work=[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]|date=November 15, 2003|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090807060733/http://www.blender.com/guide/67285/good-bad-dirrty.html|archive-date=August 7, 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref> She defended her new image: "I'm in the power position, in complete command of everything and everybody around me. To be totally balls-out like that is, for me, the measure of a true artist."<ref name="blender"/>

''Stripped'' was released in October 2002.<ref name="MC">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/stripped/christina-aguilera/critic-reviews|title=Critic Reviews for Stripped|website=[[Metacritic]]|access-date=January 20, 2018}}</ref> The album incorporated various genres from R&B and [[flamenco]] to [[rock music|rock]], and lyrically revolves around the theme of self-esteem while also discussing sex and gender equality.<ref name="Nowhere"/><ref name="rs_Stripped"/> It received mixed reviews from music critics, who viewed the employment of various musical styles incoherent, but praised Aguilera's vocals.<ref name="MC"/><ref name="rs_Stripped">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/stripped-20021105|title=Stripped|magazine=Rolling Stone|first=Jancee|last=Dunn|author-link=Jancee Dunn|date=November 6, 2002|access-date=January 20, 2018|archive-date=September 21, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921182528/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/stripped-20021105|url-status=dead}}</ref> The album peaked at number two on the ''Billboard'' 200 and has sold over 4.3 million copies in the US as of 2014.<ref name="Shake">{{cite web|author=Gary Trust|date=1 September 2014|url=https://www.billboard.com/pro/ask-billboard-taylor-swift-out-shakes-mariah-carey/|title=Ask Billboard: Taylor Swift Out-'Shake's Mariah Carey|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=January 21, 2022}}</ref> In the UK, the album has sold two million copies as of 2017 and was the second highest-selling album by an American female artist during the 2000s decade, behind [[Norah Jones]] with ''[[Come Away with Me]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/official-charts-flashback-2002-christina-aguilera-reinvents-herself-with-dirrty-at-number-1__21081/|title=Official Charts Flashback 2002: Christina Aguilera reinvents herself with Dirrty at Number 1|date=November 23, 2017|access-date=January 20, 2018|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|first=Rob|last=Copsey}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media|date=December 28, 2009|title=Best-Selling of the Noughties|medium=radio news|publisher=[[BBC Radio 1]]/Official Charts Company}}</ref> By 2006, ''Stripped'' had sold over 12 million copies worldwide.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/scott-storchs-outrageous-fortune-51499/|title=Scott Storch's Outrageous Fortune|magazine=Rolling Stone|author=Touré|date=June 29, 2006|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080419055040/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/10699242/scott_storchs_outrageous_fortune/print|archive-date=April 19, 2008|access-date=January 21, 2022}}</ref> The second single from the album, the ballad "[[Beautiful (Christina Aguilera song)|Beautiful]]", received universal acclaim for its empowering lyrics about embracing inner beauty, and became an anthem for the [[LGBT community]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/song-stories/beautiful-christina-aguilera|title=Beautiful by Christina Aguilera|magazine=Rolling Stone|access-date=April 2, 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140327020233/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/song-stories/beautiful-christina-aguilera|archive-date=March 27, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title='Beautiful,' Damn It|work=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]|first=Larry|last=Flick|date=January 20, 2004|page=90|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=72QEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA90|issue=906}}</ref> It was the album's best-charting single, peaking at number two on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref name="AguileraBBCharts"/> The song won [[Grammy Award for Best Female Pop Vocal Performance|Best Female Pop Vocal Performance]] at the [[46th Annual Grammy Awards]] in 2004.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/02/09/arts/the-grammy-award-winners-of-2004.html|title=The Grammy Award Winners of 2004|work=The New York Times|date=February 9, 2004|access-date=October 20, 2013}}</ref>

''Stripped'' was followed by three other singles: "[[Fighter (Christina Aguilera song)|Fighter]]", "[[Can't Hold Us Down]]", and "[[The Voice Within]]", all of which were released in 2003 and entered the top 40 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref name="AguileraBBCharts"/> During promotion of ''Stripped'', Aguilera cultivated a new image by adopting the [[alter ego]] Xtina, dyeing her hair black, and debuting several tattoos and piercings.<ref name="CareerBiggest"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/christina_aguilera/0,,,00.html|title=Christina Aguilera: Five Fun Facts|work=People|access-date=October 19, 2013|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131022140434/http://www.people.com/people/christina_aguilera/0,,,00.html|archive-date=October 22, 2013}}</ref> She co-headlined the [[Justified and Stripped Tour]] alongside Justin Timberlake from June to September 2003 in support of ''Stripped'' and Timberlake's album ''[[Justified (album)|Justified]]'' (2002), before embarking on her solo [[The Stripped Tour|Stripped Tour]] until December.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/justin-timberlake-and-christina-aguilera-double-trouble-244042/|title=Justin Timberlake and Christina Aguilera: Double Trouble|first=Jancee|last=Dunn|magazine=Rolling Stone|date=June 26, 2003|access-date=January 21, 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.frontiertouring.com/index.php?action=retail&form_name=view_retail&merchant_id=595&sectionID=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120325202833/http://www.frontiertouring.com/index.php?action=retail&form_name=view_retail&merchant_id=595&sectionID=|title=Frontier Touring: The Stripped Tour|publisher=Frontier Touring|archive-date=March 25, 2012}}</ref> Aguilera attended the [[2003 MTV Video Music Awards]] in August, where she and Britney Spears kissed [[Madonna]] during their performance of "[[Like a Virgin (song)|Like a Virgin]]" and "[[Hollywood (Madonna song)|Hollywood]]", which received considerable media attention.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/madonna-magic-at-mtv-awards/|title=Madonna Magic At MTV Awards|last=Moody|first=Nekesa Mumbi|work=CBS News|date=August 29, 2003|access-date=February 22, 2013}}</ref> She hosted the [[2003 MTV Europe Music Awards]], where she won [[MTV Europe Music Award for Best Female|Best Female]] award, in November.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1480240/its-justins-night-as-christina-kelly-osbourne-fight-at-mtv-europe-awards/|title=It's Justin's Night As Christina, Kelly Osbourne Fight At MTV Europe Awards|first=Jon|last=Wiederhorn|publisher=MTV News|date=November 6, 2003|access-date=October 20, 2013}}</ref> ''Billboard'' announced Aguilera as the Top Female Pop Act of 2003.<ref name="YIM2003"/>

===2004–2009: Marriage, ''Back to Basics'', and first child===
[[File:Christina Aguilera Sanremo.jpg|thumb|upright|Aguilera performing at the [[Sanremo Music Festival]] in 2006]]
In 2004, Aguilera recorded a [[Car Wash (song)#Christina Aguilera and Missy Elliott version|revised version]] of [[Rose Royce]]'s "[[Car Wash (song)|Car Wash]]" (1976) with Missy Elliott for the animated film ''[[Shark Tale]]'', in which she was a voice actress,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1491393/christina-aguilera-is-poisonous-in-video-with-missy-elliott/|title=Christina Aguilera Is Poisonous In Video With Missy Elliott|first=Jennifer|last=Vineyard|publisher=MTV News|date=September 24, 2004|access-date=October 21, 2013}}</ref> and contributed vocals to [[Nelly]]'s single "[[Tilt Ya Head Back]]".<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Singles: Essential Reviews|first=Michael|last=Paoletta|magazine=Billboard|date=September 25, 2004|volume=116|issue=39|page=55}}</ref> She was a featured artist on [[Herbie Hancock]]'s 2005 cover of [[Leon Russell]]'s "[[A Song for You]]" (1970), which was nominated for Best Pop Collaboration with Vocals at the [[48th Annual Grammy Awards]] in February 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/entertainment/music/bal-grammys-winners0209-htmlstory.html|title=Complete list of 2006 Grammy winners|newspaper=The Baltimore Sun|date=February 9, 2006|access-date=July 7, 2014}}</ref> During this time, Aguilera started working on her follow-up studio album and embraced a new image inspired by figures of the [[Classic Hollywood cinema|Classic Hollywood era]] such as [[Marilyn Monroe]], [[Marlene Dietrich]], and [[Mary Pickford]], debuting blonde curly hair and retro-styled makeup.<ref name="EW2004">{{cite magazine|url=https://ew.com/article/2004/08/30/highlights-2004-mtv-video-music-awards/|title=Highlights of the 2004 MTV Video Music Awards|first=Brian|last=Hiatt|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=August 30, 2004|access-date=January 22, 2018}}</ref><ref name="HelloMag">{{cite web|url=http://www.hellomagazine.com/music/2004/10/20/christinaaguliera/|title=Christina turns Hollywood pin-up in latest shoot|work=Hello!|date=October 20, 2004|access-date=October 20, 2013}}</ref>

Aguilera became engaged to marketing executive Jordan Bratman, who had dated her since 2003, in February 2005.<ref name="Marries">{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,1131176,00.html|title=Christina Aguilera Marries|work=People|date=November 18, 2005|access-date=October 21, 2013}}</ref> They married on November 19, 2005, at an estate in [[Napa County, California]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/music/celebrity/christina-aguileras-highs-and-lows/ss-BBgQqMJ#image=9|title=Christina Aguilera's Highs and Lows|publisher=[[MSN]]|access-date=February 23, 2015}}</ref> Aguilera released the lead single, "[[Ain't No Other Man]]", from her fifth studio album, ''[[Back to Basics (Christina Aguilera album)|Back to Basics]]'', in June 2006.<ref name="mtvnews4">{{cite news|last=Vineyard|first=Jennifer|title='Ain't No Other Man' Video Has Christina Singing The Blues|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1534591/aint-no-other-man-video-has-christina-singing-the-blues/|access-date=January 21, 2022|publisher=MTV News|date=June 19, 2006}}</ref> The song, like the majority of the album, was inspired by Aguilera's marriage and incorporates elements of early 20th-century soul, blues, and [[jazz]].<ref name="mtvnews">{{cite news|last=Moss|first=Corey|title=Christina's New Split-Personality Album Is Mature And 'Dirrty'|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1529698/christinas-new-split-personality-album-is-mature-and-dirrty/|access-date=January 21, 2022|publisher=MTV News|date=April 28, 2006}}</ref><ref name="ewb2b">{{cite magazine|url=https://ew.com/article/2006/08/14/back-basics-3/|title=Back to Basics Review|first=Jody|last=Rosen|date=August 14, 2006|magazine=Entertainment Weekly|access-date=January 21, 2022}}</ref> It reached number six on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 and has sold 1.7 million digital copies in the US as of 2014.<ref name="AguileraBBCharts"/><ref name="Shake"/> Its music video saw Aguilera debuting her new alter ego, Baby Jane, inspired by the thriller film ''[[What Ever Happened to Baby Jane? (1962 film)|What Ever Happened to Baby Jane?]]'' (1962).<ref name="mtvnews4"/>

''Back to Basics'' was released in August 2006. Aguilera described the record, a [[double album]], as a "throwback" to jazz, blues, and soul music of the 1920s, 1930s, and 1940s that incorporates "a modern twist."<ref name="B2BMusic">{{cite web|first=Jeff|last=Cornell|date=6 June 2006|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1533622/christina-makes-her-comeback-twice-as-nice-by-expanding-basics-into-double-lp/|title=Christina Makes Her Comeback Twice As Nice By Expanding Basics Into Double LP|publisher=[[MTV News]]|access-date=24 June 2021}}</ref> She was much inspired by works of such classic blues and soul singers as [[Otis Redding]], [[Millie Jackson]], and [[Nina Simone]] during the recording sessions.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JhYEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA26|title=Old School|first=Melinda|last=Newman|magazine=Billboard|page=26|volume=118|issue=30|date=July 29, 2016|access-date=January 22, 2018}}</ref> ''Back to Basics'' received generally positive reviews from critics, who commented that the retro-oriented production complements Aguilera's vocals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/back-to-basics/christina-aguilera/critic-reviews|title=Critic Reviews for Back to Basics|website=Metacritic|access-date=January 22, 2018}}</ref> It debuted atop the ''Billboard'' 200 and has sold 1.7 million copies in the US.<ref name="Shake"/> At the [[49th Annual Grammy Awards]] in February 2007, Aguilera won Best Female Pop Vocal Performance for "Ain't No Other Man" and performed "[[It's a Man's Man's Man's World]]" as a tribute to the late [[James Brown]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2007/SHOWBIZ/Music/02/11/grammy.awards/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021075431/http://edition.cnn.com/2007/SHOWBIZ/Music/02/11/grammy.awards/|title=A 'Nice' night for the Dixie Chicks|first=Todd|last=Leopold|publisher=CNN|date=February 12, 2007|archive-date=October 21, 2012}}</ref> ''Back to Basics'' was succeeded by two international top-ten singles: "[[Hurt (Christina Aguilera song)|Hurt]]" and "[[Candyman (Christina Aguilera song)|Candyman]]". Two other singles, "[[Slow Down Baby]]" and "[[Oh Mother]]", were released exclusively in Australia<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sonybmg.com.au/news/details.do?newsId=20030829004728|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070904081540/http://sonybmg.com.au/news/details.do?newsId=20030829004728|title=Christina Aguilera Arrives In Town This Week!|publisher=Sony Music Australia|date=July 12, 2007|archive-date=September 4, 2007}}</ref> and Europe,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radioandrecords.com/formats/charts/euro/Switzerland.asp|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071013015718/http://www.radioandrecords.com/formats/charts/euro/Switzerland.asp|title=Radio & Records: Swiss Top 20 Chart|work=Radio & Records|date=September 21, 2007|archive-date=October 13, 2007}}</ref> respectively. In support of ''Back to Basics'', Aguilera embarked on the [[Back to Basics Tour]], which ran from November 2006 to October 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1540564/christina-aguilera-reveals-european-tour-next-up-us-clubs/|title=Christina Aguilera Reveals European Tour — Next Up, U.S. Clubs|first=Jennifer|last=Vineyard|publisher=MTV News|date=September 11, 2006|access-date=October 23, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/art/2008/11/145_5365.html|title=Christina Aguilera Shows Off Impressive Vocals|first=Cathy|last=Garcia|work=[[The Korea Times]]|date=June 25, 2007|access-date=June 11, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/news/uae-news/aguilera-set-for-middle-east-debut|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110810070829/http://www.thenational.ae/news/uae-news/aguilera-set-for-middle-east-debut|title=Aguilera set for Middle East debut|work=[[The National (Abu Dhabi)|The National]]|first=Melanie|last=Swan|location=Abu Dhabi|date=October 23, 2008|archive-date=August 10, 2011}}</ref> With US$48.1 million grossed, the tour was the highest-grossing solo female tour of 2007.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/music-news/the-police-score-top-grossing-tour-of-07-1047044/|title=The Police Score Top-Grossing Tour Of '07|date=December 13, 2007|magazine=Billboard|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141007050948/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1047044/the-police-score-top-grossing-tour-of-07|archive-date=October 7, 2014|access-date=January 21, 2022}}</ref>

In January 2008, a son named Max was born to Aguilera and Bratman.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1579535/christina-aguilera-gives-birth-to-baby-boy/|title=Christina Aguilera Gives Birth to Baby Boy|publisher=MTV News|date=January 13, 2008|access-date=January 13, 2018}}</ref> Later that year, she appeared in the [[Martin Scorsese]] documentary ''[[Shine a Light (film)|Shine a Light]]'' chronicling a two-day concert by [[The Rolling Stones]] in New York City's [[Beacon Theatre (New York City)|Beacon Theatre]], in which Aguilera performs "[[Live with Me]]" alongside the band's lead vocalist [[Mick Jagger]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/filmreviews/3672481/Film-reviews-Shine-a-Light-and-21.html |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220110/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/filmreviews/3672481/Film-reviews-Shine-a-Light-and-21.html |archive-date=January 10, 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live|title=Film reviews: Shine a Light and 21|first=David|last=Gritten|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=April 11, 2008|access-date=August 28, 2013}}{{cbignore}}</ref> In commemoration of a decade-long career in the music industry, Aguilera released a [[greatest hits album]] titled ''[[Keeps Gettin' Better: A Decade of Hits]]'' exclusively through [[Target Corporation|Target]] in November 2008, in the US.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/music-news/target-scores-aguilera-hits-album-exclusive-1044276/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140831165331/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1044276/target-scores-aguilera-hits-album-exclusive|title=Target Scores Aguilera Hits Album Exclusive|first=Katie|last=Hasty|magazine=Billboard|date=September 3, 2008|archive-date=August 31, 2014|access-date=January 21, 2022}}</ref> In addition to previous singles, it includes four original [[electropop]]-oriented songs, two of which are remade versions of two previous singles.<ref>{{cite magazine|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707142741/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/artists/christina-aguilera/albumguide|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/artists/christina-aguilera/albumguide|title=Christina Aguilera: Album Guide|magazine=Rolling Stone|archive-date=July 7, 2011}}</ref><ref name="2008Album"/> Aguilera commented that the newly recorded tracks' "futurisic, robotic sound" served as a preview for her follow-up studio album.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/music-news/christina-aguilera-better-and-better-1043491/|title=Christina Aguilera: Better And 'Better'|first=Michael|last=Concepcion|date=November 14, 2008|access-date=January 21, 2022|magazine=Billboard}}</ref> ''Keeps Gettin' Better'' peaked at number nine on the ''Billboard'' 200, and its titular single "[[Keeps Gettin' Better]]" charted at number seven on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref name="AguileraBBCharts"/> ''Billboard'' in 2009 recognized Aguilera as the 20th most successful artist of the 2000s.<ref name="AotD"/>

===2010–2011: ''Bionic'', ''Burlesque'', and ''The Voice''===
[[File:Christina Aguilera at the premiere of Burlesque (2010).jpg|thumb|upright|left|Aguilera at the premiere of ''[[Burlesque (2010 American film)|Burlesque]]'' at the [[Empire, Leicester Square]] in 2010]]
Aguilera began working on her sixth studio album during her pregnancy when she frequently listened to [[electronic music]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1641039/christina-aguilera-brings-new-songs-classic-hits-to-today-show/|title=Christina Aguilera Brings New Songs, Classic Hits To 'Today' Show|publisher=MTV News|first=James|last=Dinh|date=June 8, 2010|access-date=January 21, 2022}}</ref> The lead single from the album, "[[Not Myself Tonight]]", was released in March 2010.<ref name="releases">{{cite web|url=http://www.clevelandleader.com/node/13444|title=New Christina Aguilera Album "Bionic" Out June 8th|first=Eugene|last=McCormick|newspaper=[[The Cleveland Leader]]|date=March 25, 2010|access-date=March 17, 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203005849/http://www.clevelandleader.com/node/13444|archive-date=December 3, 2013}}</ref> Heavily influenced by electronic genres, the song signaled Aguilera's musical experiments on her forthcoming album.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/christina-aguilera-hits-the-dance-floor-with-not-myself-tonight-110575/|title=Christina Aguilera Hits the Dance Floor With Not Myself Tonight|first=Daniel|last=Kreps|magazine=Rolling Stone|date=March 31, 2010|access-date=January 21, 2022}}</ref> It peaked at number 23 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref name="AguileraBBCharts"/> The album, titled ''[[Bionic (Christina Aguilera album)|Bionic]]'', was released in June 2010. Categorized as a R&B-flavored [[futurepop]] album by critics,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/music_blog/2010/06/album-review-christina-aguileras-bionic.html|title=Album review: Christina Aguilera's 'Bionic'|date=June 7, 2010|first=Margaret|last=Wappler|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=August 8, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/album-christina-aguilera-bionic-rca-1991440.html|title=Album: Christina Aguilera, Bionic (RCA)|first=Andy|last=Gill|work=The Independent|date=June 4, 2010|access-date=August 8, 2014}}</ref> ''Bionic'' lyrically revolves around sexual themes while also discussing [[feminism]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2010/jun/06/christina-aguilera-bionic-cd-review|title=Bionic {{!}} CD Review|work=[[The Observer]]|first=Kitty|last=Empire|date=June 6, 2010|access-date=August 10, 2014}}</ref> Critical reaction to the album was mixed; reviewers commended Aguilera's experimentation with new styles, but found it forced and unnatural.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/bionic/christina-aguilera/critic-reviews|title=Critic Reviews for Bionic|website=Metacritic|access-date=January 24, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/07/arts/music/07choice.html|title=New CD's|first=Jon|last=Pareles|author-link=Jon Pareles|work=The New York Times|date=June 7, 2010|access-date=August 8, 2014}}</ref><ref name="Guardian">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2010/jun/03/christina-aguilera-bionic-cd-review|title=Christina Aguilera – Bi-On-Ic {{!}} CD Review|work=The Guardian|date=June 3, 2010|first=Alexis|last=Petridis|access-date=August 8, 2014}}</ref> The album peaked at number three on the ''Billboard'' 200 and has sold 332,000 copies in the US as of 2019.<ref name="AlbumSales">{{cite web|author=Gary Trust|date=24 August 2019|url=https://www.billboard.com/pro/lil-nas-x-billy-ray-cyrus-christina-aguilera-ask-billboard-mailbag/|title=Ask Billboard: A Supersized Mailbag in Honor of Lil Nas X & Billy Ray Cyrus' Record Run Atop the Hot 100|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=January 21, 2022}}</ref> The album spawned one other international single, "[[You Lost Me]]". Two other singles from the album, "[[Woohoo (Christina Aguilera song)|Woohoo]]" featuring rapper [[Nicki Minaj]] and "[[I Hate Boys]]", were released in the US and Europe,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fmqb.com/Article.asp?id=69239|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140712065553/http://fmqb.com/Article.asp?id=69239|title=Airplay Archive|work=FMQB|url-status=dead|archive-date=July 12, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/be/album/woohoo-feat-nicki-minaj-single/id374246489|title=Woohoo – Single|publisher=iTunes Store Belgium|access-date=July 8, 2014}}</ref> and Australia, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.themusicnetwork.com/music-releases/singles/2010/06/28/issue-793/Christina-Aguilera--i-Hate-Boys/|title=Christina Aguilera – I Hate Boys – Issue 793|work=[[The Music Network]]|date=June 28, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120406144504/http://www.themusicnetwork.com/music-releases/singles/2010/06/28/issue-793/Christina-Aguilera--i-Hate-Boys/|archive-date=April 6, 2012}}</ref>

Aguilera starred alongside [[Cher]] in the musical film ''[[Burlesque (2010 American film)|Burlesque]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2010/dec/11/cher-christina-aguilera-burlesque|title=Cher could teach Christina Aguilera a thing or two in Burlesque|work=The Guardian|first=John|last=Patterson|date=December 11, 2010|access-date=August 29, 2013}}</ref> Written and directed by [[Steve Antin]], the film was released in theaters in November 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/movies/news/2010-11-22-burlesque24_VA_N.htm|title=Director Antin had stars in his eyes when he cast 'Burlesque'|work=USA Today|first=Susan|last=Wloszczyna|date=November 23, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140715104549/http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/movies/news/2010-11-22-burlesque24_VA_N.htm|archive-date=July 15, 2014|url-status=dead|access-date=July 8, 2014}}</ref> Aguilera played Ali Rose, who quits her bar service job and moves to Los Angeles, where she aspires to be a performer in a [[American burlesque|burlesque]] club owned by Tess Scali (Cher). ''Burlesque'' grossed US$90 million in the box office<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=burlesque.htm|title=Burlesque (2010)|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|access-date=August 25, 2013}}</ref> and received mixed reviews from critics, who found it [[cliché]]d but praised Aguilera's acting.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/burlesque|title='Burlesque' Reviews|website=Metacritic|access-date=May 2, 2014}}</ref> The film received a nomination for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture – Musical or Comedy|Best Motion Picture – Musical or Comedy]] at the [[68th Golden Globe Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/env-2011-globes-nom-list-scorecard-html-htmlstory.html|title=2011 Golden Globes nominees & winners|work=Los Angeles Times|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140715024803/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/env-2011-globes-nom-list-scorecard-html-htmlstory.html|archive-date=July 15, 2014|url-status=dead|access-date=July 8, 2014}}</ref> Aguilera recorded eight tracks for the film's ten-track [[Burlesque: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack|accompanying soundtrack]], and Cher performed the other two.<ref>{{cite AV media notes|others=Christina Aguilera, Cher|title=Burlesque: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack|year=2010|type=inlay cover|publisher=Screen Gems, Inc|page=iTunes Digital Booklet}}</ref> The soundtrack reached number 18 on the ''Billboard'' 200 and was certified gold by the RIAA.<ref name="RIAA"/><ref name="AguileraBBCharts"/>

At [[Super Bowl XLV]] in February 2011, Aguilera omitted a few lines while performing the US national anthem.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1657367/christina-aguilera-super-bowl/|title=Christina Aguilera Apologizes For Super Bowl National Anthem Flub|first=Gil|last=Kaulfman|publisher=MTV News|date=July 2, 2011|access-date=February 23, 2015}}</ref> She apologized for the incident, saying: "I got so caught up in the moment of the song that I lost my place."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.torontosun.com/entertainment/music/2011/02/07/17179721-wenn-story.html|title=Aguilera sorry for Super Bowl fumble|newspaper=[[Toronto Sun]]|date=December 12, 2010|access-date=February 7, 2011}}</ref> At the [[53rd Annual Grammy Awards]], she performed alongside [[Jennifer Hudson]], [[Martina McBride]], [[Yolanda Adams]], and [[Florence Welch]] in a segment that paid tribute to soul singer [[Aretha Franklin]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Semigran|first=Aly|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1657852/christina-aguilera-jennifer-hudson-aretha-franklin-grammy-tribute/|title=Christina Aguilera, Jennifer Hudson Belt Out Aretha Franklin Grammy Tribute|publisher=MTV News|date=February 13, 2011|access-date=December 4, 2012}}</ref> Aguilera finalized her divorce from Jordan Bratman, from whom she had been separated since September 2010, on April 15, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/celebrity/2011-04-15/christina-aguileras-divorce-finalized-today/|title=Christina Aguilera's Divorce Finalized Today|publisher=VH1|first=Liz|last=Black|date=April 15, 2011|access-date=February 23, 2015|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150224150211/http://www.vh1.com/celebrity/2011-04-15/christina-aguileras-divorce-finalized-today/|archive-date=February 24, 2015}}</ref> She concurrently started dating Matthew Rutler, an assistant on the set of ''Burlesque''.<ref name="EngagedNY">{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/gossip/christina-aguilera-engaged-boyfriend-matt-rutler-article-1.1615176|title=Christina Aguilera engaged to boyfriend Matt Rutler, reveals massive ring on Twitter|work=New York Daily News|location=New York|first=Nina|last=Golgowski|date=February 14, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140215032645/http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/gossip/christina-aguilera-engaged-boyfriend-matt-rutler-article-1.1615176|archive-date=February 15, 2014}}</ref> From April 2011 to December 2012, Aguilera served as a coach on the first three seasons of the television competition series ''[[The Voice (American TV series)|The Voice]]''.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/music-news/christina-aguilera-gwen-stefani-shakira-voice-poll-6281721/|title=Christina Aguilera, Gwen Stefani or Shakira|magazine=Billboard|date=October 14, 2014|first=Katie|last=Atkinson|access-date=January 21, 2022}}</ref> During the first season, Aguilera was featured on [[Maroon 5]]'s single "[[Moves like Jagger]]" upon the invitation of the group's lead vocalist and Aguilera's fellow ''The Voice'' coach [[Adam Levine]]. The single peaked atop the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 and was [[RIAA certification|certified diamond]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA).<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/music-news/maroon-5-and-christina-aguileras-moves-like-jagger-struts-to-no-1-on-1172581/|title=Maroon 5 and Christina Aguilera's 'Moves Like Jagger' Struts To No. 1 on Billboard Hot 100|magazine=Billboard|date=August 31, 2011|first=Gary|last=Trust|access-date=January 21, 2022}}</ref><ref name="RIAA"/>

===2012–2017: ''Lotus'', second child, and television projects===
[[File:Christina Aguilera - Breakthrough Prize Scientists, 2014 (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|Christina performing "[[Beautiful (Christina Aguilera song)|Beautiful]]" at the [[Breakthrough Prize|Breakthrough Prize Scientist Awards]] in 2014]]
Upon the third season of ''The Voice'' in September 2012, Aguilera released "[[Your Body (Christina Aguilera song)|Your Body]]" as the lead single from her seventh studio album.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/music-news/christina-aguilera-billboard-cover-story-474983/|title=Christina Aguilera: Billboard Cover Story|magazine=Billboard|first=Andrew|last=Hampp|date=September 21, 2012|access-date=January 21, 2022}}</ref> The single charted on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 at number 34.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/pro/maroon-5-still-tops-hot-100-psy-one-step-from-no-1/|title=Maroon 5 Still Tops Hot 100, PSY One Step From No. 1|magazine=Billboard|first=Gary|last=Trust|date=September 26, 2012|access-date=January 21, 2022}}</ref> The album, titled ''[[Lotus (Christina Aguilera album)|Lotus]]'', followed in November 2012. Aguilera described the record as a "rebirth" of herself after the personal struggles she overcame.<ref name="CareerBiggest">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/music-news/christina-aguileras-top-10-biggest-career-moments-474045/|title=Christina Aguilera's Top 10 Biggest Career Moments|magazine=Billboard|date=November 21, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140613130053/http://www.billboard.com/articles/list/474045/christina-aguileras-top-10-biggest-career-moments?page=0%2C2|archive-date=June 13, 2014|first=Jason|last=Lipshutz|access-date=January 21, 2022}}</ref> Contemporary reviewers found the album generic and conventional, as opposed to Aguilera's previous experimental ventures.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Review: Lotus|journal=[[Q (magazine)|Q]]|location=London|date=January 2013|issue=318|page=101}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Caramanica|first1=Jon|last2=Pareles|first2=Jon|author-link2=Jon Pareles|last3=Ratliff|first3=Ben|date=November 13, 2012|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/11/13/arts/music/albums-by-christina-aguilera-soundgarden-and-brian-eno.html?_r=0|title=Albums by Christina Aguilera, Soundgarden and Brian Eno|page=34|newspaper=The New York Times|access-date=November 17, 2012}}</ref> ''Lotus'' peaked at number seven on the ''Billboard'' 200 and has sold 303,000 copies in the US as of 2019.<ref name="AlbumSales"/> The album was supported by another single, "[[Just a Fool]]", featuring Aguilera's fellow ''The Voice'' coach [[Blake Shelton]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/music-news/christina-aguilera-blake-shelton-unveil-just-a-fool-on-the-474076/|title=Christina Aguilera, Blake Shelton Unveil 'Just a Fool' on 'The Voice'|magazine=Billboard|first=Jeff|last=Benjamin|date=November 20, 2012|access-date=January 21, 2022}}</ref> In December 2012, Aguilera was replaced by [[Shakira]] for the [[The Voice (American season 4)|fourth season]] of ''The Voice'' due to wanting to focus on solo projects.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/music-news/the-voice-locks-in-fourth-fifth-seasons-on-nbc-474926/|first=David|last=Greenwald|title='The Voice' Locks In Fourth, Fifth Seasons on NBC|magazine=Billboard|date=September 25, 2012|access-date=January 21, 2014}}</ref> She returned for the [[The Voice (American season 5)|fifth season]] in September 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/462458/the-voice-season-5-premiere-coaches-christina-aguilera-and-cee-lo-green-make-a-triumphant-return|title=The Voice Season 5 Premiere: Coaches Christina Aguilera and Cee Lo Green Make a Triumphant Return|first=Leanne|last=Aguilera|publisher=E!|date=September 23, 2013|access-date=June 20, 2014}}</ref>

In 2013, Aguilera scored three international top-ten singles. She was featured on rapper [[Pitbull (rapper)|Pitbull]]'s "[[Feel This Moment]]", which peaked at number eight on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 and was certified platinum by the RIAA.<ref name="RIAA"/><ref name="AguileraBBCharts"/> She subsequently appeared on Mexican singer [[Alejandro Fernández]]'s cover of [[Miguel Gallardo (singer)|Miguel Gallardo]]'s "[[Hoy Tengo Ganas de Ti#Alejandro Fernández and Christina Aguilera version|Hoy Tengo Ganas de Ti]]" (1976), which earned a diamond certification in Mexico.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amprofon.com.mx/certificaciones-amprofon.php?key=Alejandro+Fern%C3%A1ndez&action=Buscar&anio=&disquera=&tipoAlbum=&tipoCertificacion=|title=Certificaciones Amprofon|language=es|publisher=[[Asociación Mexicana de Productores de Fonogramas y Videogramas]]|access-date=February 6, 2018|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.today/20141022235531/http://www.amprofon.com.mx/certificaciones-amprofon.php?key=Alejandro+Fern%C3%A1ndez&action=Buscar&anio=&disquera=&tipoAlbum=&tipoCertificacion=|archive-date=October 22, 2014}}</ref> Aguilera collaborated with [[A Great Big World]] on the ballad "[[Say Something (A Great Big World song)|Say Something]]", which earned a six-time platinum certification from the RIAA<ref name="RIAA"/> and won [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Duo/Group Performance|Best Pop Duo/Group Performance]] at the [[57th Annual Grammy Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/awards/57th-annual-grammy-awards|title=57th Annual Grammy Awards|date=November 28, 2017|publisher=[[National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences]]|access-date=February 6, 2018}}</ref> Aguilera temporarily withdrew from ''The Voice'' for the [[The Voice (U.S. season 6)|sixth]] and [[The Voice (U.S. season 7)|seventh]] seasons, wishing to devote time to her family. She was respectively replaced by Shakira and [[Gwen Stefani]] during the two seasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv-movies/shakira-usher-return-voice-season-6-article-1.1551737|title=Shakira, Usher returning to 'The Voice' for Season 6|first=Zayda|last=Rivera|work=New York Daily News|date=December 18, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140906051505/http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv-movies/shakira-usher-return-voice-season-6-article-1.1551737|archive-date=September 6, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/entertainment/news/christina-aguilera-gwen-stefani-the-voice-confirms-coach-2014294|title=Christina Aguilera Welcomes Gwen Stefani to The Voice, Confirms Singer's Role as Season 7 Coach|work=Us Weekly|date=April 29, 2014|access-date=February 23, 2015}}</ref> After her engagement to Matthew Rutler in February 2014 and the birth of their daughter Summer in August,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/gossip/la-et-mg-christina-aguilera-baby-girl-name-matthew-rutler-20140818-story.html|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=August 18, 2014|access-date=August 18, 2014|title=Christina Aguilera welcomes, names new baby girl with Matthew Rutler|first=Christie|last=D'Zurilla}}</ref> she returned for the [[The Voice (U.S. season 8)|eighth season]] in October.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/music-news/christina-aguilera-returning-the-voice-season-8-6281700/|title=Goodbye, Gwen: Christina Aguilera Returning to 'The Voice'|date=October 14, 2014|magazine=Billboard|first=Joe|last=Lynch|access-date=January 21, 2022}}</ref> Aguilera's last season on ''The Voice'' was the [[The Voice (American season 10)|tenth]], which she won with her contestant [[Alisan Porter]] in May 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/alisan-porter-makes-christina-aguilera-first-winning-female-voice-coach/|title=Alisan Porter makes Christina Aguilera first winning female 'Voice' coach|work=CBS News|last=Park|first=Andrea|date=May 25, 2016|access-date=May 28, 2016}}</ref>

Aguilera played a recurring role of Jade St. John, a pop singer who tries to venture out to [[country music]], on the [[Nashville (season 3)|third season]] of [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s musical drama series ''[[Nashville (2012 TV series)|Nashville]]'' in April 2015.<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Berman|first1=Eliza|title=Watch Christina Aguilera Vamp It Up on a Sneak Peak From Nashville|magazine=Time|date=April 9, 2015|url=http://time.com/3816030/christina-aguilera-nashville/|access-date=May 1, 2015}}</ref> Two promotional singles were released in order to support her appearance: "The Real Thing" and "[[Shotgun (Christina Aguilera song)|Shotgun]]".<ref>{{cite web|title=The Real Thing (feat. Christina Aguilera) – Single by Nashville Cast|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/real-thing-feat.-christina/id983077384|publisher=iTunes Store (US)|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150414060423/https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/real-thing-feat.-christina/id983077384|archive-date=April 14, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150414060418/https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/shotgun-feat.-christina-aguilera/id983078411|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/shotgun-feat.-christina-aguilera/id983078411|title=Shotgun – Single by The Nashville Cast|publisher=[[iTunes Store]] (US)|archive-date=April 14, 2015}}</ref> She and her partner Rutler served as executive producers for a music-based game show, ''Tracks'', which aired on [[Spike TV]] in March 2016.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wagmeister|first1=Elizabeth|title=Christina Aguilera Producing Music Game Show for Spike TV|url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/news/tracks-game-show-christina-aguilera-spike-tv-1201730419/|access-date=March 16, 2016|work=Variety|date=March 15, 2016}}</ref>

On June 16, 2016, Aguilera released a song titled "[[Change (Christina Aguilera song)|Change]]" in which she dedicated to the victims of the 2016 [[Orlando nightclub shooting]] as well as [[Christina Grimmie]], who was fatally shot in Orlando the day before the nightclub shooting. The proceeds were donated to the National Compassion Fund to benefit the victims' families.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/tv/tv-news/watch-christina-aguilera-belt-orlando-tribute-change-on-kimmel-110780/|title=Watch Christina Aguilera Belt Orlando Tribute 'Change' on 'Kimmel'|magazine=Rolling Stone|first=Ryan|last=Reed|date=June 24, 2016|access-date=January 21, 2022}}</ref> Her other works included recording a [[disco]] song titled "[[Telepathy (Christina Aguilera song)|Telepathy]]" featuring [[Nile Rodgers]] for the soundtrack of [[Netflix]] original series ''[[The Get Down]]'' (2016),<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.ew.com/article/2016/08/11/christina-aguilera-telepathy/|title=Christina Aguilera's Telepathy: Xtina returns to the dance floor|first=Joey|last=Nolfl|magazine=Entertainment Weekly|date=August 11, 2016|access-date=February 6, 2018}}</ref> being a voice actress for ''[[The Emoji Movie]]'' (2017),<ref>{{cite news|last1=French|first1=Megan|last2=Blynn|first2=Jamie|title=Meet Christina Aguilera's 'Emoji Movie' Character Akiko Glitter: First Pic!|url=https://www.usmagazine.com/entertainment/news/meet-christina-aguileras-emoji-movie-character-first-pic-w482253/|access-date=May 15, 2017|work=Us Weekly|date=May 15, 2017}}</ref> and starring in the romantic science fiction film ''[[Zoe (film)|Zoe]]'' released in 2018.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McNary|first1=Dave|title=Christina Aguilera, Theo James, Rashida Jones Join Sci-Fi Romance 'Zoe'|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/christina-aguilera-theo-james-rashida-jones-romance-zoe-1202404532/|access-date=May 2, 2017|work=Variety|date=May 1, 2017}}</ref> In November 2017, Aguilera performed a medley of ''[[The Bodyguard (soundtrack)|The Bodyguard]]'' songs during the [[American Music Awards of 2017|American Music Awards]] in honor to celebrate Whitney Houston.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/christina-aguilera-whitney-houston-tribute-ama_n_5a127861e4b0dd63b1ab4021|title=Christina Aguilera Performs Touching Tribute To Whitney Houston At AMAs|work=[[HuffPost]]|publisher=[[BuzzFeed]]|first=Rebecca|last=Shapiro|date=November 20, 2017|access-date=March 19, 2021}}</ref>

===2018–2021: ''Liberation'' and Christina Aguilera: The Xperience ===
[[File:Liberation Tour (31108486747).jpg|thumb|Aguilera performing on her [[The Liberation Tour (Christina Aguilera tour)|Liberation Tour]] at the [[Pepsi Center]] in 2018|left]]
Aguilera started working on her eighth studio album in the summer of 2015.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/music-news/christina-aguilera-next-album-pharrell-williams-6457974/|title=Christina Aguilera Talks Next Album, Working with Pharrell Williams on New Music|last=Lipshut|first=Jason|date=January 30, 2015|magazine=Billboard|access-date=January 21, 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.papermag.com/christina-aguilera-transformation-2553214651.html|title=Christina Aguilera Is Back With a New Transformation|last1=Lodi|first1=Marie|date=March 26, 2018|work=[[Paper (magazine)|Paper]]|access-date=May 6, 2018}}</ref> "[[Accelerate (Christina Aguilera song)|Accelerate]]" featuring [[Ty Dolla Sign]] and [[2 Chainz]] was released as the lead single from the album.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://time.com/5264447/christina-aguileras-accelerate/|title=Christina Aguilera Is Back With a New Rap-Forward Single|date=May 3, 2018|magazine=Time|access-date=May 5, 2018}}</ref> "Accelerate" became Aguilera's tenth number one song on the US ''Billboard'' Dance Songs Chart.<ref name="lvgs">{{cite web |last=Radke |first=Brock |date=October 19, 2018 |title=Christina Aguilera's creativity has been liberated |url=https://lasvegasmagazine.com/entertainment/2018/oct/19/christina-aguilera-concert-caesars-palace/ |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200722171507/https://lasvegasmagazine.com/entertainment/2018/oct/19/christina-aguilera-concert-caesars-palace/ |archive-date=2020-07-22 |access-date=July 22, 2020 |work=Las Vegas Magazine |publisher=[[Greenspun Media Group]]}}</ref> It was followed by the [[promotional single]] "[[Twice (song)|Twice]]" on May 11,<ref>{{cite magazine |date=May 11, 2018 |title=Christina Aguilera's 'Twice' Is Here: Listen |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8455537/christina-aguilera-twice |magazine=Billboard |access-date=May 12, 2018}}</ref> and the second single "[[Fall in Line]]" featuring [[Demi Lovato]] on May 16.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/hear-christina-aguileras-empowering-new-song-fall-in-line-with-demi-lovato-628085/|title=Hear Christina Aguilera's Empowering New Song 'Fall in Line' With Demi Lovato|last=Kreps|first=Daniel|date=May 16, 2018|magazine=Rolling Stone|access-date=January 21, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=White |first1=Jack |date=May 16, 2018 |title=Christina Aguilera and Demi Lovato release their much-anticipated collaboration Fall In Line |url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/christina-aguilera-and-demi-lovato-release-their-much-anticipated-collaboration-fall-in-line__22928/ |access-date=May 19, 2018 |publisher=Official Charts Company}}</ref> "[[Like I Do (Christina Aguilera song)|Like I Do]]" featuring [[GoldLink]] was released on June 7, 2018, as the album's third and final single.<ref>{{cite magazine |date=June 7, 2018 |title=Christina Aguilera Releases Bouncy New Single 'Like I Do' Featuring Goldlink: Listen |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8459889/christina-aguilera-like-i-do-goldlink-new-song |magazine=Billboard |access-date=January 6, 2019}}</ref> ''Liberation'', was released on June 15, 2018, to favorable reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/liberation/christina-aguilera|title=Reviews for Liberation by Christina Aguilera|website=Metacritic|access-date=October 31, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/christina-aguileras-liberation-w521561|title=Review: Christina Aguilera Flexes Her Diva Power on the Excellent 'Liberation'|last=Spanos|first=Brittany|date=June 14, 2018|magazine=Rolling Stone|access-date=June 19, 2018|archive-date=June 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180616130610/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/christina-aguileras-liberation-w521561|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/13/arts/music/christina-aguilera-liberation-review.html|title=Christina Aguilera Exults in Her Voice on 'Liberation'|last=Pareles|first=Jon|date=June 13, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=June 21, 2018}}</ref> Aguilera heavily incorporated R&B and hip hop on the album to represent her desire for freedom from what she described as the "churning hamster wheel" that was ''The Voice''.<ref name="Freedom">{{cite magazine|first=Allie|last=Jones|date=3 May 2018|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/features/christina-aguilera-new-album-liberation-interview-cover-story-2018-8446904/|title=Christina Aguilera on 'Longing for Freedom' & Her Hip-Hop-Inspired Return to Music|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=January 21, 2022}}</ref> ''Liberation'' debuted at number six on the ''Billboard'' 200 chart, becoming Aguilera's seventh US top-ten album.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/pro/5-seconds-of-summer-third-no-1-album-billboard-200-chart/|title=5 Seconds of Summer Earn Third No. 1 Album on Billboard 200 Chart With 'Youngblood'|last1=Caulfield|first1=Keith|date=June 24, 2018|magazine=Billboard|access-date=January 21, 2022}}</ref> At the [[61st Annual Grammy Awards]], "Fall in Line" was nominated for Best Pop Duo/Group Performance, while "Like I Do" received a nomination for [[Best Rap/Sung Performance]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/awards/61st-annual-grammy-awards|title=61st Annual GRAMMY Awards|date=December 6, 2018|publisher=National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences|access-date=December 14, 2018}}</ref> Aguilera starred in the romantic science fiction ''Zoe'', which was premiered at the [[Tribeca Film festival]] in April 2018, and was later released on July 20 by [[Amazon Studios]].

To promote ''Liberation'', Aguilera embarked on her first tour in 10 years, [[The Liberation Tour (Christina Aguilera tour)|The Liberation Tour]], which ran from September to November 2018.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/pro/christina-aguilera-liberation-tour-dates/|title=Christina Aguilera Announces Liberation Tour, First Outing Since 2008|date=May 9, 2018|access-date=January 21, 2022|first=Kaufman|last=Gil|magazine=Billboard}}</ref> and a follow-up European tour, [[The X Tour (Christina Aguilera)|The X Tour]], which ran from July to December 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.idolator.com/7714327/christina-aguilera-announces-the-x-tour?chrome=1|title=She's Coming, Europe! Christina Aguilera Announces 'The X Tour'|first=Mike|last=Nied|website=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]|date=March 4, 2019|access-date=June 29, 2019}}</ref> She also headlined [[Christina Aguilera: The Xperience]],<ref>{{Cite web |last=Entertainment |first=Caesars |title=International Superstar Christina Aguilera Announces Final Show Dates For "Christina Aguilera: The Xperience" At Planet Hollywood Resort & Casino |url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/international-superstar-christina-aguilera-announces-final-show-dates-for-christina-aguilera-the-xperience-at-planet-hollywood-resort--casino-301014071.html |access-date=2022-09-10 |website=www.prnewswire.com |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Christina Aguilera: The Xperience, will open at Zappos Theater at Planet Hollywood Resort & Casino on Friday, May 31, 2019 |url=https://www.caesars.com/meetings/press/christinaaguileraresidency |access-date=2022-08-30 |website=www.caesars.com |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Radke |first=Brock |date=2019-05-31 |title=Best Bets: Shin Lim, Christina Aguilera, Anita Baker and more for your Las Vegas weekend - Las Vegas Sun Newspaper |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2019/may/31/best-bets-shin-lim-christina-aguilera-anita-baker/ |access-date=2022-08-30 |website=lasvegassun.com |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2019-01-29 |title=Christina Aguilera set for Las Vegas residency at Planet Hollywood |url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/entertainment/entertainment-columns/kats/christina-aguilera-set-for-las-vegas-residency-at-planet-hollywood-1584516/ |access-date=2022-08-30 |website=Las Vegas Review-Journal |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Christina Aguilera reveals details of Las Vegas residency |url=https://news.yahoo.com/christina-aguilera-reveals-details-las-vegas-residency-094028253.html |access-date=2022-08-30 |website=news.yahoo.com |language=en-US}}</ref> a 25-date concert residency at the [[Zappos Theater]] at [[Planet Hollywood Las Vegas]], beginning in May and concluding in March 2020.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/music-news/christina-aguilera-brings-the-xperience-to-las-vegas-8495496/|title=Christina Aguilera Brings 'The Xperience' to Las Vegas|date=January 29, 2019|magazine=Billboard|first=Melinda|last=Sheckells|access-date=January 21, 2022}}</ref> In October 2019, Aguilera released the soul and blues-inspired song "Haunted Heart" from the soundtrack of the computer-animated ''[[The Addams Family (2019 film)|Addams Family]]'' film,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/snoop-dogg-and-migos-share-new-song-for-the-addams-family-listen/|title=Snoop Dogg and Migos Share New Song for The Addams Family: Listen|website=Pitchfork|last=Moreland|first=Quinn|date=September 13, 2019|access-date=September 14, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.europafm.com/noticias/musica/christina-aguilera-regresa-musica-haunted-heart-pelicula-familia-addams_201909295d908b860cf2abfa5eabb8d2.html|title=Christina Aguilera regresa a la música con 'Haunted Heart' para la película de 'La Familia Addams'|publisher=[[Europa FM (Spain)|Europa FM]]. [[Atresmedia]]|language=Spanish|date=September 29, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191001061437/https://www.europafm.com/noticias/musica/christina-aguilera-regresa-musica-haunted-heart-pelicula-familia-addams_201909295d908b860cf2abfa5eabb8d2.html|access-date=March 19, 2021|archive-date=October 1, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://stereopop.com.br/musica/haunted-heart-confira-a-cancao-de-christina-aguilera-para-a-animacao-a-familia-adams|title='Haunted Heart' – Confira a canção de Christina Aguilera para a animação 'A Família Adams'|work=Stereo Pop|language=Portuguese|date=September 27, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191014190142/http://stereopop.com.br/musica/haunted-heart-confira-a-cancao-de-christina-aguilera-para-a-animacao-a-familia-adams|access-date=March 19, 2021|archive-date=October 14, 2019}}</ref> and a month later "[[Fall on Me (Andrea Bocelli and Matteo Bocelli song)#A Great Big World and Christina Aguilera version|Fall on Me]]"—her second collaboration with A Great Big World—was premiered.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://etcanada.com/news/542768/christina-aguilera-and-a-great-big-world-to-perform-new-track-fall-on-me-at-the-2019-amas/|title=Christina Aguilera And A Great Big World Release New Track 'Fall On Me'|first=Becca|last=Longmire|date=November 22, 2019|work=[[Entertainment Tonight Canada]]|access-date=September 9, 2020|archive-date=September 9, 2020|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200909104432/https://etcanada.com/news/542768/christina-aguilera-and-a-great-big-world-to-perform-new-track-fall-on-me-at-the-2019-amas/|url-status=live}}</ref> On March 6, 2020, Aguilera released "[[Loyal Brave True]]" as a promotional single from the live action remake of ''[[Mulan (2020 film)|Mulan]]'';<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/christina-aguilera-mulan-new-song-loyal-brave-true-964115/amp/|title=Christina Aguilera Returns to Her Disney Roots with New Song|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=March 7, 2020}}</ref> ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' considered it [[Academy Award for Best Original Song|Oscar]]-worthy.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/oscars-2021-best-original-song-nominees-1141919/|title=Oscars 2021: Hear the Nominees for Best Original Song|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|first=Kory|last=Grow|date=March 15, 2021|access-date=March 16, 2021}}</ref> She released a re-recording of "[[Reflection (Mulan song)#2020 live action version|Reflection]]" on August 28.<ref>{{Cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/pop/christina-aguilera-reflection-disney-mulan-video-9441813/|title=Christina Aguilera Returns to Her 'Reflection' For Disney's 'Mulan' With Two New Stunning Videos|access-date=January 21, 2022|magazine=Billboard}}</ref>

In July 2021, Aguilera [[Christina Aguilera with the LA Phil|performed for two nights]] at the [[Hollywood Bowl]] with [[Gustavo Dudamel]] and the [[Los Angeles Philharmonic]].<ref name="hollbowl">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/concerts/christina-aguilera-philharmonic-hollywood-bowl-recap-9602622/|title=Christina Aguilera Reimagines Her Biggest Hits With the LA Philharmonic at the Hollywood Bowl|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|first=Rania|last=Aniftos|date=July 17, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210717181511/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/concerts/9602622/christina-aguilera-philharmonic-hollywood-bowl-recap/|access-date=January 21, 2022|archive-date=July 17, 2021}}</ref><ref name="noise">{{cite web|url=https://www.noise11.com/news/christina-aguilera-performs-with-orchestra-at-hollywood-bowl-20210718|title=Christina Aguilera Performs With Orchestra At Hollywood Bowl|publisher=[[Paul Cashmere|Noise11.com]]. The Noise Network|first=Paul|last=Cashmere|date=July 18, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210718042318/https://www.noise11.com/news/christina-aguilera-performs-with-orchestra-at-hollywood-bowl-20210718|access-date=July 18, 2021|archive-date=July 18, 2021}}</ref> Both shows were sold out.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thatgrapejuice.net/2021/07/christina-aguilera-blazes-sold-out-hollywood-bowl-shows-dazzles-with-dirrty-fighter-more/|title=Christina Aguilera Blazes Sold-Out Hollywood Bowl Shows / Dazzles With 'Dirrty,' 'Fighter,' & More|work=That Grape Juice|publisher=Townsquare Music|date=July 18, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210718153008/https://thatgrapejuice.net/2021/07/christina-aguilera-blazes-sold-out-hollywood-bowl-shows-dazzles-with-dirrty-fighter-more/|access-date=July 18, 2021|archive-date=July 18, 2021}}</ref><ref name="hollbowl"/><ref name="noise"/> In early October, Aguilera featured on the [[The Addams Family 2#Music|soundtrack]] for ''[[The Addams Family 2]]'' performing the [[The Addams Family Theme|theme song from the original series]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/megan-thee-stallion-and-snoop-dogg-join-the-addams-family-2-soundtrack-3057094|title=Megan Thee Stallion and Snoop Dogg join 'The Addams Family 2' soundtrack|access-date=October 13, 2021|website=NME|date=September 28, 2021}}</ref> That same week, Aguilera performed two medleys for [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s Walt Disney World's 50th Anniversary special with the songs "[[Reflection (Mulan song)#2020 live action version|Reflection]]", "[[When You Wish Upon a Star]]" and "[[Loyal Brave True]]".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/travel/christina-aguilera-has-full-circle-moment-as-she-performs-at-disney-world-50th-anniversary/|title=Christina Aguilera Has a 'Full Circle Moment' as She Performs at Disney World 50th Anniversary|access-date=October 13, 2021|website=People}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://insidethemagic.net/2021/10/christina-aguilera-disney-worlds-50th-anniversary-zw1/|title=Christina Aguilera's 'Reflection' Shows Clearly at Disney World's 50th Anniversary|access-date=October 13, 2021|website=ITM|date=October 8, 2021}}</ref> Later that month, Aguilera performed "[[River Deep – Mountain High]]" at the [[Rock & Roll Hall of Fame]] as a tribute for [[Tina Turner]].<ref>{{Cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/tina-turner-rock-hall-tribute-christina-aguilera-1250914/|title=Christina Aguilera, Mickey Guyton Belt for Tina Turner at Rock Hall Tribute|access-date=November 2, 2021|magazine=Rolling Stone|date=October 31, 2021}}</ref> On December 7, 2021, Aguilera was also honored with the first Music Icon award at the [[47th People's Choice Awards]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/music/2021-peoples-choice-awards-christina-aguilera-accepts-music-icon-award/|title=Christina Aguilera Reflects on Her Incredible 2021: 'This Has Been a Year FULL of Celebration!'|access-date=December 7, 2021|website=People|date=December 7, 2021}}</ref>

=== 2022–present: ''Aguilera'' ===
[[File:Christina Aguilera at the Expo 2020 in Dubai.png|thumb|upright|Aguilera performing "A Million Dreams" at the [[Expo 2020]] in 2022]]
In early 2021, Aguilera announced that her ninth studio album would be in Spanish, being her first in 22 years, following up ''[[Mi Reflejo]]'' (2000).<ref name="billboard123"/> She also announced that the album would be released in three parts, with the first being an [[extended play]] titled ''[[La Fuerza]]'', eventually released on January 21, 2022.<ref name="billboard123">{{Cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/latin/christina-aguilera-la-fuerza-release-date-tracklist-1235020543/|title=Christina Aguilera Unveils Release Date & Tracklist for Her Upcoming Spanish-Language EP 'La Fuerza'|access-date=January 20, 2021|magazine=Billboard}}</ref> Preceding the EP's release, on October 21, 2021, Aguilera released "[[Pa Mis Muchachas]]", with [[Becky G]], [[Nicki Nicole]] and [[Nathy Peluso]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/style/christina-aguilera-dons-a-new-red-hairdo-in-sultry-snap-announcing-upcoming-music/|title=Christina Aguilera Dons a New Red Hairdo in Sultry Snap Announcing Upcoming Music|access-date=October 20, 2021|website=People}}</ref> Following that, on November 19, Aguilera debuted the second single, "[[Somos Nada]]", at the [[22nd Annual Latin Grammy Awards]] and performed it and "Pa' Mis Muchachas" alongside Becky, Nicole and Peluso.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.popsugar.com/entertainment/christina-aguilera-somos-nada-music-video-48611953|title=Christina Aguilera Debuts Sultry Song "Somos Nada" During the Latin Grammys|access-date=November 19, 2021|website=Pop Sugar|date=November 18, 2021}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eonline.com/news/1309801/christina-aguilera-rocks-fiery-look-during-epic-return-to-the-2021-latin-grammys-stage|title=Christina Aguilera Rocks Fiery Look During Epic Return to the 2021 Latin Grammys Stage|access-date=November 19, 2021|website=E!|date=November 19, 2021}}</ref> On January 20, 2022, alongside the release of ''La Fuerza'', "[[Santo (song)|Santo]]", a collaboration with [[Ozuna]], was released as the third single.<ref name="newsopener">{{cite web|title=Christina Aguilera Teases 'Santo' Collab With Ozuna & New EP ''La Fuerza'': See The Photo|url=https://newsopener.com/music-updates/christina-aguilera-teases-santo-collab-with-ozuna-new-ep-la-fuerza-see-the-photo/|access-date=January 15, 2022|website=NewsOpener|date=January 14, 2022}}</ref> On May 6, 2022, a music video was released for "[[La Reina (song)|La Reina]]".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hollywoodlife.com/2022/05/06/christina-aguilera-la-reina-music-video-dress/|title=Christina Aguilera Is Red Hot In Plunging Dress For 'La Reina' Video: Watch|access-date=May 31, 2022|website=Hollywood Life|date=May 7, 2022 }}</ref>

On April 1, 2022, Aguilera performed at the [[Dubai]] [[Expo 2020]] and closed the show with a cover of "[[A Million Dreams]]".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/expo-2020/expo-2020-dubai-closing-ceremony-as-it-happened-the-worlds-greatest-show-makes-grand-exit-1.1648723150920|title=Expo 2020 Dubai closing ceremony as it happened: The 'World's Greatest Show' makes grand exit|access-date=April 2, 2022|website=Gulf News}}</ref> In late May, Aguilera announced ''[[La Tormenta (EP)|La Tormenta]]'', the second extended play apart of her multi-part forthcoming Spanish-language studio album and its single, "[[Suéltame]]" with Argentine singer [[Tini (singer)|Tini]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/music/christina-aguilera-announces-new-spanish-ep-la-tormenta/|title=Christina Aguilera Announces New Spanish EP La Tormenta and New Single 'Sueltame'|access-date=May 25, 2022|website=People}}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/latin/christina-aguilera-announces-new-ep-tini-collaboration-1235074728/|title=Christina Aguilera Announces New EP 'La Tormenta' & a Collaboration With Tini|access-date=May 25, 2022|magazine=Billboard}}</ref> The EP was released on May 30, 2022, after being delayed due to the [[Robb Elementary School shooting]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thatgrapejuice.net/2022/05/stream-christina-aguileras-tormenta/|title=Stream: Christina Aguilera's EP 'La Tormenta'|access-date=May 31, 2022|website=ThatGrapeJuice}}</ref> On May 31, 2022, her ninth studio album, ''[[Aguilera (album)|Aguilera]]'', was released on streaming services and featured all the songs from ''La Fuerza'', ''La Tormenta'' and a new duet version of the song "Cuando Me Dé la Gana" featuring [[Christian Nodal]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwmusic/article/Christina-Aguilera-Releases-New-Album-AGUILERA-20220531 |title=Christina Aguilera Releases New Album 'Aguilera' |website=Broadwayworld |last=Major |first=Michael |date=May 31, 2022 |access-date=May 31, 2022}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.totalntertainment.com/music/christina-aguilera-releases-new-album-aguilera/|title=CHRISTINA AGUILERA RELEASES NEW ALBUM 'AGUILERA'|access-date=June 1, 2022|website=TotalNtertainment|date=May 31, 2022 }}</ref>

On June 11, 2022, Aguilera performed at [[Los Angeles Pride]] alongside [[Mya (singer)|Mya]], [[Kim Petras]] and [[Paris Hilton]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eonline.com/news/1334459/christina-aguilera-wears-hulk-outfit-with-strap-on-dildo-during-l-a-pride-event|title=Christina Aguilera Wears Hulk Outfit With Strap-on Dildo During L.A. Pride Event|access-date=June 14, 2022|website=E! News|date=June 14, 2022 }}</ref> During one segment of the show, Aguilera wore a [[strap-on dildo]] which received both praise and controversy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.perthnow.com.au/entertainment/music/christina-aguilera-dons-sex-toy-for-x-rated-performance-at-la-pride-concert-c-7146269|title=Christina Aguilera dons sex toy for x-rated performance at LA Pride concert|access-date=June 14, 2022|website=PerthNow|date=June 13, 2022 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.out.com/pride/2022/6/13/christina-aguilera-whipped-out-glittery-green-strap-la-pride|access-date=June 14, 2022|website=OUT|title=Christina Aguilera Whipped Out a Glittery Green Strap-On For Her LA Pride Performance|date=June 13, 2022 }}</ref> After her [[Los Angeles Pride]] headline show, Agulera embarked on a festival tour, [[EU/UK Summer Series]],<ref name="summer">{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/xtina/status/1549492049275039745|title=See you soon!|publisher=[[Twitter]]. [[Twitter, Inc.]]|date=July 19, 2022|archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220721160721/https://twitter.com/xtina/status/1549492049275039745|archive-date=July 21, 2022|access-date=July 21, 2022|url-status=live}}</ref> which includes three festivals in Spain, one in Monaco,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/review-christina-aguilera-wows-fans-27640534|title=Christina Aguilera wows fans as she gives five star performance at Monte Carlo Summer Festival|access-date=August 2, 2022|website=The Mirror|date=August 2, 2022 }}</ref> three arena shows in United Kingdom,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/d6f18353-67ea-4808-a853-c2e27739fa41|title=Christina Aguilera review — powerhouse entertainer thrills the O2 Arena|access-date=August 8, 2022|website=Financial Times|date=August 8, 2022 }}</ref> and ends with [[Brighton Pride]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2022/08/07/christina-aguilera-dont-say-gay-brighton-pride/|title=Christina Aguilera hits out at 'Don't Say Gay' during Brighton Pride performance|access-date=August 7, 2022|website=PinkNews|date=August 7, 2022 }}</ref>

On September 29, 2022, Aguilera performed "La Reina" at the [[2022 Billboard Latin Music Awards|2022 ''Billboard'' Latin Music Awards]] and received the [[Billboard Spirit of Hope Award|''Billboard'' Spirit of Hope Award]].<ref>{{Cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/latin/christina-aguilera-performs-la-reina-billboard-latin-music-awards-2022-1235147723/|title=Christina Aguilera Earns Her Crown at 2022 Billboard Latin Music Awards With Ranchera Anthem 'La Reina'|accessdate=September 30, 2022|magazine=Billboard}}</ref> ''La Luz'', the third and final EP from ''Aguilera'', was released that same day and featured a spoken intro by Aguilera and "No Es Que Te Extrañe".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uproxx.com/pop/christina-aguilera-estranged-father-song/|title=Christina Aguilera May Be Singing About Her Estranged Father In Her New Spanish Song|accessdate=September 30, 2022|website=UPROXX|date=September 28, 2022 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://portalpopline.com.br/la-luz-christina-aguilera-confirma-terceiro-ep-em-espanhol/|title="La Luz": Christina Aguilera confirma terceiro EP em espanhol|access-date=June 2, 2022|website=PopLine|date=June 2022 }}</ref> In October, Aguilera began teasing a deluxe 20th anniversary version of ''[[Stripped (Christina Aguilera album)|Stripped]]'' alongside a new music video for "[[Beautiful (Christina Aguilera song)|Beautiful]]".<ref>{{Cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/pop/christina-aguilera-new-beautiful-music-video-1235154527/|title=Christina Aguilera Announces New 'Beautiful' Music Video: 'Put Your Mind, Body & Soul First'|accessdate=October 15, 2022|magazine=Billboard}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.legacyrecordings.com/2022/10/14/christina-aguileras-stripped-20th-anniversary-celebrated-with-deluxe-digital-edition/|title=Christina Aguilera's 'Stripped' 20th Anniversary Celebrated with Deluxe Digital Edition|accessdate=October 15, 2022|website=Legacy|date=October 14, 2022 }}</ref>

==Artistry==
===Voice===
Critics have described Aguilera as a [[soprano]],<ref name="ChildStar">{{cite web|first=Elizabeth|last=Day|date=23 November 2008|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2008/nov/23/christina-aguilera-music|title=Elizabeth Day Talks to Child Star, Singing Sensation and New Mother Christina Aguilera|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=19 June 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Lauren|last=Beale|date=26 August 2011|url=https://www.latimes.com/home/la-xpm-2011-aug-26-la-hm-hotprop-christina-aguilera-20110826-story.html|title=Christina Aguilera Sells Sunset Strip-Area Home|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=19 June 2021}}</ref><ref name="ClassicFM">{{cite web|author=Maddy Shaw Roberts|date=14 March 2019|url=https://www.classicfm.com/discover-music/christina-aguilera-voice-analysis/|title=Let's Take a Moment to Appreciate How Incredible Christina Aguilera's Voice Is|publisher=[[Classic FM (UK)|Classic FM]]|access-date=19 June 2021}}</ref> possessing a four-octave [[vocal range]] (from [[C (musical note)|C<sub>3</sub>]] to [[C♯ (musical note)|C♯<sub>7</sub>]]),<ref>{{cite magazine|first=Samantha|last=Grossman|date=20 May 2014|url=https://time.com/105319/compare-vocal-ranges-of-worlds-greatest-singers/|title=This Interactive Chart Compares the Vocal Ranges of the World's Greatest Singers|magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|access-date=19 June 2021|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.today/20140520212926/http://time.com/105319/compare-vocal-ranges-of-worlds-greatest-singers/|archive-date=May 20, 2014}}</ref><ref name="Overdue">{{cite web|first=Nick|last=Levine|date=2 August 2019|url=https://www.vice.com/en/article/xweqya/christina-aguilera-genie-in-a-bottle-20-year-anniversary-essay|title=We're Long Overdue for a Christina Aguiera Comeback|publisher=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]|access-date=19 June 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Contessa|last=Gayles|date=24 May 2011|url=http://blog.music.aol.com/2011/05/24/10-things-you-didnt-know-about-the-voice-christina-aguilera/|title=10 Things You Didn't Know About 'The Voice' Coach and 'Dirrty' Pop Star Christina Aguilera|publisher=[[AOL]]|access-date=19 June 2021|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110601042700/http://blog.music.aol.com/2011/05/24/10-things-you-didnt-know-about-the-voice-christina-aguilera|archive-date=1 June 2011}}</ref> being also able to perform the [[whistle register]].<ref>{{cite magazine|first=Michael|last=Slezak|date=16 August 2006|url=https://ew.com/article/2006/08/16/essential-christina-aguilera/|title=The Essential Christina Aguilera|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|access-date=19 June 2021}}</ref> After the release of her [[Christina Aguilera (album)|self-titled debut album]], [[Ron Fair]] — executive of [[RCA Records]] — said he was betting on Aguilera due to her "perfect intonation", considering that she had "pipes to be the next [[Barbra Streisand]] or [[Céline Dion]]".<ref name="Behind">{{cite web|first=Alisa|last=Valdes-Rodriguez|date=26 July 1999|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1999-jul-26-ca-59618-story.html|title=Genie Behind 'Bottle'|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=19 June 2021}}</ref> In an article for ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'', [[Maura Johnston]] wrote that although Aguilera works in contemporary pop music, she has "an instrument that despite its ability to leap octaves has a low-end grounding similar to that possessed by opera singers".<ref>{{cite web|first=Maura|last=Johnston|date=15 November 2012|url=https://slate.com/culture/2012/11/christina-aguileras-lotus-reviewed.html|title=Christina Aguilera's Lotus, Reviewed|work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]|access-date=19 June 2021}}</ref> Highlighting her vocal versatility, Joan Anderman from ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' stated that she is "a real singer [...] blessed with the sort of breathtaking elasticity, golden tones, and sheer power that separate the divas from the dabblers".<ref>{{cite web|first=Joan|last=Anderman|date=10 September 1999|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/442155198/|title=Aguilera Shows Potential to Be More Than Just Marketing|publisher=[[The Boston Globe]]|access-date=19 June 2021}}</ref> Aguilera is also recognized for making use of [[melisma]] in her songs and performances;<ref name="ArtMelisma">{{cite web|first=Lauren|last=Everitt|date=15 February 2012|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/magazine-17039208|title=Whitney Houston and the Art of Melisma|publisher=[[BBC News]]|access-date=19 June 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Sarah|last=Handel|date=16 February 2011|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/talk/2011/02/16/133810158/please-cut-out-the-oversouling|title=Please, Cut Out the 'Oversouling'|publisher=[[NPR]]|access-date=19 June 2021}}</ref> [[Jon Pareles]], writing for ''[[The New York Times]]'', analyzed her vocal abilities, emphasizing that "she can aim a note as directly as a missile or turn its trajectory into an aerobatic spiral of leaping, quivering, scalloping melismas".<ref>{{cite web|first=Jon|last=Pareles|date=13 June 2018|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/13/arts/music/christina-aguilera-liberation-review.html|title=Christina Aguilera Exults in Her Voice on 'Liberation'|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=19 June 2021}}</ref> According to critics of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine, she has been modeled her "dramatic and melismatic technique" following steps of artists like [[Etta James]].<ref name="RS100">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/100-greatest-singers-of-all-time-147019/christina-aguilera-7-46198/|title=100 Greatest Singers of All Time|date=December 3, 2010|publisher=[[Rolling Stone]]|access-date=26 July 2021}}</ref>
