Throughout her career, her vocal ability has yielded comparisons with other vocalists. As a result of her use of melismatic technique, [[David Browne (journalist)|David Browne]] associated her with [[Whitney Houston]] and [[Mariah Carey]], opining that the three form the team of the main proponents of this vocal modality.<ref name="Songbirds">{{cite web|first=David|last=Browne|date=26 December 2010|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/12/26/arts/music/26browne.html|title=Thrilling Songbirds Clip Their Wings|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=19 June 2021}}</ref> Sharing the same point of view, [[Sasha Frere-Jones]], columnist for ''[[The New Yorker]]'', expressed that the technique was responsible for making her a "serious singer" without needing to "reincarnate the [[Sarah Vaughan]]".<ref name="SexSymbol">{{cite magazine|first=Sasha|last=Frere-Jones|date=28 August 2006|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2006/09/04/sex-symbols|title=Sex Symbols|magazine=[[The New Yorker]]|access-date=19 June 2021}}</ref> [[Steve Kipner]] — songwriter of "[[Genie in a Bottle]]" (1999) — considered that Aguilera has an "impressive" vocal dexterity, being able to "internalized all the riffs from [[Chaka Khan]]".<ref name="Behind"/> [[Ann Powers]], critic from ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', said that Aguilera has a voice "purely powerful as that of Etta James [...] and she's moving toward the expressiveness of [[Gladys Knight]], if not [[Aretha Franklin]]"; however, Powers notes that her vocal ability in ballad songs "connects her to Barbra Streisand", in addition to comparing her to [[Donna Summer]] when she works on songs influenced by [[rhythm and blues]].<ref name="BabyJane">{{cite web|first=Ann|last=Powers|date=15 August 2006|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2006-aug-15-et-christina15-story.html|title=Old-School? Her?|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=19 June 2021}}</ref>

However, Aguilera has also been criticized for the excessive use of melisma, as well as for [[oversinging]] in her songs and concerts.<ref>{{cite web|first=Corey|last=Moss|date=2 February 2006|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1523040/the-scourge-of-american-idol-oversingers/|title=The Scourge of 'American Idol': Oversingers|publisher=[[MTV News]]|access-date=19 June 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Preston|last=Jones|date=26 March 2007|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/entertainment/wo-o-o-whoa-stop-oversinging/|title=Wo-o-o, whoa: Stop Oversinging!|publisher=[[The Seattle Times]]|access-date=19 June 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=J. Freedom du Lac|date=16 August 2006|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/2006/08/16/a-divas-near-myth-span-classbankheadchristina-aguileras-back-to-basics-misstates-her-case-for-greatnessspan/0ce78d60-9f8c-4881-8ab2-2275463a5fe1/|title=A Diva's Near Myth Christina Aguilera's 'Back to Basics' Misstates Her Case for Greatness|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=19 June 2021}}</ref> Writing for ''[[The Huffington Post]]'', John Eskow stated that she is the main proponent of "oversouling" and, despite recognizing that she has a "great instrument", opined that she "[doesn't] seem to know when to stop" with the use of "gratuitous and confected melisma".<ref>{{cite web|first=John|last=Eskow|date=8 February 2011|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/christina-aguilera-and-th_b_819979|title=Christina Aguilera and the Hideous Cult of Oversouling|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|access-date=19 June 2021}}</ref> Lucy Davies, author at [[BBC Music]], acknowledges that Aguilera has a "stunning voice", but indicated that "she could be more varied, simply by cutting out some of the 'y-e-e-eeeh, woah yeh's' in her songs".<ref>{{cite web|first=Lucy|last=Davies|date=14 August 2006|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/4g25/|title=Review of Christina Aguilera - Back to Basics Album|publisher=[[BBC Music]]|access-date=19 June 2021}}</ref> During the recording session of "[[Beautiful (Christina Aguilera song)|Beautiful]]" (2002), the producer [[Linda Perry]] recalled that Aguilera had difficulty avoiding "vocal improvisations", stopping the recording every time she started to "[oversing]". Perry used the first take, saying, "She had a hard time accepting that as the final track. She's a perfectionist. She knows her voice really well and she knows what's going on. She can hear things that nobody else would catch."<ref>{{cite magazine|first=Brian|last=Hiatt|date=29 October 2002|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,385297_2,00.html|title=The Inside Story of Christina Aguilera's New Album|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|access-date=19 June 2021|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080430102822/http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,385297_2,00.html|archive-date=30 April 2008}}</ref> In an article for ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'', Chris Willman opined that Aguilera's tendency to oversinging is due to the influence of Carey in her vocal abilities, noting "her slightly nasal tone that really only becomes obvious when she's overselling a song".<ref>{{cite magazine|first=Chris|last=Willman|date=11 December 2000|url=https://ew.com/article/2000/12/11/christina-aguileras-oversinging-dangerous-her-career/|title=Christina Aguilera's Oversinging Is Dangerous to Her Career|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|access-date=19 June 2021}}</ref> [[VH1]] writer Alexa Tietjen added that Aguilera "does tend to take it to the extreme at times [...] but Christina's vocal prowess is what's gotten her so far. Love them or hate them, the riffs are a part of who she is as a performer."<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/news/54328/christina-aguilera-is-badass/|title=15 Reasons Why Christina Aguilera Is A Bad B*tch|access-date=July 23, 2021|website=VH1}}</ref>

===Influences===
According to Pier Dominguez, the domestic violence that Aguilera suffered during her childhood directly impacted her developing personality.<ref>{{harvnb|Dominguez|2003|pp=10–11}}</ref> However, the author states that unlike other children who witness the violence at home, she did not show feelings of guilt, emotional disturbance or aggressive behavior towards people; on the contrary, she created an "internal defense mechanism".<ref name="Dominguez11">{{harvnb|Dominguez|2003|p=11}}</ref><ref name="ChildStar"/> On the other hand, Chloé Govan comments that the fact that Aguilera had been a victim of bullying at school made her an introverted and insecure person.<ref>{{harvnb|Govan|2013|pp=13–14}}</ref> Her mother's role was crucial in changing this situation, from whom she learned a "message about self-respect".<ref name="Dominguez7">{{harvnb|Dominguez|2003|p=7}}</ref> Both authors agree that the learning had a strong influence on Aguilera's behavior in the transition to adulthood and exerted an impact on her early number-one singles in career, "[[Genie in a Bottle]]" and "[[What a Girl Wants (Christina Aguilera song)|What a Girl Wants]]" (both from 1999),<ref name="Dominguez7"/><ref>{{harvnb|Govan|2013|p=17}}</ref> the lyrics of which can refer to [[female empowerment]].<ref name="Ranked">{{cite magazine|first=Chris|last=Malone|date=24 August 2019|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/pop/christina-aguilera-debut-album-songs-ranked-8528099/|title=Christina Aguilera's Debut Album Turns 20: All the Tracks Ranked|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=January 21, 2022}}</ref><ref name="Retros">{{cite web|first=Mike|last=Nied|date=31 July 2017|url=https://www.idolator.com/7666889/retrospective-christina-aguilera-genie-in-a-bottle|title=Retrospective: Christina Aguilera's 'Genie in a Bottle'|publisher=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]|access-date=22 June 2021}}</ref>
