Aguilera states that her biggest influence in music was [[Etta James]]: "[She's] my all-time favorite singer [...] I'll still be as raunchy as I wanna be, and I'll have her memory to back me up. She's what I want to be someday".<ref>{{cite web|first=Jennifer|last=Vineyard|date=28 June 2006|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1535359/christina-aguilera-can-die-happy-shes-bonded-with-bad-girl-idol-etta-james/|title=Christina Aguilera Can Die Happy — She's Bonded With 'Bad Girl' Idol Etta James|publisher=[[MTV News]]|access-date=22 June 2021}}</ref> As her first references to sing and perform, Aguilera credits the musical ''[[The Sound of Music]]'' (1959) and its lead actress, [[Julie Andrews]];<ref>{{cite web|first=Craig|last=Rosen|date=29 September 2000|url=http://music.yahoo.com/read/story/12058962|title=Christina Aguilera Climbs Every Mountain for 'My Kind of Christmas'|publisher=[[Yahoo! Music]]|access-date=22 June 2021|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110524205307/http://music.yahoo.com/read/story/12058962|archive-date=24 May 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Lynn|last=Hirschberg|date=1 July 2011|url=https://www.wmagazine.com/story/christina-aguilera-cover-story|title=From the Vaults: The Fall & Rise of Christina Aguilera|work=[[W Magazine]]|access-date=22 June 2021}}</ref>  other of the main inspirations cited throughout her career includes [[Whitney Houston]],<ref name="Behind"/> [[Mariah Carey]],<ref>{{harvnb|Dominguez|2003|p=19}}</ref> [[Michael Jackson]],<ref>{{cite web|first=Becky|last=Bain|date=23 June 2010|url=https://www.idolator.com/5545501/christina-aguilera-jonas-brothers-and-more-remember-michael-jackson|title=Christina Aguilera, Jonas Brothers and More Remember Michael Jackson|publisher=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]|access-date=24 June 2021}}</ref> [[Pearl Bailey]],<ref name="Greenberger27">{{harvnb|Greenberger|2008|p=27}}</ref> [[Beyoncé]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.idolator.com/7914585/christina-aguilera-talks-madonna-beyonce-new-music|title=Christina Aguilera Talks Madonna, Beyoncé & New Music|date=September 17, 2020|website=idolator}}</ref> and the bands [[Red Hot Chili Peppers]] and [[Guns N' Roses]].<ref name="Greenberger27"/><ref>{{harvnb|Dominguez|2003|p=40}}</ref> Furthermore, Aguilera recalls that she started singing her first songs in Spanish during her childhood because of her parents who constantly listened to works by [[Julio Iglesias]].<ref>{{harvnb|Dominguez|2003|p=3}}</ref> Other musical inspirations for Aguilera include [[Chavela Vargas]] and [[Vicente Fernández]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xvDNMbu0mkU|title=Christina Aguilera Interview with Yuriria Sierra – Pa Mis Muchachas, La Fuerza|publisher=[[YouTube]]|access-date=January 27, 2022}}</ref>. Aguilera described her song "[[La Reina (song)|La Reina]]" from ''[[Aguilera (album)|Aguilera]]'' (2022) as a respectful response to Fernández's "[[El Rey (song)|El Rey]]".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://quenoticias.com/entretenimiento/christina-aguilera-la-reina-lyrics/|title=Christina Aguilera lanza "La Reina", un tema escrito por varios artistas venezolanos como Servando Primera ¡Mira la historia detrás de esta colaboración!|website=Que!|date=May 11, 2022 |access-date=October 14, 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://wearemitu.com/latidomusic/la-reina-christina-aguilera/|title=Christina Aguilera's New Single is a Glorious Response to Vicente Fernández's 'El Rey' |website=Mitu|date=May 10, 2022 |access-date=October 14, 2022}}</ref>

In recognition of what she describes as "positive female artists," Aguilera mentioned [[Madonna]] and [[Janet Jackson]] as artistic influences; in 2000, during an interview with ''[[Jam!|Jam! Canoe]]'', she demonstrated her respect for both singers because they have "taken on the stage, the studio and the screen and have been successful in all three [...] artists who aren't afraid to take chances and be daring, experimental and sexy".<ref>{{cite web|first=Stephanie|last=McGrath|date=17 May 2020|url=http://jam.canoe.ca/Music/Artists/A/Aguilera_Christina/2000/05/17/pf-742783.html|title=The Christina Aguilera Interview|publisher=[[Jam!]]|access-date=22 June 2021|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120711195940/http://jam.canoe.ca/Music/Artists/A/Aguilera_Christina/2000/05/17/pf-742783.html|archive-date=July 11, 2012}}</ref> [[Cher]] was also highlighted as one of Aguilera's source of inspiration in career as she remembered that saw her for the first time in the music video for "[[If I Could Turn Back Time]]" (1989), described as a "pivotal moment" that encouraged her as a "woman who's been there, done everything, before everyone else – who had the guts to do it".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://buffalonews.com/entertainment/music/tracing-cher-s-influence-among-pop-divas/article_399bf473-4b58-5d61-a036-c9a6c5dc3780.html|title=Tracing Cher's Influence Among Pop Divas|publisher=[[Buffalo News]]|access-date=22 June 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Krista|last=Smith|date=24 November 2010|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2010/12/cher-201012|title=Forever Cher|publisher=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|access-date=22 June 2021}}</ref> [[Billie Holiday]] and [[Ella Fitzgerald]] were Aguilera's biggest influences on her vocal abilities as a child.<ref>{{harvnb|Govan|2013|p=2017}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Donovan|2010|p=45}}</ref>{{full citation needed|date=May 2022}}

Some of her inspirations were portrayed in her artistic work; during the process of developing of her fifth studio album, ''[[Back to Basics (Christina Aguilera album)|Back to Basics]]'' (2006), Aguilera stated to being influenced by music records from [[Marvin Gaye]], [[Aretha Franklin]], [[Nina Simone]] and [[Otis Redding]].<ref name="OldSoul">{{cite web|first=Jennifer|last=Vineyard|date=4 November 2006|url=http://www.mtv.com/bands/a/aguilera_christina/news_feature_080906/|title=Christina Aguilera's Old Soul|publisher=[[MTV News]]|access-date=22 June 2021|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140805022136/http://www.mtv.com/bands/a/aguilera_christina/news_feature_080906/|archive-date=5 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1531567/for-the-record-quick-news-on-christina-aguilera-jennifer-lopez-snoop-dogg-jessica-simpson-bjork-more/|title=For the Record: Quick News on Christina Aguilera, Jennifer Lopez, Snoop Dogg, Jesica Simpson, Bjork & More|publisher=[[MTV News]]|access-date=22 June 2021}}</ref> In the audiovisual work for "[[Candyman (Christina Aguilera song)|Candyman]]" (2007), she performed three different roles as an allusion to the interpretation of "[[Boogie Woogie Bugle Boy]]" by the group [[The Andrews Sisters]] on a brief appearance in the film ''[[Buck Privates]]'' (1941).<ref>{{cite web|first=Sal|last=Cinquemani|date=2 March 2007|url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/music/christina-aguilera-candyman/|title=Christina Aguilera: 'Candyman'|work=[[Slant Magazine]]|access-date=22 June 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|first=Richard|last=Corliss|date=21 October 2011|url=https://entertainment.time.com/2011/10/24/the-all-time-100-songs/slide/boogie-woogie-bugle-boy-andrews-sisters/|title=100 Greatest Popular Songs: TIME List of Best Music|magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|access-date=22 June 2021}}</ref> Outside the music industry, she mentioned [[Marilyn Monroe]] as a reference, paying tribute to the actress in the music video for "[[Tilt Ya Head Back]]" (2004) and in movie ''[[Burlesque (2010 American film)|Burlesque]]'' (2010) — where she recorded one of Monroe's most popular songs, "[[Diamonds Are a Girl's Best Friend]]", featured in musical ''[[Gentlemen Prefer Blondes (1953 film)|Gentlemen Prefer Blondes]]'' (1953).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sfgate.com/news/article/Nick-accused-of-cheating-on-Jessica-Nelly-2640343.php|title=Nelly Pursuing Aguilera on Video Set|newspaper=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|date=October 28, 2004|access-date=22 June 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcchicago.com/news/national-international/christina-aguilera-and-cher-dish-diva-details-at-the-burlesque-premiere/1862045/|title=Christina Aguilera & Cher Dish Diva Details on 'Burlesque'|publisher=[[NBC Chicago]]|access-date=22 June 2021}}</ref> Furthermore, Aguilera highlighted her inspirations in the art world, declaring to be an appreciator of works by [[Andy Warhol]], [[Roy Lichtenstein]] and [[Banksy]].<ref name="LookBack">{{cite web|first=Jocelyn|last=Vena|date=10 November 2008|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1599011/christina-aguilera-looks-back-and-forward-with-new-lp-next-lp/|title=Christina Aguilera Looks Back - And Forward - with New LP, Next LP|publisher=[[MTV News]]|access-date=22 June 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Matthew|last=Beard|date=6 April 2006|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/this-britain/aguilera-invests-16325000-in-banksy-6104457.html|title=Aguilera Invests £25,000 in Banksy|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|access-date=22 June 2021}}</ref>

===Musical style and themes===
Generally referred to as a [[Pop music|pop]] artist,<ref name="Hiatus">{{cite web|first=Gerrick D.|last=Kennedy|date=2 July 2018|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-ms-christina-aguilera-interview-20180702-story.html|title=Q&A: After a Six-Year Hiatus, Christina Aguilera Finds Her 'Liberation'|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=24 June 2021}}</ref> Aguilera has gone on to experiment with different musical genres throughout her career.<ref name="Remade"/> She explains that she always tries to bring something new in her projects, "experiment with [her] voice" in addition to verbalizing her preference of working with more "obscure" collaborators and that she is not necessarily inclined to contact "the number-one chart-toppers in music" because of their popular demand.<ref name="2008Album">{{cite magazine|first=Mariel|last=Concepcion|date=31 October 2008|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/music-news/hits-set-tees-up-next-christina-aguilera-album-1043616/|title=Hits Set Tees Up Next Christina Aguilera Album|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=January 21, 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|first=Jonathan|last=Cohen|date=11 June 2006|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/music-news/new-aguilera-album-set-for-august-58465/|title=New Aguilera Album Set For August|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=January 21, 2022}}</ref> Reviewing her artistically, Alexis Petridis, columnist from ''[[The Guardian]]'', recognized that her "boldness in reinventing herself" was always "one of her most impressive facets,"<ref>{{cite web|first=Alexis|last=Petridis|date=14 June 2018|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2018/jun/14/christina-aguilera-liberation-review-metoo-makeover-hits-high-and-low-notes|title=Christina Aguilera: Liberation Review – #MeToo Makeover Hits High and Low Notes|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=24 June 2021}}</ref> while Kelefa Sanneh from ''[[The New York Times]]'' highlighted her "decision to snub some of the big-name producers on whom pop stars often rely".<ref>{{cite web|first=Kelefa|last=Sanneh|date=17 August 2006|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/08/17/arts/music/17sann.html|title=Honey They've Shrunk the Pop Stars (but Christina Aguilera Fights On)|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=24 June 2021}}</ref>

Aguilera's first two records, ''Christina Aguilera'' (1999) and ''Mi Reflejo'' (2000), were produced with an influsion of [[teen pop]] and [[dance-pop]], with the latter also referencing her incentive through [[Latin music]].<ref name="Ranked"/><ref>{{cite web|first=Dan|last=Aquilante|date=12 September 2000|url=https://nypost.com/2000/09/12/christinas-a-winner-in-spanish-too/|title=Christina's a Winner in Spanish, Too|publisher=[[New York Post]]|access-date=24 June 2021}}</ref> She showed artistic growth with ''Stripped'' (2002) which was described as "substantive and mature [...] with pleasantly surprising depth," where she showed a range of genres, including [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]], [[hip hop music|hip hop]], [[rock music|rock]], and [[soul music|soul]], and moved away from the teen niche.<ref name="LFReview">{{cite magazine|author=|date=2 November 2002|url=https://www.billboard.com/billboard/reviews/review_displayprint.jsp?vnu_content_id=1749128|title=Reviews & Previews: Stripped|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=24 June 2021|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20021220135838/https://www.billboard.com/billboard/reviews/review_displayprint.jsp?vnu_content_id=1749128|archive-date=20 December 2002}}</ref><ref name="NotAPuppet">{{cite web|first=Kim|last=Stitzel|date=12 February 2002|url=http://www.mtv.com/bands/a/aguilera_christina/news_feature_feb_02/|title=Christina Aguilera: Not Your Puppet|publisher=[[MTV News]]|access-date=24 June 2021|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090305024500/http://www.mtv.com/bands/a/aguilera_christina/news_feature_feb_02/|archive-date=5 March 2009}}</ref> On her fifth studio album, ''Back to Basics'' (2006), Aguilera worked with several producers to create a "throwback with elements of old-school genres combined with a modern-day twist [and] hard-hitting beats".<ref name="B2BMusic"/> [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] from [[AllMusic]] called the project an "artistic statement [...] a little crass and self-centered, but also catchy, exciting and unique".<ref name="BackAllMusic">{{cite web|author=Stephen Thomas Erlewine|date=15 August 2006|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/back-to-basics-mw0000574370|title=Back to Basics: Album Review|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|access-date=24 June 2021}}</ref>

In 2010, Aguilera developed the [[Burlesque (soundtrack)|soundtrack for ''Burlesque'']], whose content was influenced by ''[[Cabaret (1972 film)|Cabaret]]'' (1972) and highlighted several songs that were redone as dance numbers in a fashion similar to ''[[Moulin Rouge!]]'' (2001).<ref>{{cite web|first=Jim|last=Farber|date=25 November 2010|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/music-arts/burlesque-soundtrack-review-christina-aguilera-vocal-athletics-out-diva-cher-chops-article-1.452395|title='Burlesque' Soundtrack Review: Christina Aguilera's Vocal Athletics Can't Out-Diva Cher's Chops|work=[[New York Daily News]]|access-date=24 June 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Michael|last=Fleming|date=15 October 2007|url=https://variety.com/2007/film/news/screen-gems-enlists-antin-for-burlesque-1117974104/|title=Screen Gems Enlists Antin for 'Burlesque'|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|access-date=24 June 2021}}</ref> In the same year, ''Bionic'' saw Aguilera working with producers specialized in [[electronic music]] to create a [[future-pop]] project with elements taken from [[electro (music)|electro]].<ref>{{cite web|first=James|last=Montgomery|date=8 June 2010|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1641082/christina-aguilera-says-bionic-is-about-fun-and-the-future/|title=Christina Aguilera Says Bionic Is About Fun and the Future|publisher=[[MTV News]]|access-date=24 June 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Margaret|last=Wappler|date=7 June 2010|url=https://latimesblogs.latimes.com/music_blog/2010/06/album-review-christina-aguileras-bionic.html|title=Album Review: Christina Aguilera's Bionic|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=24 June 2021}}</ref> Sam Lanksy from [[MTV Buzzworthy]] described it as "forward-thinking and even timeless," and praised its "subversive [and] ambient production".<ref name="LegacyBionic">{{cite web|first=Sam|last=Lansky|date=7 June 2012|url=http://buzzworthy.mtv.com/2012/06/07/christina-aguilera-bionic/|title=The Legacy of 'Bionic': Why Christina Aguilera's Misunderstood Album Was Actually Ahead of Its Time|publisher=[[MTV Buzzworthy]]|access-date=24 June 2021|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120611042933/http://buzzworthy.mtv.com/2012/06/07/christina-aguilera-bionic/|archive-date=11 June 2012}}</ref> Aguilera explored and heavily incorporated [[electro-pop]] on ''Lotus'' (2012).<ref>{{cite web|first=Simon|last=Price|date=11 November 2012|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/album-christina-aguilera-lotus-rca-8303715.html|title=Album: Christina Aguilera, Lotus, RCA|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|access-date=24 June 2021}}</ref> Conversely, in 2018 she contributed with [[Kanye West]] and [[Anderson Paak]] on ''Liberation'', creating an album inspired by R&B and hip-hop styles which she had included in her previous material.<ref>{{cite web|first=Cherise|last=Johnson|date=3 May 2018|url=https://hiphopdx.com/news/id.46709/title.christina-aguilera-is-dropping-an-rbhip-hop-album-with-kanye-west-beatsZ|title=Christina Aguilera Announces 'Liberation' Hip-Hop/R&B Album Featuring Kanye West, 2 Chainz & More|publisher=[[HipHopDX]]|access-date=24 June 2021}}</ref> Aguilera had noted that, "There's nothing like an amazing hip-hop beat. At the end of the day, I am a soul singer [...] singing soulfully is where my core, my root and my heart really is".<ref name="Freedom"/>

Regarding the themes of her music, Aguilera stated that she feels a "sense of responsibility" to reference portions of her personal life so that "people that can relate might not feel as alone in the circumstance".<ref>{{cite magazine|first=David|last=Greenwald|date=13 August 2006|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/music-news/basic-instinct-57547/|title='Basic' Instinct|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=24 June 2021}}</ref> Most of her songs have covered themes of love, motherhood, marriage and fidelity.<ref name="OldSoul"/><ref>{{cite news|first=Mesfin|last=Fekadu|date=7 June 2010|url=http://archive.boston.com/ae/music/articles/2010/06/07/review_aguilera_has_an_identity_crisis_on_new_cd/?rss_id=Boston+Globe+--+CD+reviews|title=Review: Aguilera Has An Identity Crises on New CD|newspaper=Boston.com|publisher=[[The Boston Globe]]|access-date=24 June 2021}}</ref> She has also deal with heavy topics such as [[domestic violence]] and [[abusive relationship]]s.<ref name="Nice">{{cite web|first=Lola|last=Ogunnaike|date=30 July 2006|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/07/30/arts/30ogun.html|title=Christina Aguilera, That Dirrty Girl, Cleans Up Real Nice|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=24 June 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Sal|last=Cinquemani|date=2 November 2002|url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/music/christina-aguilera-stripped/|title=Review: Christina Aguilera, Stripped|work=[[Slant Magazine]]|access-date=24 June 2021}}</ref> Sex has also played a huge part in Aguilera's music.<ref>{{cite web|first=Josh|last=Kun|date=1 December 2012|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Mvzad9KEt0wC&pg=PT18|title=Reviews: Christina Aguilera, Stripped (RCA)|publisher=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|access-date=24 June 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|first=Leah|last=Greenblatt|date=9 June 2010|url=https://ew.com/article/2010/06/09/bionic/|title=Bionic|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|access-date=24 June 2021}}</ref> In an interview with ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'', she stated, "If I want to be sexual, it's for my own appreciation and enjoyment. That's why I like to talk about the fact that sometimes I am attracted to women. I appreciate their femininity and beauty".<ref>{{cite web|first=Eunice|last=Oh|date=11 June 2010|url=https://people.com/celebrity/christina-aguilera-why-im-sometimes-attracted-to-women/|title=Christina Aguilera: 'Why I'm Sometimes Attracted to Women'|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|access-date=24 June 2021}}</ref> Recognized for being feministic in her music,<ref name="PopLifecycle">{{cite news|first=Eric|last=Solomon|date=30 July 2018|url=https://www.popmatters.com/christina-aguilera-2591013516.html|title=Is There Life Beyond the Pop Lifecycle for Christina Aguilera?|newspaper=[[PopMatters]]|access-date=24 June 2021}}</ref> Aguilera denounced the [[double standard]] for the first time in "[[Can't Hold Us Down]]" (2002),<ref>{{cite web|first=Jason|last=Heller|date=15 March 2010|url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/a-soundproofed-room-of-ones-own-17-wellintended-ye%2C39169/|title=17 Well-Intended Yet Misguided Feminist Anthems|publisher=[[The A.V. Club]]|access-date=24 June 2021|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100403042138/http://www.avclub.com/articles/a-soundproofed-room-of-ones-own-17-wellintended-ye%2C39169/|archive-date=3 April 2010}}</ref> explaining that men are applauded for their sexual behaviors, while women who behave in a similar fashion are disdained.<ref>{{harvnb|Railton|Watson|2011|page=88}}</ref> Writing for ''The Guardian'', Hermione Hoby noted that she "incites a sisterly spirit of collaboration [and] not shy of the odd feministic declaration herself".<ref>{{cite web|first=Hermione|last=Hoby|date=13 June 2010|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2010/jun/13/christina-aguilera-interview-bionic|title=Christina Aguilera: 'I'm a Very Sexual Person by Nature'|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=24 June 2021}}</ref>

==Image==
Aguilera has reinvented her public image numerous times during her career.<ref>{{cite web|author=Joey Guerra|date=20 February 2007|url=https://blog.chron.com/handstamp/2007/02/christina-aguilera-claims-her-pop-throne/|title=Christina Aguilera Claims Her Pop Throne|publisher=[[Houston Chronicle]]|access-date=5 July 2021|archive-date=February 10, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150210190839/http://blog.chron.com/newswatch/2011/04/ktru-station-off-air-but-still-broadcasting-online/|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Guy Trebay|date=20 March 2013|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/03/21/fashion/justin-timberlake-is-all-dressed-up.html|title=Justin Timberlake Is All Dressed Up|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=5 July 2021}}</ref> Early in her career, she was marketed as a [[bubblegum pop]] singer due to the genre's high financial return in the late 1990s,<ref name="ChildStar"/> becoming a [[teen idol]].<ref name="Chaos">{{cite web|author=Monica Eng|date=16 January 2000|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2000-01-16-0001160301-story.html|title=Pop Idol's Store Visit Cut Short By Chaos|publisher=[[Chicago Tribune]]|access-date=5 July 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Jon Matsumoto|date=16 December 2002|url=https://www.bmi.com/news/entry/20021217christina_aguilera_christina_aguilera_a_gifted_artist_with_an_in|title=Christina Aguilera: A Gifted Artist with an Independent Vision|publisher=[[Broadcast Music, Inc.]]|access-date=5 July 2021}}</ref> ''[[Stereogum]]'' wrtier Tom Breihan noted that Aguilera "thought of herself primarily as a [...] young [[Mariah Carey]]-type, but her [[Artists and repertoire|A&R]] rep [[Ron Fair]] had instead sent [her] into the pop zeitgeist" of the times.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stereogum.com/2194221/the-number-ones-christina-aguileras-what-a-girl-wants/columns/the-number-ones/|title=The Number Ones: Christina Aguilera's "What A Girl Wants"|access-date=August 17, 2022|website=Stereogum|date=July 29, 2022 }}</ref> However, she was accused of cultivating a sexual image, attracting criticism regarding her revealing clothes;<ref name="PostG">{{cite web|author=Ed Masley|date=27 August 2000|url=http://old.post-gazette.com/magazine/20000827aguilera2.asp|title=Concert Review: Aguilera Wows 'Em With Awe-Inspiring Vocals|publisher=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]|access-date=5 July 2021}}</ref> in an interview with [[MTV News]], [[Debbie Gibson]] accused her of "influencing girls out there wearing less and less", considering that "she lives and breathes the sexual image".<ref>{{cite web|author=Jon Wiederhorn|date=23 August 2001|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1448367/deborah-gibson-britney-twinkles-christina-rankles/|title=Deborah Gibson: Britney Twinkles, Christina Rankles|publisher=[[MTV News]]|access-date=5 July 2021}}</ref> In response to negative comments, Aguilera stated: "Just because I have a certain image, everyone wants me to be this role model. But nobody is perfect, and nobody can live up to that".<ref>{{cite web|author=Neil Strauss|date=6 July 2000|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/christina-aguilera-the-hit-girl-190789/|title=Christina Aguilera: The Hit Girl|publisher=[[Rolling Stone]]|access-date=5 July 2021}}</ref> Furthermore, her music and image received comparisons to [[Britney Spears]].<ref name="FastTrack"/><ref name="RicherSound">{{cite web|author=Lola Ogunnaike|date=28 July 2006|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/07/28/arts/28iht-chris.2322180.html|title=Aguilera Aims for Edgy, but Richer, Sound|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=5 July 2021}}</ref> [[David Browne (journalist)|David Browne]], author from ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'', noted that she was "a good girl pretending to be bad" when compared to Spears' music and image.<ref>{{cite web|author=David Browne|date=19 May 2000|url=https://ew.com/article/2000/05/19/oops-i-did-it-again/|title=Oops!... I Did It Again|publisher=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|access-date=5 July 2021|archive-date=October 28, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201028205130/http://www.ew.com/article/2000/05/19/oops-i-did-it-again/|url-status=dead}}</ref> In contrast, Christopher J. Farley of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' considered her a more impressive artist than Spears.<ref name="Time2000">{{cite magazine|author=Christopher J. Farley|date=27 February 2000|url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,39950,00.html|title=Christina Aguilera|magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|access-date=5 July 2021}}</ref> Megan Turner from ''[[New York Post]]'' compared the "battle" between both artists in the media with the previous one between [[The Beatles]] and [[The Rolling Stones]]; however, she highlighted the difference in them, opining that "while Britney has a va-va-voom sexuality [...] Aguilera had charm and a youthful appeal".<ref>{{cite web|author=Megan Turner|date=20 January 2000|url=https://nypost.com/2000/01/20/battle-of-the-bubblegum-divas-can-christina-aguilera-oust-britney-spears-as-pop-musics-reigning-teen-queen/|title=Battle of the Bubblegum Divas: Can Christina Aguilera Oust Britney Spears As Pop Music Reigning Teen Queen?|publisher=[[New York Post]]|access-date=5 July 2021}}</ref> ''[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]]'' writer James Tison labelled Aguilera a "[[diva]]" saying she "mastered being one in the best way possible".<ref name="BustleAguilera1">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bustle.com/articles/84356-7-times-christina-aguilera-was-a-diva-in-the-best-way-possible|title=Christina Aguilera's 7 Best Diva Moments|access-date=July 28, 2021|website=Bustle}}</ref> He added that "one of her best diva qualities is her willingness to embrace her own sexuality".<ref name="BustleAguilera1"/>
[[File:Aguilera Madame Tussauds.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Wax statue of Aguilera at the [[Madame Tussauds]], localized in London]]
In 2002, Aguilera introduced her [[alter ego]] Xtina, for which she adopted increasingly provocative and extravagant looks.<ref name="SMHStripped">{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/music/aguilera-sheds-teen-pop-image-alongside-clothes-20021030-gdfrtl.html|title=Aguilera Sheds Teen Pop Image, Alongside Clothes|date=October 30, 2002|publisher=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|access-date=5 July 2021}}</ref> During this period, she dyed her hair black, debuted body piercings and photographed nude for several publications.<ref name="GotDirty">{{cite web|author=ABC Staff|date=6 January 2006|url=https://abcnews.go.com/2020/story?id=123689&page=1|title=How Christina Aguilera Got 'Dirty'|publisher=[[ABC News]]|access-date=5 July 2021}}</ref> While analyzing her new visual, ''[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]'' and ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazines wrote that her new clothes echoed as if she were participating in the ''[[Girls Gone Wild (franchise)|Girls Gone Wild]]'' franchise.<ref name="Nowhere">{{cite web|author=Sophie Wilkinson|date=26 October 2017|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/d3dpby/christina-aguilera-stripped-gender-equality-15-anniversary|title=15 Years After Christina Aguilera's 'Stripped', We're Still Nowhere Near Gender Equality|publisher=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]|access-date=5 July 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Jancee Dunn|date=5 November 2002|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/stripped-182419/|title=Stripped: Album Review|publisher=[[Rolling Stone]]|access-date=5 July 2021}}</ref> On the other hand, she reinforced her new visual direction by dressing up as a nun during a performance of "[[Dirrty]]" (2002) accompanied by a choir and undressed to reveal what she would wear underneath to serving as the host of the [[2003 MTV Europe Music Awards]].<ref name="XRated">{{cite web|author=Auslan Cramb|date=7 November 2003|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1446089/X-rated-Christina-puts-on-a-dirrty-show-for-MTV.html |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220110/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1446089/X-rated-Christina-puts-on-a-dirrty-show-for-MTV.html |archive-date=January 10, 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live|title=X-Rated Christina Puts on a Dirrty Show for MTV|publisher=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|access-date=5 July 2021}}{{cbignore}}</ref> In a review of her persona, author [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] of [[AllMusic]] opined that Aguilera reached "maturity with transparent sexuality and pounding sounds of nightclubs".<ref>{{cite web|author=Stephen Thomas Erlewine|date=18 November 2003|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/in-the-zone-mw0000320439|title=In the Zone|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|access-date=5 July 2021}}</ref> Writing for ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', Adam White was more positive about her image and recognized that her "embracing of an overtly sexual image in the wake of adolescent stardom was a tried and tested route to adult success".<ref name="TurnedPop">{{cite news|author=Adam White|date=9 November 2019|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/music/artists/get-little-naughty-christina-aguilera-turned-pop-dirrty/ |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220110/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/music/artists/get-little-naughty-christina-aguilera-turned-pop-dirrty/ |archive-date=January 10, 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live|title=Get a Little Naughty: How Christina Aguilera Turned Pop Dirrty|newspaper=The Telegraph|publisher=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|access-date=5 July 2021}}{{cbignore}}</ref>

Under a new persona named Baby Jane — a reference to ''[[What Ever Happened to Baby Jane? (film)|What Ever Happened to Baby Jane?]]'' (1962) — Aguilera again transformed her public image in 2006;<ref>{{cite web|author=Jennifer Vineyard|date=19 June 2006|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1534591/aint-no-other-man-video-has-christina-singing-the-blues/|title='Ain't No Other Man' Video Has Christina Singing the Blues|publisher=[[MTV News]]|access-date=5 July 2021}}</ref> sticking to the platinum blonde in her hair, she started to dress inspired by actresses from [[Classic Hollywood cinema|Old Hollywood]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Hazel Cills|date=4 June 2013|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/rzzgxr/christina-aguilera-the-style-evolution-of-a-diva|title=Christina Aguilera: The Style Evolution of a Diva|publisher=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]|access-date=5 July 2021}}</ref> However, in 2010, her new looks were highlighted in the international media for comparisons with those used by [[Lady Gaga]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Leah Greenblatt|date=18 May 2010|url=https://ew.com/article/2010/05/18/christina-aguilera-lady-gaga-feud/|title=Christina Aguilera's Lady Gaga Talk: For Real or for Show?|publisher=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|access-date=5 July 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Jocelyn Vena|date=21 April 2010|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1637525/christina-aguilera-on-lady-gaga-comparisons-my-work-speaks-for-itself/|title=Christina Aguilera On Lady Gaga Comparisons: 'My Work Speaks for Itself'|publisher=[[MTV News]]|access-date=5 July 2021}}</ref> After gaining weight in 2012, she was criticized by several publications;<ref>{{cite web|author=Sugey Palomares|date=29 October 2012|url=http://www.latina.com/entertainment/adam-levine-christina-aguilera-weight-gain|title=Adam Levine Defends Christina Aguilera Over Weight Gain Criticism|publisher=[[Latina (magazine)|Latina]]|access-date=5 July 2021|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121101035734/http://www.latina.com/entertainment/adam-levine-christina-aguilera-weight-gain|archive-date=1 November 2012}}</ref> in the following year, she received favorable media attention after a significant weight loss.<ref>{{cite web|author=Chiderah Monde|date=25 November 2013|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/gossip/american-music-awards-2013-christina-aguilera-stuns-red-carpet-article-1.1528131|title=American Music Awards 2013: Christina Aguilera Stuns On Red Carpet a Year After Receiving Criticism for Last Year's Look|work=[[New York Daily News]]|access-date=5 July 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/christina-aguilera-dishes-on-weight-loss-secret|title=Christina Aguilera Dishes on Weight Loss|date=February 17, 2017|publisher=[[Fox News]]|access-date=5 July 2021}}</ref> In the March 2018 edition of ''[[Paper (magazine)|Paper]]'', she appeared without makeup and [[photo manipulation|photographic manipulation]], receiving praise and attracting attention to artists who would pose the same way on their social media.<ref>{{cite web|author=Katie Baille|date=27 March 2018|url=https://metro.co.uk/2018/03/27/christina-aguilera-ditches-makeup-hordes-celebs-inspiring-us-go-makeup-free-7420087/|title=Christina Aguilera Ditches Makeup, And So Have All of These Celebs|publisher=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]|access-date=5 July 2021}}</ref>

Aguilera has been cited as a [[sex symbol]].<ref name="SexSymbol"/><ref name="Remade">{{cite web|author=Kelefa Sanneh|date=8 September 2002|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/09/08/arts/the-new-season-music-idol-returns-her-image-remade.html|title=The New Season/Music: Idol Returns, Her Image Remade|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=5 July 2021}}</ref> Through [[VH1]], she was included in the list of the sexiest entertainment artists in 2002 and 2013;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/shows/dyn/the_greatest/61932/episode_wildcard.jhtml?wildcard=/shows/dynamic/includes/wildcards/the_greatest/sexiest_list_full.jhtml&event_id=862758&start=21|title=100 Sexiest Artists|publisher=[[VH1]]|access-date=5 July 2021|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060831174054/http://www.vh1.com/shows/dyn/the_greatest/61932/episode_wildcard.jhtml?wildcard=%2Fshows%2Fdynamic%2Fincludes%2Fwildcards%2Fthe_greatest%2Fsexiest_list_full.jhtml&event_id=862758&start=21|archive-date=August 31, 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/news/1187/vh1-100-sexiest-artists-complete-list/|title=VH1's 100 Sexiest Artists|publisher=[[VH1]]|access-date=5 July 2021}}</ref> in publications from ''[[FHM]]'' and ''[[Complex Networks|Complex]]'', she received similar honors in 2004 and 2012, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|author=Rachel Clun|date=26 March 2004|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/music/whos-the-sexiest-aussie-20040326-gdim4e.html|title=Who's the Sexiest Aussie?|publisher=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|access-date=5 July 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Lauren Nostro|date=10 December 2012|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2012/12/the-100-hottest-female-singers-of-all-time/christina-aguilera|title=The 100 Hottest Female Singers of All Time|publisher=[[Complex Networks|Complex]]|access-date=5 July 2021}}</ref> In 2003, she was chosen as the sexiest woman of the year by ''[[Maxim (magazine)|Maxim]]'', stamping the cover of the best-selling issue of the magazine's history.<ref>{{cite web|author=Adrianne Palicki|date=24 April 2007|url=http://www.maxim.com/girls-of-maxim/christina-aguilera|title=Girls of Maxim|publisher=[[Maxim (magazine)|Maxim]]|access-date=5 July 2021|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120301161931/http://www.maxim.com/girls-of-maxim/christina-aguilera|archive-date=1 March 2012}}</ref> Furthermore, she was mentioned as one of the most beautiful people in the world in 2003 and 2007 in ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' editions.<ref>{{cite web|author=Michelle Tauber|date=12 May 2003|url=https://people.com/archive/cover-story-50-most-beautiful-people-vol-59-no-18/|title=50 Most Beautiful People|publisher=[[People (magazine)|People]]|access-date=5 July 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Caitlin Johnson|date=25 April 2007|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/people-magazine-names-100-most-beautiful/|title=People Magazine Names 100 Most Beautiful|publisher=[[CBS News]]|access-date=5 July 2021}}</ref> Aguilera also is recognized a [[gay icon]];<ref>{{cite encyclopedia
 | last =Pinfold
 | first =Michael
 | editor-last=Gerstner
 | editor-first=David A.
 | title =Christina Aguilera
 | encyclopedia = Routledge International Encyclopedia of Queer Culture
 | edition= 1
 | pages =16
 | publisher =[[Routledge]]
 | language =English
 | date =2006
 | url =https://www.google.com/books/edition/Routledge_International_Encyclopedia_of/XS_SnVPixE8C
 | isbn = 9780415306515
 | access-date = 2022-06-15}}</ref><ref name="LGBTQCommunity">{{cite web|author=Lamar Dawson|date=14 December 2017|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/music-news/christina-aguilera-lgbtq-community-8070309/|title=Christina Aguilera: 5 Times She Showed Up for the LGBTQ Community|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=January 1, 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Fan Zhong|date=16 May 2018|url=https://www.wmagazine.com/story/christina-aguilera-album-liberation-fall-in-line|title=Christina Aguilera Is Back at Last, and She Has Got Something to Say|publisher=[[W (magazine)|W]]|access-date=5 July 2021}}</ref> in 2019, she was awarded by the [[Human Rights Campaign]] for using her "platform to share a message of hope and inspiration to those who have been marginalized [...] bringing greater visibility to the LGBTQ community".<ref>{{cite web|author=Trilby Beresford|date=7 March 2019|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/music-news/christina-aguilera-receive-equality-award-lgbtq-advocacy-1193132/|title=Christina Aguilera to Receive Equality Award for LGBTQ Advocacy|publisher=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|access-date=5 July 2021}}</ref> Her fashion sense has also attracted media attention throughout her artistic life;<ref>{{cite web|author=Sarah Toscano|date=14 October 2019|url=https://www.elitedaily.com/p/10-of-christina-aguileras-most-iconic-outfits-that-are-beautiful-no-matter-what-they-say-18812667|title=10 of Christina Aguilera's Most Iconic Outfits|publisher=[[Elite Daily]]|access-date=5 July 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Amy Odell|date=24 September 2020|url=https://www.cosmopolitan.com/style-beauty/fashion/news/g5694/vintage-christina-aguilera/|title=50 Christina Aguilera Fashion Moments You Forgot You Were Obsessed With|publisher=[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]|access-date=5 July 2021}}</ref> [[Jon Caramanica]], journalist from ''[[The New York Times]]'', concluded that "Aguilera will be remembered for her glamour and her scandalous take on femme-pop",<ref name="ChangedJud">{{cite web|author=Jon Caramanica|date=17 September 2012|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/09/18/arts/music/how-christina-aguilera-changed-judging-of-reality-tv-music.html|title=How Christina Aguilera Changed Judging of Reality TV Music|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=5 July 2021}}</ref> while Janelle Okwodu from ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'' noted that she "has never been afraid to take a fashion risk [and] has filled her videos with jaw-dropping styles and risqué runway looks".<ref>{{cite web|author=Janelle Okwodu|date=18 September 2018|url=https://www.vogue.com/article/christina-aguilera-gareth-pugh-spring-2020-party-video|title=How Christina Aguilera Brought Down the House at London Fashion Week|publisher=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]|access-date=5 July 2021}}</ref> Following her appearance at [[New York Fashion Week]] in 2018, ''[[Dazed]]'' named her one of the most stylish people of the year.<ref>{{cite web|author=Emma Elizabeth Davidson|date=11 December 2018|url=https://www.dazeddigital.com/fashion/article/42550/1/most-stylish-people-2018-jeff-goldblum-jonah-hill-asap-rocky-bella-hadid-xtina|title=The 20 Most Stylish People of 2018|publisher=[[Dazed]]|access-date=5 July 2021}}</ref>

Aguilera has called her fans "fighters", which has become the nickname used on social media to refer to her fanbase.<ref name="Overdue"/><ref name="LGBTQCommunity"/> She is one of the most popular musicians on [[Twitter]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/datablog/2013/apr/19/twitter-music-app-100-most-followed-musicians|title=The 100 Most Popular Musicians on Twitter|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=April 19, 2013|access-date=5 July 2021}}</ref> with approximately 17 million followers,<ref>{{cite web|author=Alaa Elassar|date=25 August 2019|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/08/25/entertainment/christina-aguilera-20th-anniversary-debut-album-trnd/index.html|title=Christina Aguilera Celebrates the 20th Anniversary of Her Debut Album|publisher=[[CNN]]|access-date=5 July 2021}}</ref> and was one of the most searched artists in the world in 2002, 2004, and 2010 through [[Google]].<ref>
{{cite web|url=https://trends.google.com/trends/yis/2004/GLOBAL/|title=Google Trends 2004|access-date=5 July 2021}}<br>
{{cite web|url=https://trends.google.com/trends/yis/2002/GLOBAL/|title=Google Trends 2002|access-date=5 July 2021}}<br>
{{cite web|author=Liz Heron|date=6 May 2010|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Technology/50-popular-women-web-google-search-results/story?id=10573331|title=50 Most Popular Women on the Web, Per Google Search Results|publisher=[[ABC News]]|access-date=5 July 2021}}</ref> She was also one of the most popular searches in 2003 by [[Yahoo! Search]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://search.yahoo.com/top2003|title=Top Yahoo! Searches 2003|publisher=[[Yahoo!]]|access-date=5 July 2021|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040113043600/http://search.yahoo.com/top2003|archive-date=13 January 2004}}</ref> When she became a coach on ''[[The Voice (American TV series)|The Voice]]'', Aguilera became one of the [[List of highest paid American television stars|highest-paid American television stars]];<ref>{{cite web|author=Sharon Waxman|date=13 May 2013|url=https://www.thewrap.com/christina-aguilera-returning-voice-17-million-exclusive-91361/|title=Cee Lo Green Nears Deal to Join Christina Aguilera on Season 5 of 'The Voice', Says NBC Exec|publisher=[[TheWrap]]|access-date=5 July 2021}}</ref> in 2011, it was reported that she would receive $225,000 per episode, as well as $12 million per season in 2013, $12.5 million in 2014, and $17 million in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|author=CBS News Staff|date=10 August 2011|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/pictures/tv-stars-salaries/16/|title=TV Stars' Salaries|publisher=[[CBS News]]|access-date=5 July 2021}}<br>
{{cite web|author=Shirley Halperin|date=14 May 2013|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/music-news/christina-aguilera-could-snag-12-million-for-voice-return-1561434/|title=Christina Aguilera Could Snag $12 Million for 'Voice' Return|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=January 21, 2022}}<br>
{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/the-23-highest-paid-reality-tv-stars-2014-1|title=The 23 Highest-Paid Reality TV Stars|publisher=[[Business Insider]]|access-date=5 July 2021}}<br>
{{cite web|author=Jethro Nededog|date=6 June 2016|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/reality-tv-stars-salaries-2016-6|title=Reality TV Stars' Salaries|publisher=[[Business Insider]]|access-date=5 July 2021}}</ref> In 2007, ''[[Forbes (magazine)|Forbes]]'' included her on its list of richest women in entertainment with an estimated net worth estimated of $60 million,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/2007/01/17/richest-women-entertainment-tech-media-cz_lg_richwomen07_0118womenstars_lander.html?sh=47f97edcd9c7|title=The 20 Richest Women in Entertainment|work=[[Forbes (magazine)|Forbes]]|access-date=5 July 2021}}</ref> and estimated that she had earned $20 million that year.<ref>{{cite web|author=Dorothy Pomerantz|date=29 January 2008|url=https://www.forbes.com/2008/01/28/music-madonna-hollywood-biz-cz_dp_0129musicwomen_slide.html?sh=7068b1f61105|title=The Top-Earning Women in Music|work=[[Forbes (magazine)|Forbes]]|access-date=5 July 2021}}</ref> In 2021, [[Yahoo! Finance]] estimated Aguilera's fortune at $160 million.<ref name="NetWorth">{{cite web|author=Gabrielle Olya|date=7 February 2021|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/j-lo-katy-perry-more-200033524.html|title=J.Lo, Katy Perry and More: The Net Worths of the Super Bowl's Richest Halftime Performers|publisher=[[Yahoo! Finance]]|access-date=5 July 2021}}</ref>

==Legacy==
Various music journalists and authors have noted Aguilera's legacy in [[show business|entertainment industry]]<ref name="Overdue"/><ref name="PopScene">{{cite web|author=Jeff Benjamin|date=29 October 2017|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/pop/christina-aguilera-stripped-anniversary-influence-8014854/|title=How Christina Aguilera's 'Stripped' Album Is Influencing the Pop Scene 15 Years Later|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=January 21, 2022}}</ref><ref name="TurnedPop"/> and deemed her as one of the greatest artists in the [[pop music]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Gregory Hicks|date=25 January 2012|url=https://www.michigandaily.com/arts/step-salon-christina-aquilera?page=0,0|title=Step into the Salon: Christina Aguilera's Controversial Pop Legend Status|publisher=[[The Michigan Daily]]|access-date=26 July 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Dave Quinn|date=13 September 2018|url=https://people.com/music/christina-aguilera-open-to-duet-with-britney-spears/|title=Christina Aguilera Open to Duet with Britney Spears|publisher=[[People (magazine)|People]]|access-date=26 July 2021}}</ref> In 2004, she was listed as one of the most influential people in music market according ''[[The Independent]]'',<ref>{{cite web|author=Ciar Byrne|date=29 June 2004|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/features/the-music-industrys-100-most-influential-people-5355761.html|title=The Music Industry's 100 Most Influential People|work=[[The Independent]]|access-date=26 July 2021}}</ref> and was cited as the eight greatest woman in the phonographic industry by [[VH1]].<ref name="VH1Women">{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/news/1238/the-100-greatest-women-in-music/|title=The 100 Greatest Women In Music|publisher=[[VH1]]|access-date=26 July 2021}}</ref> Early in her career, Aguilera was labeled as a [[teen idol]],<ref name="Chaos"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/shows/the_greatest/episode.jhtml?episodeID=67297|title=The 50 Greatest Teen Idols|publisher=[[VH1]]|access-date=26 July 2021|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120209143618/http://www.vh1.com/shows/the_greatest/episode.jhtml?episodeID=67297|archive-date=9 February 2012}}</ref> and has been cited as one of the artists who revived [[teen pop]] in the late nineties;<ref>{{cite web|author=Steve Huey|date=January 2008|url=http://www.mtv.com/music/artist/aguilera_christina/artist.jhtml#bio|title=Christina Aguilera: Full Biography|publisher=[[MTV]]|access-date=26 July 2021|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080110035013/http://www.mtv.com/music/artist/aguilera_christina/artist.jhtml#bio|archive-date=10 January 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Evan Serpick|date=February 2010|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/artists/christina-aguilera/biography|title=Christina Aguilera: Bio|publisher=[[Rolling Stone]]|access-date=26 July 2021|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120208215427/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/artists/christina-aguilera/biography|archive-date=8 February 2012}}</ref> ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine stated that she was "pioneer [in] a different type of teen stardom", crediting her vocal ability as responsible for the phenomenon.<ref name="Time2000"/> Since then, she was named as one of the greatest singers in contemporary pop music;<ref>{{cite web|author=Joshua David Stein|date=16 May 2010|url=https://www.out.com/entertainment/music/2010/05/16/christina-aguilera-reclaims-fame|title=Christina Aguilera Reclaims the Fame|publisher=[[Out (magazine)|Out]]|access-date=26 July 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Mark Sundstrom|date=17 August 2016|url=http://www.fuse.tv/2016/08/christina-aguilera-back-to-basics-best-performances|title=10 Best Christina Aguilera Performances from the 'Back to Basics' Era|publisher=[[Fuse TV]]|access-date=26 July 2021|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822032146/http://www.fuse.tv/2016/08/christina-aguilera-back-to-basics-best-performances|archive-date=22 August 2016}}</ref> by [[MTV]], she was cited as one of the best voices in music since eighties,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com:80/onair/mtv2/22_greatest/|title=22 Greatest Voices in Music|publisher=[[MTV]]|access-date=26 July 2021|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030122093658/http://www.mtv.com:80/onair/mtv2/22_greatest/|archive-date=22 January 2003}}</ref> while ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' and ''[[Consequence of Sound]]'' included her in their lists of greatest singers of all time.<ref name="RS100"/><ref name="CoS100">{{cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2016/10/the-100-greatest-singers-of-all-time/full-post/|title=The 100 Greatest Singers of All Time|date=October 11, 2016|publisher=[[Consequence of Sound]]|access-date=26 July 2021}}</ref> In 2013, ''[[Latina (magazine)|Latina]]'' honored her as the best vocalist of Latin origin in history.<ref>{{cite web|author=Sugey Palomares|date=8 February 2013|url=http://www.latina.com/entertainment/music/50-best-latino-singers-all-time|title=The 50 Best Latin Singers and Pop Stars of All Time|publisher=[[Latina (magazine)|Latina]]|access-date=26 July 2021|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170702121133/http://www.latina.com/entertainment/music/50-best-latino-singers-all-time|archive-date=2 July 2017}}</ref> With the recognition of her vocal ability and influence in the music industry, she has been referred in media with the titles of "[[Honorific titles in popular music|Princess of Pop]]"<ref name="Nice"/><ref>{{cite web|author=Gerrick D. Kennedy|date=23 August 2013|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-xpm-2013-aug-23-la-et-ms-mtv-video-music-awards-30-memorable-moments-20130823-story.html|title=MTV Video Music Awards: 30 Moments That Make It a Can't-Miss Event|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=26 July 2021}}</ref> and "[[Honorific titles in popular music|Voice of a Generation]]".<ref name="VOAG"/><ref name="VOAG1"/><ref name="3Arena"/>
[[File:Xtina star walk of fame.jpg|thumb|upright|right|Aguilera's star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]], received in 2010]]
Upon launching her music career in the late nineties, Aguilera was cited as one of the artists who shaped the "Latin explosion",<ref>{{cite web|author=Agustin Gurza|date=15 August 2004|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2004-aug-15-ca-gurza15-story.html|title=1999 Was the Year of the Latin Explosion|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=26 July 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Jennifer Mota|date=14 May 2019|url=https://peopleenespanol.com/chica/remember-the-u-s-latin-music-wave-at-the-turn-the-millennium-here-it-is/|title=Remember the U.S. Latin Music Wave at the Turn of the Millennium?|publisher=[[People en Español]]|access-date=26 July 2021}}</ref> in addition to contributed to the [[Latin American music in the United States#2000s Latin pop boom|Latin pop boom in American music]] in early of the century.<ref>{{cite web|author=Lucas Villa|date=26 June 2020|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/latin/thalia-paulina-rubio-christina-aguilera-talk-landmark-2000-albums-9408858/|title=Thalia, Paulina Rubio, Christina Aguilera Open Up About Landmark 2000 Albums: Exclusive|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=January 21, 2022}}</ref> Considered one of the greatest artists of the 2000s,<ref name="20YXtina">{{cite web|author=Richard S. He|date=4 May 2018|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/pop/christina-aguilera-career-essay-liberation-8454536/|title=20 Years of Xtina: How She Found, Lost and Liberated Her Voice Again|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=January 21, 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Jeremy Helligar|date=15 June 2018|url=https://variety.com/2018/music/opinion/can-christina-aguilera-reclaim-her-rightful-place-on-the-pop-star-star-throne-1202848126/|title=Can Christina Aguilera Reclaim Her (Rightful) Place as Top Pop Star?|publisher=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|access-date=26 July 2021}}</ref> she has been classified between the main references of the [[Millennials]];<ref>{{cite web|author=Keith Caulfield|date=8 August 2017|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/pop/pop-samples-rihanna-camila-cabello-90s-00s-resurgence-7896826/|title=The Turn-of-the-Century Pop Resurgence: Are Late-'90s/Early-'00s Samples About to be Everywhere?|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=January 21, 2022}}</ref> writing for ''[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]'' magazine, Wanna Thompson analyzed her impact in the turn of the century, stating that alongside [[Britney Spears]], "Aguilera dominated mainstream pop-related discussions. [Her] perfectly packaged music and looks appealed to tweens and teens who wanted to be like the pretty, chart-topping pop stars plastered everywhere".<ref>{{cite web|author=Wanna Thompson|date=16 November 2018|url=https://www.vice.com/en/article/nepnqq/gwen-stefani-cultural-appropriation-legacy|title=Gwen Stefani Should Have Been Canceled a Long Time Ago|publisher=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]|access-date=26 July 2021}}</ref> The commercial success of her first projects as a [[bubblegum pop]] singer caused an effect that influenced record labels to invest in new artists who attracted the same youthful appeal, catapulting names like [[Jessica Simpson]] and [[Mandy Moore]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Rich Cohen|date=4 May 2009|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/culture/2009/06/jessica-simpson200906|title=The Jessica Simpson Question|publisher=[[Vanity Fair (magazines)|Vanity Fair]]|access-date=26 July 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Jess Cohen|date=25 July 2018|url=https://www.eonline.com/news/954879/mandy-moore-reflects-on-her-early-days-in-pop-music-alongside-britney-spears|title=Mandy Moore Reflects on Early Days in Pop Music|publisher=[[E! News]]|access-date=26 July 2021}}</ref>

Critics also highlighted the impact of her work in [[popular culture]]; while ''[[Stripped (Christina Aguilera album)|Stripped]]'' (2002) was cited as "the blueprint for divas making the transition from teen idol to adult pop star",<ref>{{cite web|author=Mike Nied|date=24 October 2017|url=https://www.idolator.com/7670364/impact-christina-aguilera-stripped|title=Reflecting On the Impact of Christina Aguilera|publisher=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]|access-date=26 July 2021}}</ref> Aguilera is credited for "paving the way for a generation of pop singers".<ref name="3Arena">{{cite web|author=Tony Clayton-Lea|date=3 November 2019|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/music/christina-aguilera-at-3arena-dublin-everything-you-need-to-know-1.4066866|title=Christina Aguilera at 3Arena, Dublin: Everything You Need to Know|publisher=[[The Irish Times]]|access-date=26 July 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Eddie Fu|date=15 June 2018|url=https://genius.com/a/how-christina-aguileras-evolution-paved-the-way-for-a-generation-of-pop-singers|title=How Christina Aguilera's Evolution Paved the Way for a Generation of Pop Singers|publisher=[[Genius (website)|Genius]]|access-date=26 July 2021}}</ref> [[Jeff Benjamin Billboard|Jeff Benjamin]] from ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' stated that the album explored a "process of self-identification and declaration still influencing today's mainstream scene", in addition to "how of today's biggest pop stars have followed a similar path, exploring and incorporating these strategies into their careers".<ref name="PopScene"/> In 2007, [[Christina Aguilera (album)|her self-titled debut album]] was added to the definitive list from [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]], being recognized as one of the "history's most influential and popular albums".<ref>{{cite web|author=Andrew Moore|date=May 2007|url=https://www.rockhall.com/pressroom/definitive-200|title=Definitive 200|publisher=[[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]]|access-date=26 July 2021|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070510104154/https://www.rockhall.com/pressroom/definitive-200|archive-date=10 May 2007}}</ref> Since then, Aguilera and her work have influenced various recording artists including [[Ariana Grande]],<ref>{{cite tweet|user=arianagrande|number=27637810617913344|title=My biggest musical influences are Imogen Heap, Christina Aguilera, MJ and Rihanna}}</ref> [[Ava Max]],<ref>{{cite news|author=Lucy Mapstone|date=11 January 2019|url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/life/features/ava-max-my-parents-left-albania-in-1990-and-lived-in-a-church-in-paris-for-a-whole-year-37700264.html|title=Ava Max: My Parents Left Albania in 1990 and Lived in a Church in Paris for a Whole Year|newspaper=Belfasttelegraph|publisher=[[Belfast Telegraph]]|access-date=26 July 2021}}</ref> [[Becky G]],<ref>{{cite web|author=Zach Seemayer|date=November 18, 2021|url=https://www.wusa9.com/article/entertainment/entertainment-tonight/2021-latin-grammys-becky-g-says-performing-with-christina-aguilera-is-a-full-circle-moment-exclusive/603-8e679ed2-6536-4b3e-9b3d-d72763db316e|title=2021 Latin GRAMMYs: Becky G Says Performing with Christina Aguilera Is a 'Full Circle Moment'|publisher=[[WUSA (TV)|WUSA]]|access-date=November 26, 2021}}</ref> [[Britney Spears]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/CidYiczuBJG/|title=By no means was I being critical of Christina's beautiful body (...)|author=[[Britney Spears|Spears, Britney]]|via=[[Instagram]]|access-date=September 14, 2022|date=September 13, 2022|url-status=live|archive-date=September 14, 2022|archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220914080910/https://i.imgur.com/ft8aat6.jpg|format=As quoted: "I flew to see her show once [...]. I was inspired by her show and she is a beautiful woman of power … Thank you @xtina for inspiring me !!!"}}</ref> [[Camila Cabello]],<ref>{{cite web|language=Spanish|author=Adriano Moreno|date=30 May 2017|url=https://los40.com/los40/2017/05/23/musica/1495553567_084827.html|title=Camila Cabello Se Inspira en Edurne y Christina Aguilera Para Su Debut en Solitario|publisher=[[LOS40]]|access-date=26 July 2021}}</ref> [[Charli XCX]],<ref>{{cite web|author=Ashley Spurgeon|date=November 4, 2013|url=https://www.nashvillescene.com/music/british-pop-starlet-charli-xcx-the-particularly-grown-up-21-year-old/article_19f1b422-e914-5f21-8508-d044e498d9ae.html|title=British Pop Starlet Charli XCX, the Particularly Grown-Up 21-Year-Old|publisher=[[Nashville Scene]]|access-date=November 26, 2021}}</ref> [[Demi Lovato]],<ref>{{cite web|author=Mariah Haas|date=29 September 2017|url=https://people.com/music/demi-lovato-reveals-christina-aguilera-really-inspired-album/|title=Demi Lovato Reveals Christina Aguilera Album Inspiration|publisher=[[People (magazine)|People]]|access-date=26 July 2021}}</ref> [[Dua Lipa]],<ref>{{cite web|author=Brennan Carley|date=24 January 2018|url=https://www.gq.com/story/dua-lipa-is-changing-the-rules-of-pop-music|title=Dua Lipa Is Changing the Rules of Pop Music|publisher=[[GQ]]|access-date=26 July 2021}}</ref> [[Grimes (musician)|Grimes]],<ref>{{cite web|author=Kat Stoeffel|date=14 March 2012|url=https://observer.com/2012/03/snip-snip-bang-bang-from-rooney-to-runway-cropped-tops-come-to-the-forehead/|title=Snip, Snip, Bangs, Bangs! From Rooney to Runway, Cropped Tops Come to the Fore(head)|publisher=[[The New York Observer]]|access-date=26 July 2021}}</ref> [[Halsey (singer)|Halsey]],<ref>{{cite web|author=Lauren Rearick|date=10 January 2020|url=https://www.teenvogue.com/story/halsey-you-should-be-sad-music-video|title=Halsey References Lady Gaga, Christina Aguilera and More Pop Stars in Her 'You Should Be Sad' Video|publisher=[[Teen Vogue]]|access-date=26 July 2021}}</ref> [[Hayley Williams]],<ref>{{cite tweet|user=yelyahwilliams|number=413167086563639296|title=Xtina, such a dream meeting you! Remember learning how to sing high notes to your first record :) thx for always inspiring. Happy finale!|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224010018/https://twitter.com/yelyahwilliams/status/413167086563639296|archive-date=December 24, 2013}}</ref> [[Iggy Azalea]],<ref>{{Cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/awards/billboard-women-in-music-honoree-iggy-azalea-6363521/|title=Billboard Women in Music Honoree Iggy Azalea: 'If I Lose Every Award to Sam Smith, I'm Okay With It'|access-date=June 21, 2022|magazine=Billboard}}</ref> [[Karol G]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://vmagazine.com/article/reggaeton-queen-karol-g-is-the-one-to-watch/|title=Reggaeton Queen Karol G Is The One To Watch|publisher=[[V (American magazine)|V]]|access-date=26 July 2021}}</ref> [[Kelly Clarkson]],<ref name="RS100"/> [[Lady Gaga]],<ref>{{cite web|author=Zayda Rivera|date=18 December 2013|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv-movies/feud-christina-aguilera-lady-gaga-perform-voice-finale-article-1.1551550|title=Christina Aguilera, Lady Gaga Put Feud Rumors to Rest with Duet on 'The Voice'|work=[[New York Daily News]]|access-date=26 July 2021}}</ref> [[Lauren Jauregui]],<ref name="playlist">{{cite web|url=https://www.teenvogue.com/story/lauren-jauregui-shares-playlist-of-her-life|title=Lauren Jauregui Shares the Playlist of Her Life|work=[[Teen Vogue]]|date=October 26, 2018|access-date=December 14, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://top40-charts.com/artist.php?aid=14678|title=Fifth Harmony Biography, Discography, Chart History|website=Top40-Charts.com}}</ref> [[Meghan Trainor]],<ref>{{cite web|date=12 May 2016|author=Patrick Ryan|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/reviews/2016/05/12/meghan-trainor-thank-you-album-review/84228362/|title=Review: Meghan Trainor Exudes Confidence on 'Thank You'|publisher=[[USA Today]]|access-date=20 February 2021}}</ref> [[Miley Cyrus]],<ref>{{cite web|author=Timothy Mitchell|date=25 February 2014|url=https://nypost.com/2014/02/25/a-miley-inspired-short-history-of-cheeky-chaps/|title=A Miley-Inspired Short History of Cheeky Chaps|publisher=[[New York Post]]|access-date=26 July 2021}}</ref> [[Nicki Nicole]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wonderlandmagazine.com/2021/10/27/new-noise-nicki-nicole/|title=Nicki Nicole Gets Candid on Her New Album|work=[[Wonderland (magazine)|Wonderland]]|date=October 27, 2021|access-date=October 28, 2021}}</ref> [[Olivia Rodrigo]],<ref>{{cite web|author=David Amsdem|date=14 May 2021|url=https://www.wmagazine.com/culture/olivia-rodrigo-drivers-license-sour-interview|title=Olivia Rodrigo Talks Driver's License, Deja Vu and New Album, Sour|publisher=[[W (magazine)|W]]|access-date=26 July 2021}}</ref> [[Rina Sawayama]],<ref>{{cite web|author=Venetia La Manna|date=2 March 2021|url=https://www.iheart.com/podcast/256-talking-tastebuds-31065656/episode/rina-sawayama-on-mental-health-music-78335191/|title=Rina Sawayama on Mental Health, Music Awards Eligibility & Sustainability|publisher=[[iHeartRadio]]|access-date=26 July 2021}}</ref> [[Rosalía (singer)|Rosalía]],<ref>{{cite web|language=Spanish|author=P. Cantó|date=12 March 2019|url=https://www.elconfidencial.com/cultura/2019-03-12/rosalia-artistas-admira-azucar-moreno_1876342/|title=Música: Rosalía Elige a Las 28 Mujeres que Le Inspiran: de Aretha Franklin a Azúcar Moreno|publisher=[[El Confidencial]]|access-date=26 July 2021}}</ref> [[Sabrina Carpenter]],<ref>{{cite web|author=Megan Downing|date=15 June 2017|url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/get-to-know/news/sabrina-carpenter-get-to-know-introducing-interview|title=Get to Know: Sabrina Carpenter|publisher=[[MTV UK]]|access-date=28 July 2021}}</ref> [[Sam Smith]],<ref>{{cite news|author=Cameron Adams|date=15 April 2015|url=https://www.news.com.au/entertainment/music/tours/sam-smith-on-lady-gaga-tom-petty-boy-george-and-his-next-album/news-story/9e8a23f4c7d8d17f4089fb1a1f10856f|title=Sam Smith on Lady Gaga, Tom Petty, Boy George... and His Next Album|newspaper=News.com.au — Australia's Leading News Site|publisher=[[News Corp Australia]]|access-date=26 July 2021}}</ref> [[Selena Gomez]],<ref>{{cite web|author=Mike Wass|date=2 September 2015|url=https://www.idolator.com/7606741/selena-gomez-revival-album-inspired-by-christina-aguilera-stripped|title=Selena Gomez's New Album Was Inspired By Christina Aguilera's 'Stripped'|publisher=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]|access-date=26 July 2021}}</ref> and [[Tinashe]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/tinashe-1/news/tinashe-i-think-more-women-should-collaborate-and-support-each-other|title=Tinashe: "I Think More Women Should Collaborate And Support Each Other"|publisher=[[MTV UK]]|access-date=26 July 2021}}</ref> and athletes such as figure skater [[Johnny Weir]],<ref>{{cite web|author=Ian Spelling|date=9 February 2018|url=https://www.northjersey.com/story/entertainment/tv/2018/02/09/fashion-forward-olympics-correspondent-johnny-weir-talks-olympics-living-lynhurst-and-his-passion-fa/323456002/|title=Former Figue Skater Johnny Weir Talks Olympics & His Love of Fashion|publisher=[[Herald News (New Jersey)|Herald News]]|access-date=31 July 2021}}</ref> ice dancers [[Zachary Donohue]] and [[Madison Hubbell]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.popsugar.co.uk/fitness/hubbell-donohue-burlesque-ice-dance-nationals-2021-48113893|title=Watch the Sexy, Burlesque-Inspired Skate That Propelled These Ice Dancers to a National Title|work=[[PopSugar|PopSugar UK]]|publisher=Group Nine Media|first=Amanda|last=Prahl|date=January 17, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210119135557/https://www.popsugar.co.uk/fitness/hubbell-donohue-burlesque-ice-dance-nationals-2021-48113893|access-date=January 20, 2021|archive-date=19 January 2021}}</ref> and swimmer [[Dana Vollmer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.seventeen.com/health/fitness/dana-vollmer-motivation-tips|title=Dana Vollmer Success Tips (Interview)|last=Abel|first=Alex|date=February 18, 2013|work=[[Seventeen (American magazine)|Seventeen]]|access-date=31 July 2021}}</ref>

Aguilera has also been praised for emphasizing the importance of feminism in pop music;<ref>{{cite web|author=Emma Garland|date=22 October 2019|url=https://crackmagazine.net/article/long-reads/retrospective-christina-aguilera-stripped/|title=Christina Aguilera's 'Stripped' Was a Watershed Moment in 21st Century Pop|publisher=[[Crack Magazine]]|access-date=26 July 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Shilpa Ganatra|date=21 September 2019|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/music/christina-aguilera-i-came-out-with-dirrty-and-that-was-my-f-k-it-moment-1.4017353|title=Christina Aguilera: 'I Came Out with Dirrty and That Was My F**k It Moment'|publisher=[[The Irish Times]]|access-date=26 July 2021}}</ref> several journalists agree that her use of sexual imagery has helped catalyze public discourse on the topic.<ref name="Nowhere"/><ref name="Vagenda">{{cite web|author=Rhiannon Lucy Cosslett|date=7 October 2013|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/oct/07/miley-cyrus-music-business-women-sinead-oconnor|title=Miley Cyrus: Does the Music Business Exploit Women?|work=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=26 July 2021}}</ref> Lamar Dawson, columnist from ''[[The Huffington Post]]'', praised her feminist efforts in the music industry and recognized that "while Christina isn't the first pop star to place feminist rhetoric into pop culture, she led the charge at the beginning of the 21st century of influencing the next generation of impressionable teens who were too young for [[Janet Jackson|Janet [Jackson]]] and [[Madonna]]'s curriculum".<ref>{{cite web|author=Lamar Dawson|date=22 October 2017|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/christina-aguileras-stripped-is-15-and-still-amazing_b_59ebf681e4b092f9f24192ca|title=Christina Aguilera's 'Stripped' Is 15 and Still Amazing|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|access-date=26 July 2021}}</ref> Gerrick D. Kennedy from ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' shared the same point of view and stated that "for a generation who hit puberty during the great 2000 pop explosion, Aguilera was an essential voice with music that tackled self-empowerment, feminism, sex and domestic violence — subject matter her contemporaries were shying away from".<ref name="Hiatus"/> Rhiannon Lucy Cosslett, co-founder of ''[[The Vagenda]]'', opined that the provocative dance routines in Aguilera's music videos was "empowering",<ref name="Vagenda"/> as she has been referred to as the forerunner of the ''[[slutdrop]]'' dance style.<ref name="Slutdrop">{{cite web|author=Sophie Wilkinson|date=1 December 2012|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2012/dec/01/slutdropping-empowering-dance-move|title=Slutdropping: The Dancefloor Move That's Bringing Women Together|work=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=26 July 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Lucy Morris|date=28 April 2017|url=https://graziadaily.co.uk/fashion/news/11-moments-christina-aguileras-dirrty-video-showed-mtv-age-lawless-paradise/|title=11 Moments from Christina Aguilera's Dirrty Video That Showed the MTV Age Was a Lawless Paradise|publisher=[[Grazia]]|access-date=26 July 2021}}</ref>

Aguilera's videography impact was also analysed by music critics. While "[[Dirrty]]" (2002) has been described as "one of the most controversial videos in pop music history",<ref name="Jeri">{{cite web|author=Bianca Gracie|date=27 July 2018|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/pop/christina-aguilera-dirrty-music-video-interview-david-lachapelle-jeri-slaughter-8467192/|title=Director David LaChapelle & Choreographer Jeri Slaughter on the Making of Christina Aguilera's 'Dirrty' Music Video|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=January 21, 2022}}</ref><ref name="TurnedPop"/> and one of the greatest music videos of all time,<ref>{{cite web|author=Sal Cinquemani|date=30 June 2003|url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/music/100-greatest-music-videos/|title=The 100 Greatest Music Video of All Time|publisher=[[Slant Magazine]]|access-date=26 July 2021}}</ref> Issy Beech from ''[[i-D]]'' recognized that the audiovisual work "paved a path for videos like "[[Anaconda (Nicki Minaj song)|Anaconda]]" and "[[Wrecking Ball (Miley Cyrus song)|Wrecking Ball]]" [...] paved the way for open sexuality from women in pop".<ref>{{cite web|author=Issy Beech|date=1 December 2016|url=https://i-d.vice.com/en_uk/article/a3v9b5/how-xtinas-dirrty-changed-sex-in-pop|title=How Xtina's 'Dirrty' Changed Sex in Pop|work=[[i-D]]|publisher=[[Vice Media]]|access-date=26 July 2021}}</ref> In the video for "[[Beautiful (Christina Aguilera song)|Beautiful]]" (2002), the highlight scene of a gay kiss has been considered one of the most important moments for [[LGBT culture]],<ref>{{cite web|author=Adam Bloodworth|date=4 October 2019|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/rupaul-drag-race-uk-queer-culture-lgbt-bitchy-catty-a9143376.html|title=RuPaul's Drag Race UK: Is Wrong to Embrace the Outdated Stereotype of Queer Bitchiness|work=[[The Independent]]|access-date=26 July 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|language=Portuguese|url=https://oglobo.globo.com/cultura/57-marcos-lgbtqi-na-cultura-pop-do-brasil-do-mundo-23767523|title=57 marcos LGBTQI+ na cultura pop do Brasil e do mundo|date=June 28, 2019|publisher=[[O Globo]]|access-date=26 July 2021}}</ref> in addition to start Aguilera's image as a [[gay icon]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Daniel Megarry|date=11 March 2019|url=https://www.gaytimes.co.uk/community/119548/christina-aguilera-to-be-named-ally-for-equality-by-human-rights-campaign/|title=Christina Aguilera Named Ally for Equality by Human Rights Campaign|publisher=[[Gay Times]]|access-date=26 July 2021}}</ref> Both works was elected as one of the greatest music videos of the 21st century by editors from ''Billboard'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/media/lists/100-greatest-music-videos-of-the-21st-century-8466543/|title=The 100 Greatest Music Videos of the 21st Century: Critics' Picks|date=July 24, 2018|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=January 21, 2022}}</ref> while she was named one of the greatest women of the video era according VH1.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/shows/the_greatest/episode.jhtml?episodeID=66397#moreinfo|title=50 Greatest Women of the Video Era|publisher=[[VH1]]|access-date=26 July 2021|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121104173933/http://www.vh1.com/shows/the_greatest/episode.jhtml?episodeID=66397#moreinfo|archive-date=4 November 2012}}</ref> In 2012, her videographic collection and some looks used throughout her career were part of an exhibition by the [[National Museum of Women in the Arts]] aimed at illustrating "the essential roles women have played in moving rock and roll and American culture forward".<ref>{{cite web|author=Amy Mannarino|date=6 August 2012|url=https://nmwa.org/press-room/press-releases/women-who-rock-vision-passion-power-national-museum-women-arts-dc|title=Women Who Rock: Vision, Passion, Power|publisher=[[National Museum of Women in the Arts]]|access-date=26 July 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Elizabeth Olson|date=26 October 2012|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/10/28/arts/artsspecial/women-who-rock-exhibit-traces-female-music-artists-in-america.html|title='Women Who Rock' Exhibit Traces Female Music Artists in America|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=26 July 2021}}</ref> [[Jon Caramanica]] from ''[[The New York Times]]'' also commented about her contributions to television, observing an expressive number of artists signing with television networks to act as coaches of singing [[reality competition]] after her participation in the [[The Voice (American TV series)|American version]] of [[The Voice (franchise)|''The Voice'' franchise]].<ref name="ChangedJud"/>

== Achievements ==
{{Main|List of awards and nominations received by Christina Aguilera}}
[[File:Christina Aguilera 2019 Disney Legends Awards Ceremony D23 EXPO 2019 (51441238154).jpg|thumb|left|upright|Aguilera performing "[[Reflection (song)|Reflection]]" during the [[D23 Expo]] in 2019, where she was honored as a [[Disney Legends|Disney Legend]]]]
Aguilera has accumulated several awards and accolades in her career. At the age of nineteen, she won the [[Grammy Award for Best New Artist]], being recognized by [[The Recording Academy]] as one of the youngest singers to receive such an honor;<ref>{{cite web|author=Diana Pearl|date=12 January 2019|url=https://people.com/music/grammys-youngest-nominees/|title=The Youngest Artists to Ever Be Nominated for a Grammy Award|publisher=[[People (magazine)|People]]|access-date=27 July 2021}}</ref> by the same ceremony, she received four other trophies.<ref>{{cite web|author=Andrea Park|date=7 December 2018|url=https://www.wmagazine.com/story/demi-lovato-grammy-nomination|title=Demi Lovato Calls Grammy Nomination for Her Collaboration With Christina Aguilera "Surreal"|publisher=[[W (magazine)|W]]|access-date=27 July 2021}}</ref> Furthermore, she was honored with a [[Latin Grammy Award]],<ref>{{cite web|author=Christina Saraceno|date=30 October 2001|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/christina-wins-latin-grammy-235689/|title=Christina Wins Latin Grammy|publisher=[[Rolling Stone]]|access-date=27 July 2021}}</ref> two [[MTV Video Music Awards]],<ref>{{cite web|author=Justin Oppelaar|date=6 September 2001|url=https://variety.com/2001/music/news/marmalade-jams-at-vmas-1117852371/|title=Lady Marmalade Jams at VMAs|publisher=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|access-date=27 July 2021}}</ref> one [[Billboard Music Awards|''Billboard'' Music Awards]],<ref>{{cite web|author=Daniel Jenkins|date=16 December 2000|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OxEEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA18|title=2000 Billboard Music Awards: A Night of Sparkling Performances and VIP-Packed Parties|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=27 July 2021}}</ref> one [[Guinness World Records]],<ref>{{harvnb|Folkard|2005|p=360}}</ref> and was also nominated to the [[Golden Globe Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Mike Moody|date=14 December 2010|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/movies/a293251/aguilera-thrilled-over-golden-globe-noms/|title=Aguilera 'Thrilled' Over Golden Globe Noms|publisher=[[Digital Spy]]|access-date=27 July 2021}}</ref> In 2010, she received a star on [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] in "recognition of her achievements in the [[recording industry]]";<ref>{{cite web|author=James Dinh|date=15 November 2010|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1652335/christina-aguilera-honored-on-hollywood-walk-of-fame/|title=Christina Aguilera Honored On Hollywood Walk Of Fame|publisher=[[MTV News]]|access-date=27 July 2021}}</ref> in 2019, she was also immortalized as a [[Disney Legend]] in "honor for her remarkable contributions to [[the Walt Disney Company]]".<ref name="DisneyLegend">{{cite web|author=Lauren Huff|date=23 August 2019|url=https://ew.com/movies/2019/08/23/d23-disney-legends-robert-downey-jr-christina-aguilera/|title=Robert Downey Jr., Christina Aguilera, and More Honored as Disney Legends|publisher=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|access-date=27 July 2021}}</ref> In addition to being often cited as one of the most prominent Latin artists in the [[show business|entertainment industry]],<ref>{{harvnb|Valdivia|2010|p=108}}</ref><ref name="ProeminentLatin">{{cite web|author=Darek Michael Wajda|date=23 June 2016|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/latino/latino-celebrities-sign-open-letter-congress-gun-violence-n597731|title=Latino Celebrities Sign Open Letter to Congress on Gun Violence|publisher=[[NBC News]]|access-date=27 July 2021}}</ref><ref name="Influyentes">{{cite web|language=Spanish|url=https://www.univision.com/noticias/mes-de-la-hispanidad/hispanos-influyentes-en-estados-unidos|title=Hispanos Influyentes en Estados Unidos|publisher=[[Univision]]|access-date=27 July 2021}}</ref> Aguilera was elected as one of the [[Time 100|100 most influential people in the world]] by ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' in 2013.<ref name="Time100">{{cite magazine|author=Céline Dion|date=18 April 2013|url=https://time100.time.com/2013/04/18/time-100/slide/christina-aguilera/|title=The 100 Most Influential People in the World|magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|access-date=27 July 2021}}</ref> Aguilera is set to be honored for her philanthropic and humanitarin efforts with the ''Billboard'' Spirit of Hope Award at the ''Billboard'' Latin Music Awards in September 2022.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Roiz |first=Jessica |date=2022-09-08 |title=Christina Aguilera to Receive Spirit of Hope Award at 2022 Billboard Latin Music Awards |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/latin/christina-aguilera-honored-2022-billboard-latin-music-awards-spirit-of-hope-1235135923/ |access-date=2022-09-09 |magazine=Billboard |language=en-US}}</ref>

Aguilera is recognized as one of the world's [[List of best-selling music artists|best-selling music artists]], with estimated sales around 75 million records.<ref name="3Arena"/><ref>{{cite web|author=Muri Assunção|date=27 June 2020|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/snyde/ny-christina-aguilera-last-name-too-ethnic-change-20200627-kncxjsoaibhwvevmnjrc5hugdi-story.html|title=Christina Aguilera's Name Was 'Too Ethnic' for Music Execs|work=[[New York Daily News]]|access-date=27 July 2021}}</ref> According to [[Nielsen Soundscan]], she has sold over 18.3 million albums in the United States;<ref name="AlbumSales"/> her [[Christina Aguilera (album)|self-titled debut album]] (1999) was certified [[RIAA certification|eight times platinum]] and listed as one of the best-selling in the country by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?advance_search=1&tab_active=awards_by_album&awardal=&formatal=Album&typeal=&type_optional=ST#search_section|title=Top Albums|publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of America]]|access-date=27 July 2021}}</ref> Regarding her [[digital download (music)|digital sales]], it is estimated that she has sold around 21.4 million tracks in the country until 2014.<ref name="Shake"/> In United Kingdom, Aguilera has sold over 9.4 million records as of 2013, which 3.3 million in albums sales and 6.1 million in singles sales;<ref>{{cite web|author=Justin Myers|date=7 October 2013|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/disneys-official-top-10-biggest-selling-pop-princesses-revealed-__4620/|title=How Does Miley Cyrus Compare to Britney, Selena, Demi and Disney's Other Pop Princesses?|publisher=[[The Official Charts Company]]|access-date=27 July 2021}}</ref> also, according [[The Official Charts Company]], her fourth studio album ''[[Stripped (Christina Aguilera album)|Stripped]]'' (2002) is one of the few to surpass the 2 million copies sold,<ref name="2M">{{cite web|author=Rob Copsey|date=14 April 2021|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/christina-aguilera-working-on-new-english-and-spanish-language-albums__32906/|title= Christina Aguilera Working on New English and Spanish Language Albums|publisher=[[The Official Charts Company]]|access-date=27 July 2021}}</ref> becoming the [[List of best-selling albums of the 2000s (decade) in the United Kingdom|second highest-selling album by an American female artist during the 2000s]] and one of the [[List of best-selling albums of the 21st century in the United Kingdom|best-selling albums of the millennium in the country]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Noughties' Official UK Albums Chart Top 100|periodical=[[Music Week]]|publisher=[[UBM plc|United Business Media]]|location=London, England|page=19|date=30 January 2010}}</ref><ref name="Millennium">{{cite web|author=Liv Moss|date=19 March 2015|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/official-biggest-selling-albums-of-the-millennium-so-far-revealed-__8698/|title=Official Biggest Selling Albums of the Millennium So Far Revealed|publisher=[[The Official Charts Company]]|access-date=27 July 2021}}</ref> Furthermore, "[[Moves Like Jagger]]" (2011) — her collaboration with band [[Maroon 5]] — was cited as one of the [[List of best-selling singles in Australia|best-selling singles in Australia]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aria.com.au/pages/httpwww.aria.com.aupagesaria-charts-accreditations-singles-2014.htm|title=ARIA Charts - Accreditations - 2014 Singles|publisher=[[Australian Recording Industry Association]]|access-date=27 July 2021|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200810124828/http://www.aria.com.au/pages/httpwww.aria.com.aupagesaria-charts-accreditations-singles-2014.htm|archive-date=10 August 2020}}</ref> [[List of best-selling singles in Canada|Canada]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://musiccanada.com/gold-platinum/?_gp_search=Moves+Like+Jagger+Maroon+5|title=Gold/Platinum|publisher=[[Music Canada]]|access-date=27 July 2021}}</ref> [[List of best-selling singles in South Korea|South Korea]],<ref name="Gaon">Cumulative sales for "Moves Like Jagger":
*{{cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?serviceGbn=S1020&termGbn=year&hitYear=2011&targetTime=11&nationGbn=E|title=Download Chart (International) – 2011|work=[[Gaon Music Chart]]|publisher=[[Korea Music Content Industry Association]]|access-date=27 July 2021}}
*{{cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?serviceGbn=S1020&termGbn=year&hitYear=2012&targetTime=11&nationGbn=E|title=Download Chart (International) – 2012|work=[[Gaon Music Chart]]|publisher=[[Korea Music Content Industry Association]]|access-date=27 July 2021}}
*{{cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?serviceGbn=S1020&termGbn=year&hitYear=2013&targetTime=11&nationGbn=E|title=Download Chart (International) - 2013|work=[[Gaon Music Chart]]|publisher=[[Korea Music Content Industry Association]]|access-date=27 July 2021}}
*{{cite web| url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?serviceGbn=S1020&termGbn=year&hitYear=2014&targetTime=11&nationGbn=E| title=Download Chart (International) – 2014|work=[[Gaon Music Chart]]|publisher=[[Korea Music Content Industry Association]]|access-date=27 July 2021}}
*{{cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?serviceGbn=S1020&termGbn=year&hitYear=2015&targetTime=11&nationGbn=E|title=Download Chart (International) – 2015|work=[[Gaon Music Chart]]|publisher=[[Korea Music Content Industry Association]]|access-date=27 July 2021}}
*{{cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?serviceGbn=S1020&termGbn=year&hitYear=2016&targetTime=15&nationGbn=E|title=Download Chart (International) – 2016|work=[[Gaon Music Chart]]|publisher=[[Korea Music Content Industry Association]]|access-date=27 July 2021}}
*{{cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?serviceGbn=S1020&termGbn=year&hitYear=2017&targetTime=2017&nationGbn=E|title=Download Chart (International) – 2017|work=[[Gaon Music Chart]]|publisher=[[Korea Music Content Industry Association]]|access-date=27 July 2021}}</ref> the [[List of best-selling singles in the United Kingdom|United Kingdom]],<ref>{{cite web|author=Justin Myers|date=14 February 2020|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/the-best-selling-singles-of-all-time-on-the-official-uk-chart__21298/|title=The Best-Selling Singles of All Time on the Official UK Chart|publisher=[[The Official Charts Company]]|access-date=27 July 2021}}</ref> and the [[List of best-selling singles in the United States|United States]],<ref name="MLJMC1">{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&se=Moves+Like+Jagger#search_section|title=Gold & Platinum|publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of America]]|access-date=27 July 2021}}</ref> as well as one of the [[List of best-selling singles#Best-selling digital singles|best-selling digital singles]] with over 14.4 million copies.<ref name="MLJSales">{{cite web|author=Jessica Goldstein|date=3 April 2014|url=https://www.vulture.com/2014/04/tv-music-show-judges-biggest-success-pharrell-the-voice.html|title=Pharrell and The Voice: Which Musicians Have Benefited the Most From Being TV Judges?|publisher=[[New York (magazine)|New York Magazine]]|work=[[Vulture.com|Vulture]]|access-date=27 July 2021}}</ref>

After being listed as the top female artist of 2000 and 2003,<ref name="YIM2000">{{cite web|author=Jeff Silberman|date=30 December 2000|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ehEEAAAAMBAJ&pg=RA37-PA2|title=Year in Music: 2000|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=27 July 2021}}</ref><ref name="YIM2003">{{cite web|author=Geoff Mayfield|date=27 December 2003|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bA8EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA68|title=Year in Music: 2003|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=27 July 2021}}</ref> ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' classified Aguilera as the twentieth most successful artist of the 2000s.<ref name="AotD">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/music-news/artists-of-the-decade-page-two-266419/|title=Artists of the Decade|date=December 11, 2009|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=January 21, 2022}}</ref> Through the same publication, she was considered one of the most successful artists of the decade on [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/charts/decadeendcharts/2009/billboard-200-artists|title=Billboard 200 Artists|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=27 July 2021|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121006014550/http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/charts/decadeendcharts/2009/billboard-200-artists|archive-date=6 October 2012}}</ref> [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/charts/decadeendcharts/2009/hot-100-artists|title=Billboard Hot 100 Artists|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=27 July 2021|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121008004835/http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/charts/decadeendcharts/2009/hot-100-artists|archive-date=8 October 2012}}</ref> and [[Mainstream Top 40]] charts,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts-decade-end/pop-songs-artists?year=2009#/charts-decade-end/pop-songs-artists?year=2009|title=Billboard Pop Songs Artists|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=27 July 2021|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100106053404/http://www.billboard.com/charts-decade-end/pop-songs-artists?year=2009#/charts-decade-end/pop-songs-artists?year=2009|archive-date=6 January 2010}}</ref> and the second best-selling singles artist in the United States, behind [[Madonna]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/charts/decadeendcharts/2009/singles-sales-artists|title=Singles Sales Artists|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=27 July 2021|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110303202050/http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/charts/decadeendcharts/2009/singles-sales-artists|archive-date=3 March 2011}}</ref> In 2016, she was also nominated as one of the greatest artists in history of the Mainstream Top 40 and [[Dance Club Songs]] charts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/greatest-of-all-time-pop-songs-artists|title=Greatest of All Time Pop Songs Artists Chart|date=October 18, 2017|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=27 July 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/greatest-top-dance-club-artists|title=Greatest of All Time Top Dance Club Artists|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=27 July 2021|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161204011113/https://www.billboard.com/charts/greatest-top-dance-club-artists|archive-date=4 December 2016}}</ref> In addition, Aguilera was recognized by the magazine as one of the four female artists in history to have a [[List of Billboard Hot 100 chart achievements and milestones|number-one single on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 in three consecutive decades]].<ref name="VegasEarned">{{cite web|author=Eric Frankenberg|date=12 July 2019|url=https://www.billboard.com/pro/christina-aguilera-launches-vegas-residency-the-xperience-earnings/|title=Christina Aguilera Launches Vegas Residency 'The Xperience' with $4 Million Earned|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=January 21, 2022}}</ref> In 2020, she was cited by ''[[Pollstar]]'' as one of the top female artists of the 21st century in the [[concert|concert industry]]; according to the publication, she sold more than 1.8 million tickets for her performances throughout her career, with an earning exceeding $113.8 million.<ref>{{cite web|author=Bob Allen|date=27 March 2020|url=https://www.pollstar.com/article/ladies-might-box-office-triumph-by-top-female-earners-144117|title=Ladies Might: Box Office Triumph By Top Female Earners|publisher=[[Pollstar]]|access-date=27 July 2021}}</ref> In Morocco, Aguilera held her largest audience concert, attracting 250,000 people to her performance at [[Mawazine Festival#2016|Mawazine Festival]], becoming the record audience in history of the event.<ref>{{cite web|language=French|author=Aïda Bouazza|date=30 May 2016|url=https://www.leconomiste.com/article/998335-mawazine|title=Mawazine: Une Clôture En Apothéose|publisher=[[L'Économiste]]|access-date=27 July 2021}}</ref>

== Other activities ==
=== Investments and endorsements ===
Outside of her projects in the music industry, Aguilera has worked in other activities. In 2016, after founding her own production company, MX Productions, she signed a contract with [[Lions Gate Entertainment]] to develop a music competition program, named ''Tracks'', which was aired on [[Spike TV]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Lesley Goldberg|date=15 March 2016|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/tv/tv-news/spike-orders-music-game-show-875671/|title=Spike Orders Music Game Show 'Tracks' from Christina Aguilera|publisher=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|access-date=3 July 2021}}</ref> At the same year, it was reported that she was an investor of multiple companies, including [[Pinterest]], [[DraftKings]], [[Lyft]] and [[MasterClass]] — for which she also developed a singing class.<ref>{{cite web|author=Todd Spangler|date=21 July 2016|url=https://variety.com/2016/digital/exec-shuffle-people-news/masterclass-matthew-rutler-christina-aguilera-1201819025/|title=Celeb-Instructor Startup MasterClass Names Matthew Rutler Head of Talent, Biz Dev|publisher=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|access-date=1 July 2021}}</ref> Throughout her career, she has worked with the sale of your own products; in 2011, she attended [[São Paulo Fashion Week]] to unveil her first clothes line which was commercialized at the Brazilian department store [[C&A]].<ref>{{cite web|language=Portuguese|author=Flavia Guerra|date=1 February 2011|url=https://www.estadao.com.br/blogs/revista/christina-aguilera-a-mulher-brasileira-e-perfeita-para-minhas-roupas/|title=Christina Aguilera: 'A mulher brasileira é perfeita para minhas roupas'|publisher=[[O Estado de S. Paulo]]|access-date=1 July 2021}}</ref> In 2004, she started her perfume line through [[Procter & Gamble]] (P&G),<ref>{{cite web|author=Kim Novak|date=17 January 2007|url=https://metro.co.uk/2007/01/17/smell-of-success-for-christina-560868/|title=Smell of Success for Christina|publisher=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]|access-date=1 July 2021}}</ref> which is maintained with annual releases since then; in addition to being awarded numerous times at the [[FiFi Awards]] by [[The Fragrance Foundation]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecut.com/2008/04/marc_jacobs_tom_ford_christina_1.html|title=Marc Jacobs, Tom Ford and Christina Aguilera Win Top Fragrance Awards|magazine=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|access-date=1 July 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Belisa Silva|date=27 April 2012|url=https://wwd.com/beauty-industry-news/fragrance/fifi-award-finalists-revealed-5880580/|title=FiFi Award Top Five and Award Winners|publisher=[[Women's Wear Daily]]|access-date=1 July 2021}}</ref> her fragrances ranked among the United Kingdom's best-sellers in 2007 and 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rcalabelgroup.co.uk/news/8020/|title=Christina Top Fragrance Charts|publisher=[[RCA/Jive Label Group]]|access-date=1 July 2021|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080109000818/http://www.rcalabelgroup.co.uk/news/8020/|archive-date=9 January 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vogue.co.uk/article/all-star-perfumes|title=All Star Perfumes|date=July 17, 2019|publisher=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]|access-date=1 July 2021}}</ref> In 2016, Aguilera's fragrance business was acquired by [[Elizabeth Arden, Inc.]], where it was estimated that the brand had $80 million in sales and $10 million in earnings in January of that year.<ref>{{cite web|author=Allison Collins|date=12 May 2016|url=https://wwd.com/beauty-industry-news/fragrance/elizabeth-arden-buy-christina-aguilera-fragrance-business-10429525/|title=Elizabeth Arden to Buy Christina Aguilera Fragrance Business|publisher=[[Women's Wear Daily]]|access-date=1 July 2021}}</ref>

Aguilera has also been involved in marketing initiatives during her career, endorsing numerous brands, including [[Sears]] and [[Levi's]] (2000),<ref>{{cite web|author=David Basham|date=27 April 2000|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1424806/christina-aguilera-announces-tour-youth-programs/|title=Christina Aguilera Announces Tour, Youth Programs|publisher=[[MTV News]]|access-date=1 July 2021}}</ref> [[Skechers]] (2003),<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Susman|first=Gary|date=27 August 2003|url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,478535,00.html|title=Toeing the Line|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|access-date=3 July 2021|archive-date=January 3, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150103052041/http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,478535,00.html|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Mercedes-Benz]], [[Virgin Mobile]] (both in 2004),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baby-benz.com/portal/a-class-w169/137--christina-aguilera-says-an-exclusive-qhelloq-to-the-new-a-class-|title=Christina Aguilera Says an Exclusive 'Hello' to the New A-Class|publisher=[[Mercedes-Benz]]|access-date=3 July 2021|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180701223245/http://www.baby-benz.com/portal/a-class-w169/137--christina-aguilera-says-an-exclusive-qhelloq-to-the-new-a-class-|archive-date=1 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Owen Gibson|date=19 April 2004|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2004/apr/19/digitalmedia.advertising|title=Aguilera to Star in 'Raunchy' Virgin Ads|work=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=January 3, 2015}}</ref> [[Pepsi]], [[Orange UK]], [[Sony Ericsson]] (both in 2006),<ref>{{cite web|author=Corey Moss|date=13 October 2005|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1511468/for-the-record-quick-news-on-christina-aguilera-game-50-cent-jessica-simpson-nelly-c-delores-tucker-more/|title=For the Record: Quick News On Christina Aguilera, Game, 50 Cent, Jessica Simpson, Nelly & More|publisher=[[MTV News]]|access-date=3 July 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Lars Brandle|date=18 March 2006|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HhYEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA14|title=Orange Deal Juicy for Aguilera|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=3 July 2021}}</ref> [[Oreo]] (2017),<ref>{{cite web|author=Pauline Lacsamana|date=8 February 2017|url=https://www.yahoo.com/lifestyle/oreo-launches-dunk-challenge-christina-224118518.html|title=Oreo Launches Dunk Challenge with Christina Aguilera and Shaquille O'Neal|publisher=[[Yahoo!]]|access-date=3 July 2021}}</ref> and [[SweeTarts]] (2021).<ref>{{cite web|author=Tomás Mier|date=13 July 2021|url=https://people.com/music/christina-aguilera-reinspired-by-music-latin-album-sweetarts-exclusive/|title=Christina Aguilera Says She's 'Re-Inspired by Music All Over Again'|publisher=[[People (magazine)|People]]|access-date=26 July 2021}}</ref> In 2001, she signed with [[Coca-Cola]] to star in a series of television commercials in a deal reported to worth up £50 million.<ref>{{cite web|author=Julia Day|date=28 March 2001|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2001/mar/28/advertising2|title=Aguilera and Britney Go Head-To-Head in Cola Wars|work=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=1 July 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=NME Staff|date=28 March 2001|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/christina-aguilera-53-1399741|title=Coke Fiend Christina|publisher=[[NME]]|access-date=1 July 2021}}</ref> Furthermore, Aguilera inspired a clothing line by [[Versace]] in 2003, starring as a model in its advertising campaign;<ref>{{cite web|author=Gary Susman|date=5 March 2003|url=https://ew.com/article/2003/03/05/versace-signs-christina-aguilera/|title=Versace Signs Christina Aguilera|publisher=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|access-date=3 July 2021}}</ref> likewise, in 2008, she influenced and appeared in a campaign to promote a collection of [[sterling silver]] pieces designed by [[Stephen Webster]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Conti|first=Samantha|date=19 February 2008|url=http://www.wwd.com/accessories-news/jewelry/christina-aguilera-inspires-stephen-webster-silver-line-465346|title=Christina Aguilera Inspires Stephen Webster Silver Line|work=[[Women's Wear Daily]]|access-date=3 July 2021}}</ref> In 2004, it was reported that she earned over £200,000 pounds to open a summer sale at London's department store [[Harrods]].<ref>{{cite web|date=28 June 2004|url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/lifestyle/arid-30154535.html|title=Aguilera Causes a Stir at Harrods' Sale|publisher=[[Irish Examiner]]|access-date=3 July 2021}}</ref> Following the birth of her first child in 2008, Aguilera was paid $1.5 million to submit her baby pictures to ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' magazine, which became the [[List of most expensive celebrity photographs|ninth most expensive celebrity baby photograph ever taken]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Lucey Rose|date=10 April 2008|url=https://www.forbes.com/2008/04/10/hollywood-celebrity-magazines-biz-media-cx_lr_0410babypix_slide.html#7497e8c29163|title=The Most Expensive Celebrity Baby Photos|work=[[Forbes]]|access-date=3 July 2021}}</ref>

=== Philanthropy ===
[[File:Christina Aguilera (at premiere of "To John With Love", September 2010).jpg|thumb|upright|right|Aguilera attending a beneficent event promoted by [[Montblanc (company)|Montblanc]] in 2010]]
Aguilera has done numerous philanthropic works during her career. In 2001, she signed an open letter organized by the [[People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals]] (PETA) destined to [[South Korea]], appealing on national government to ban the consumption of dogs and cats.<ref>{{harvnb|Govan|2013|p=114}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2002/apr/10/newsstory.sport5|title=Bocelli Not Blind to Tortured Dogs|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=April 10, 2002|access-date=1 July 2021}}</ref> In 2006, she replaced a costume designed by [[Roberto Cavalli]] for her [[Back to Basics Tour]] after discovering that he had used fox fur in its composition.<ref>{{cite web|author=Dan Matthews|date=12 December 2006|url=https://www.peta.org/blog/christina-aguileras-costume-change/|title=Christina Aguilera's Costume Change|publisher=[[People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals]]|access-date=1 July 2021}}</ref> In 2010, Aguilera auctioned tickets to her concerts through [[Christie's]], earmarking the proceeds to [[non-profit]] [[environmental organization]]s, including [[Conservation International]] and the [[Natural Resources Defense Council]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Coppy Holzman|date=3 February 2010|url=http://www.christies.com/about/press-center/releases/pressrelease.aspx?pressreleaseid=3916|title=Christie's Announces the 2010 Inaugural Green Auction|publisher=[[Christie's]]|access-date=1 July 2021|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100210003134/http://www.christies.com/about/press-center/releases/pressrelease.aspx?pressreleaseid=3916|archive-date=10 February 2010}}</ref> She has also worked to raise awareness of [[HIV/AIDS]]; in 2004, she was the face of a make-up line by [[MAC Cosmetics]], profits of which were used to benefit the [[Mac AIDS Fund]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Kathryn Romeyn|date=27 October 2015|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/general-news/ariana-grande-is-macs-new-834924/|title=Ariana Grande Is MAC's New Viva Glam Spokeswoman|publisher=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|access-date=January 21, 2022}}</ref> In the following year, Aguilera appeared in a photo book which raised funds for the [[Elton John AIDS Foundation]],<ref>{{cite web|author=Corey Moss|date=10 June 2005|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1503951/for-the-record-quick-news-on-paris-hilton-christina-aguilera-michael-jackson-josh-homme-a-perfect-circle-more/|title=For the Record: Quick News on Paris Hilton, Christina Aguilera, Michael Jackson, Josh Homme, a Perfect Circle & More|publisher=[[MTV News]]|access-date=1 July 2021}}</ref> in addition to starring in a campaign organized by [[YouthAIDS]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Shadi Rahimi|date=10 November 2005|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/11/10/nyregion/an-enduring-ribbon-of-stars.html|title=An Enduring Ribbon of Stars|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=1 July 2021}}</ref>

In 2003, Aguilera visited and donated over $200,000 dollars to the [[Women's Center & Shelter of Greater Pittsburgh]], a support center for victims of domestic violence.<ref>{{cite web|author=Mackenzie Carpenter|date=22 December 2003|url=https://old.post-gazette.com/localnews/20031222christinalocal4p4.asp|title=Aguilera's Visit, Story Lift Spirits at Women's Shelter|publisher=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]|access-date=1 July 2021}}</ref> In 2019, she donated part of the proceeds from her [[The Xperience|residency concert]] to an organization based in [[Las Vegas, Nevada]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/GMA/Culture/christina-aguileras-las-vegas-residency-raise-money-domestic/story?id=63003925|title=Christina Aguilera's Las Vegas Residency to Raise Money for Domestic Violence Victims|publisher=[[ABC News]]|access-date=1 July 2021}}</ref> Furthermore, she has starred in commercials on the [[Lifetime (TV network)|Lifetime]] channel calling for an end to violence against women,<ref>{{cite web|author=Corey Moss|date=4 April 2007|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1556284/for-the-record-quick-news-on-kelly-clarkson-idol-daniel-radcliffe-christina-aguilera-spidey-3-more/|title=For the Record: Quick News On Kelly Clarkson, 'Idol', Daniel Radcliffe, Christina Aguilera & More|publisher=[[MTV News]]|access-date=1 July 2021}}</ref> and collaborated with institutions that fight [[breast cancer]].<ref>{{cite web|author=John Morgan|date=3 March 2004|url=https://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/health/spotlighthealth/2004-03-03-nicole_x.htm|title=Nicole Kidman Fashions Fight Against Women's Cancer|publisher=[[USA Today]]|access-date=1 July 2021}}</ref> In 2005, she participated in a gala event designed to raise funds for child support organizations, including [[Nelson Mandela Children's Fund]];<ref>{{cite web|author=Jennifer Vineyard|date=26 October 2005|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1512314/for-the-record-quick-news-on-christina-aguilera-jennifer-lopez-and-marc-anthony-madonna-bloc-party-more/|title=For The Record: Quick News On Christina Aguilera, Jennifer Lopez And Marc Anthony, Madonna, Bloc Party & More|publisher=[[MTV News]]|access-date=1 July 2021}}</ref> similarly, in 2008, she participated in the [[Var mısın? Yok musun?|Turkish version]] of the [[game show]] ''[[Deal or No Deal]]'', where she earned ₺180,000 lire — an amount converted into donations to the country's orphanages.<ref>{{cite news|author=Acun Ilicali|date=20 October 2010|url=https://www.milliyet.com.tr/cadde/var-misin-yok-musun-da-aguilera-sov-1005397|title="Var mısın, Yok musun" da Aguilera şov|newspaper=[[Milliyet]]|access-date=1 July 2021}}</ref> In a ''[[Montblanc (company)|Montblanc]]'' initiative, she participated in a charity event promoting children's access to music education in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|author=Adam Tschorn|date=20 September 2010|url=https://latimesblogs.latimes.com/alltherage/2010/09/montblanc-unveils-john-lennon-limited-edition-pen.html|title=For the Paperback Writer: Montblanc Unveils John Lennon Pen|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=1 July 2021}}</ref> Aguilera was also involved in campaigns to encourage people to vote. During the [[2004 United States presidential election]], she was featured on advertising panels for [[Declare Yourself]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/music-news/stars-declare-support-for-voting-initiative-67360/|title=Stars 'Declare' Support For Voting Initiative|date=July 13, 2004|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=January 21, 2022}}</ref> and served as a spokesperson for [[Rock the Vote]] in the [[2008 United States presidential election|2008 presidential election]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.channel4.com/news/articles/arts_entertainment/aguilera+backs+voting+campaign/1047562|title=Aguilera Backs Voting Campaign|publisher=[[Channel 4]]|access-date=1 July 2021|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071115130951/http://www.channel4.com/news/articles/arts_entertainment/aguilera%2Bbacks%2Bvoting%2Bcampaign/1047562|archive-date=15 November 2007}}</ref>

In 2005, Aguilera donated her wedding gifts to charities in support of families affected by [[Hurricane Katrina]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Daniel Kilkelly|date=22 October 2005|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/showbiz/a25423/christina-aguilera-bans-wedding-presents/|title=Christina Aguilera Bans Wedding Presents|publisher=[[Digital Spy]]|access-date=1 July 2021}}</ref> In 2012, as a result of the disaster caused by [[Hurricane Sandy]], she participated in a special organized by [[National Broadcasting Company]] (NBC), where she performed the song "[[Beautiful (Christina Aguilera song)|Beautiful]]" (2002) and asked for donations to the [[American Red Cross]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/music-news/hurricane-sandy-coming-together-concert-christina-aguilera-bruce-springsteen-to-474372/|title='Hurricane Sandy: Coming Together' Concert: Christina Aguilera, Bruce Springsteen to Perform|date=November 2012|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=January 21, 2022}}</ref> In response to the [[2010 Haiti earthquake]], she auctioned off a [[Chrysler 300]] and used the money raised to help disaster victims.<ref>{{cite web|language=Portuguese|url=http://g1.globo.com/Noticias/Carros/0,,MUL1455619-9658,00-CHRYSLER+IRA+LEILOAR+UNIDADE+DO+SEDA+C+PARA+AJUDAR+VITIMAS+DO+HAITI.html|title=Chrysler irá leiloar unidades do sedã 300C para ajudar vítimas do Haiti|publisher=[[Globo.com]]|access-date=1 July 2021}}</ref> She additionally appeared on the ''[[Hope for Haiti Now]]'' telethon, where donations directly benefited [[Oxfam|Oxfam America]], [[Partners In Health]], [[International Red Cross and Red Crescent Movement|Red Cross]], and [[UNICEF]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Alan Duke|date=24 January 2010|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2010/SHOWBIZ/TV/01/23/haiti.telethon/index.html|title='Hope for Haiti' Raises $58 Million and Counting|publisher=[[CNN]]|access-date=1 July 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Dave Karger|date=22 January 2010|url=https://ew.com/article/2010/01/22/hope-for-haiti-now-the-telethons-10-best-performances/|title='Hope for Haiti Now': The Telehon's 10 Best Performances|publisher=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|access-date=1 July 2021}}</ref> In 2009, she became the global spokesperson for the [[World Food Program]], a branch of the [[United Nations]] (UN).<ref>{{cite web|author=Anthony Bruno|date=25 July 2009|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=54RrDyfz10MC&pg=PT6|title=Aguilera Onborad with Hunger Relief|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=1 July 2021}}</ref> Through the program, she traveled to several countries with high rates of malnutrition, such as [[Guatemala]], [[Ecuador]], and [[Rwanda]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Gary Trust|date=30 September 2015|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/music-news/christina-aguilera-ecuador-hunger-relief-trip-6714543/|title=Christina Aguilera Returns to Her Roots on Ecuador Hunger Relief Trip|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=January 22, 2022}}</ref> Since then, it is estimated that she has helped raise more than $148 million for the organization and other hunger relief agencies in 45 countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wfp.org/christina-aguilera|title=Christina Aguilera - A Voice for the Hungry|publisher=[[World Food Program]]|access-date=1 July 2021|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131207041759/http://www.wfp.org/christina-aguilera|archive-date=7 December 2013}}</ref> In 2012, her role in the project earned her the [[World Hunger Relief#History|George McGovern Leadership Award]], which she received in the [[White House]] from former [[United States Secretary of State|Secretary of State]], [[Hillary Clinton]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Sugey Palomares|date=4 October 2012|url=http://www.latina.com/entertainment/hillary-clinton-christina-aguilera-world-hunger-mission|title=Hillary Clinton Honors Christina Aguilera for World Hunger Mission|publisher=[[Latina (magazine)|Latina]]|access-date=1 July 2021|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121009061642/http://www.latina.com/entertainment/hillary-clinton-christina-aguilera-world-hunger-mission|archive-date=9 October 2012}}</ref>

In 2016, Aguilera donated proceeds of her single "[[Change (Christina Aguilera song)|Change]]" to the victims and families of the [[Orlando nightclub shooting]].<ref name="OrlandoCA1">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-36557610|title=Christina Aguilera donates song profits to Orlando victims|work=BBC News|date=June 17, 2016|access-date=August 7, 2021}}</ref> Aguilera noted that, "Like so many, I want to help be part of the change this world needs to make it a beautiful, inclusive place where humanity can love each other freely and passionately".<ref name="OrlandoCA1"/>

